No Comments

Very boring lecturer. Lecture material not very useful to labs or tests. Homework and labs were tough, especially the coding in labs. Not a grade killer though
Easy class, show up and fall asleep. If you have a brain in your head you will pass.

He's not the most respectful when you're confused on the material.

comment_Rating: He does a very good job providing an overview of the different parts of electrical engineering, which is helpful as an introduction to the major. comment_Rating: Boring.

Tormey is sooooo hot.  I really want to have his babies.  I wish this guy would come back to ND.  But I do not know where he went.  Mike come back!  For both our sake.

nice guy. lots of readings. cheap textbook.

comment_Rating: O'Brien is THE MAN.  He cares about his students and has a great sense of humor.  We start class with a prayer every class and I got to like that.  O'Brien learns every student's name and where they are from and often learns about their families.  He gave me a ride to the airport once when my car wouldn't start and he saw me in the parking lot!
Great dude. Take his class.

Professor O'Brien is quite engaging and uses a lot of real world examples to help students learn.  He learns every student's name and honestly cares for each student.  His exams are tough but if you come to class and pay attention you will learn what you need to learn.  I recommend O'Brien for his other classes too - he also teaches tax.

Professor O’Brien, is hands down the best professor to teach Business Law to a freshman! Since it is about law there is a lot of reading and memorization down the line, but he makes the class interesting, and gives out funny but clear examples for cases. Personally, if he had a class at night, I would take it!

O’Brien starts class with a prayer - nice touch. He loves Notre Dame and it shows. And he is not only apart as hell but cares that students learn from class. He will email or call you if you miss class to make sure you are ok and you will feel bad and not skip again!

Professor O'Brien is wonderful. Very responsive and cares deeply for his students. Every class starts in prayer, and he's willing to answer questions until you understand the material. I would take his class again 100 times over.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: Professor O'Brien is a very good man. He starts class with a prayer (I thought it was corny at first but am glad we did that every class). O'Brien learns everyones name and calls on a lot of people. He wants you to learn and he will make sure you come to class and learn. I missed a class and he emailed me to ask if I was sick. He ROCKS!!!!

O'Brien is a good professor. He makes lots of jokes to make class more enjoyable. There are around 7 "pop quizzes", but he normally gives a warning the class before. O'Brien is very knowledgable and passionate about law, and it is clear he wants to share this passion with his students. His tests are pretty fair and on the easier side.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Beware of pop quizzes--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Amazing professor.  Learns all the students' names and really wants to help you learn.  He is the best professor I have ever had.  He has great jokes and will take as much time as necessary to explain issues to you.  TAKE HIS CLASS.
He's awesome

Amazing professor, amazing human being. Reason for me to continue being a student here at Notre Dame.
He's just great. The best part is his lecture style; he teaches you while telling a story.  You feel like you're a dinner guest instead of at a lecture.  Just wish I could take him again and again.

He's a Grad student; taught Intro to Philo. Fun teacher; really down to earth and pretty flexible when it comes to assignments.  That said, he doesn't assign much to begin with. Four-question quizzes on readings, a few short papers, and two exams.  Makes a pretty tricky subject interesting, and you can tell he really loves the material.
hard grader, but awesome TA, he really cares about this stuff!

Took stats. SO EASY if you've taken any intro stats class before (I took AP in highschool). He really wanted to make sure everyone understood. He also tries to engage class but sometimes class isn't very receptive at 830 in the morning. Nice guy. I did very well.
Super helpful teacher. Always available for meetings. He reminds me of an absent minded professor. You can tell he really loves math.

BEST professor at the law school. Holds student's to high expectations and if you give him respect he will give it back. Destroys people who don't read closely and goes off if you're late. Great at explaining material and teaching how to attack real world and exam problems. Extremely helpful in office hours. Integrates real world concepts.
Fighting for justice.
A bit scatterbrained, but clearly knows what he talking about! He is easy to get in touch with and will take the time to sit down and explain material to you. 10/10 would take a class with him again.

Dr. Ferdig is VERY passionate about the material he teaches and that makes class a lot more fun. He is a bit disorganized, but asking for clarification and scheduling office hours does wonders. 10/10 guy
Great teacher.  A little scattered, but communicates very well.

TAKE HIM...great guy...super easy grader...loves to laugh
Father Coughlin is amazing, funny, a little scary at first, but genuinely cares about all his students.

Absolute worst professor I've ever come across, its clear he doesn't care about his students assigns atleast 70 pages of readings and at least 3 hours of viewings for each class, the stuff he talks about in class also makes no sense and is so unhelpful for the assignments.  The course seemed really interesting and has potential but isnt done right.

Professor Khan is a really great teacher. I had him for Topology, and he made the subject quite approachable. I wouldn't say he is the greatest professor of all time ,but he is very personable and willing to help if you ask.

You will not find a better professor of rhetoric at a university. I don't know where the above comment is coming from at all--must not have ever talked to him before. If you show any willingness to work, this man will teach you how to argue well, which, as he says, is to argue responsibly.
He never explains assignments and likes to go on rants. He's also really high on himself. But when you do actually turn things in for a grade, he grades fairly.
Great prof! Panel system.

Class was fun,  Garnett is very entertaining and she makes the material seem easy in class. However it turns out she is actually just blowing off all of the hard things. The exam is totally killer, hardest one I've ever taken in my life. Friends who had other professors learned WAY more than our class and had a better understanding of the material.
I hate music theory.  I love Professor Johnson's classes.
Does not explain thing very clearly, does not explain the process, just does it. Not very approachable.
Awesome teacher, don't have to go to class and extremely nice/approachable. Take the class over Mcgavaro if you can!

Prof. Prizant is a beautiful, wonderful person. Easily one of my favorite people at Notre Dame, if not the world. She's a fabulous role model for women because of her strength, confidence, and beauty. It may seem like she's a bit of a feminist sometimes, but it just makes you have that much more respect for her. Funny and interesting, too.

She's the best. She's really patient and I go to her office hours all the time. She's even available outside her office hours like every day all day. She never turns me away, and I see people meeting with her all the time. She's definitely helpful and nice and people obviously feel comfortable going to her with questions.
She's a terrible teacher. Rude, doesn't accept feedback well, and her tests don't match what she teaches.
Group work, no lectures. If she does have a power point there are so many typos it's not worth it.

Prof Flenner is good at explaining the material, but some of the concepts themselves are just difficult to understand. He is very accessible outside of class for extra help and gives partial credit on quizzes and exams. There is a homework and quiz each week. 2 section exams and 1 cumulative final.
"Here's another fact...well, it's not much of a fact. It's more like an antifact..."
One of ND's finest professors. He's amazing - if poetry were written about dirty socks that man could find a deep meaning behind it. Not to mention hearing him read Italian...swoon.
Christian is amazing! Take his classes, they will change your life!
She's awesome. She tells you exactly what you need to do to succeed. I wish I could take her class again.
Good-nature, super itelligent but hard to follow at times.
This professor helped me get a job after graduation and prepared me to keep it.
He's the best prof
Garrett is the best professor ever, and he is SO dreamy. He's so talented and helpful!

Andy is a great director and teacher for Liturgical Choir. I really can't imagine it with someone else. I am about to graduate in a few months at the end of my 5th year (dual-degree program) and I took this as a course for credit my Freshman year and then have stayed in the choir since. Definitely one of my most meaningful experiences at Notre Dame
Super helpful!  Presents clearly with great examples from when he worked as an accountant.
never saw poorer teaching
He only talk about his own research
you will regret if choose his class.
This professor is absolutely atrocious. Completely full of himself and absolutely painful to listen to.

comment_Rating: He is pretty funny, and very good at explaining the material.

Coach Gaal is seriously such a great person. I had her for Contemporary Topics. I've talked to her a bit outside of class and she's so down to earth and incredibly selfless. I could not recommend her highly enough!
He was a TERRIBLE professor. Lectures were dry and boring. The tests were unfair. DONT TAKE HIS CLASS. fair warning.
Wasn't really sympathetic. I didn't understand the way he graded. Lectures were tangential and Eurocentric (even in World Cinema). He seemed like he had good intentions...
All around great professor in a department that is really struggling right now. Had him for American Television History, he was really funny and was always open to people's points of view.

In Prof. Snapper's office hour, he teaches each student in a tailored way. If you struggle with your overall schedule and think it is fairly hard for you to keep your workload, you can come to his office and talk to him, for he is willing to help you improve time management and give some extensions if you really need.

Professor Snapper is the best professor I've had at Calvin. He cares about what he teaches and for his students. The class itself can be a little difficult (but that's just philosophy in itself) but he makes it easy to understand and interesting to learn. I'm considering minoring in philosophy because of this prof!!!

One of, if not the best Prof I have had. He spends hours outside of his lectures, even on weekends doing review sessions with his students. He responds to questions with informative emails. Prof. Snapper made intro to philosophy so interesting and engaging that I decided to add a minor in philosophy because of him. Took him in logic

Loved this class, professor Snapper is a hard grader and expects a lot, but is willing to work with his students. He is caring and in general a great person to get to know. Don't be afraid to ask questions or go see him for help!
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Snapper is a good guy, but his class seems to go off the rails a bit. I personally did not struggle but heard stories of tutors having no idea what he was teaching. I enjoyed the class and the discussion. Snapper is a good guy but picks favorites a bit. His exams are difficult but study the main arguments and you will be fine.

Best professor I have ever had. His lectures are so interesting and immersive. Lots of homework but its enjoyable. Never taken any philosophy classes before him but he made it awesome.. Really down to earth and overall a great guy.

Jeff Snapper is one of the best professors I've ever had. He makes intro philosophy fun and is always energetic about the material. He gives great examples of concepts and is willing to do whatever he can to help students understand the material. He is so caring and genuine. He really likes participation, so speak up in class!

I generally liked the professor. Surprisingly,  the lectures were somewhat fun. I would often stay after class to understand the ideas and philosophy in greater detail, sometimes pointing out alternatives or possible issues. He grades quizzes (over the readings) fairly, but be careful writing your papers. I'd recommend asking plenty of questions.

Jeff is easily one of the most down-to-earth professors out there. He's committed to helping everyone understand the material, and he does it in fun, hands-on ways. There's definitely a lot of reading for the class, but it's worth it because you learn a lot! Overall amazing professor.
He's a really nice guy; he'll go out of his way to ensure that you understand the material. He's also extremely helpful when it comes to writing papers.
Todd Adkins was a very good teacher. Always prepared and on time. Lectures were interesting and loaded with information.  Todd also has some great skills for test taking as well.

Adkins was extremely knowledgable about the topic of the class (American Politics).  He made our discussion classes really interesting and was always open to answering any of our questions inside and outside of class.  He went out of his way to help us understand the material.  One of best TAs I've ever had!

He was great at leading discussion and was always willing to answer any of our questions.  He was available outside of class for any help we needed in understanding the material.  Over all, one of the best TAs I have had so far in my college career.

Adkins did a great job relaying what he has learned in the actual governmental fields we covered. Driven by text book analysis and personal experience, Adkins added a new level to teaching. He didn't act like a cocky professor. He understands how to have day to day relationships with students and people. He is understanding and easy to talk to.

Todd Adkins is legendary. Not only does he have real experience in the field, but he's brilliant as well. I was in his discussion section for American Government, and there was never a dull moment. His questions are surprising, thought-provoking, and constructive and he has never once lacked an answer for our own questions.
The discussions were very interesting and engaging, and his experience in politics made his insight valuable.
Great instructor all the way around.  One of the best I've had here at Notre Dame.

Professor Adkins was great!  He made discussion sections a blast and was very thorough and helpful.  He was always available to help when needed. His experience in real politics made the class much more interesting.
Nice guy. Funny. He really went out of his way to help me when I took the class, so I'm biased. However, he'll go out of his way and not make you feel weird--as long as you do the work.
Good guy. obviously loves teaching. Doesnt use the text that much tho. Very funny and fun lectures and makes things clear. makes sure everyone understands before moving on.
So super friendly and good at explaining ... im gonna miss mr. J. next semester.
Very funny and is always willing to help.  You can tell he loves teaching.

Should lose lots of weight before teaching about fitness/health.

Candida is just not pleasant. There's just something about her that gives off a bad vibe. Her teaching is okay but didn't really help when it came to outside of class. I recommend trying to get a different professor if you can.
Candida is so smart and knows everything about the Bible. She is hilarious, British, and smoking hot.
Amazing professor - she told us about her fieldwork frequently and was genuinely interested in what students thought during lectures. I would take this class again!!!
She's a very knowledgeable professor but more importantly, she actually practices her field. Its an honor to be in her classroom.

Having never taken a class with Prof K I was a bit uneasy. However once classes started I felt so welcome and never wanted to miss a single minute of his class. Prof K is one of the most interesting intellectuals I have ever met at ND or any other school.His breadth of knowledge is only surpassed by his caring attitude towards his students success.

Undoubtedly one of the finest, kindness, most compassionate human beings God ever placed on the face of the earth. Dr. K not only taught me CIS/PHOTOSHOP he taught me patience, understanding, and self confidence. Dr. K is one of the best Prof's that UND students will ever have had the opportunity with which to study. Dr. K is the best ever.

Prof K is not only 1 of the best prof's at ND but also one of the kindest, considerate and caring human beings ever. He provides his home phone # and tells students they may call him 24/7 should they ever require his assistance even once the course is complete. Prof K  should be the standard by which all Prof's are judged.

Prof K is the best prof I have had at ND. He is patient, understanding, with knowledge beyond belief. One of the few Prof's that genuinely cares about his students. He assisted me on many occasions and even drove from Chicago on his days off to assist his students. He was the most exceptional Prof at Notre Dame. Sadly he retired; a big loss for ND.

I did'nt fully realize either the depth or breadth of Prof. Kadlubowski's knowledge on this very difficult subject matter until my graduation from UND. Aside of his knowledge, PROF K. would meet any studnet at any time of day or night to assist in their understading of a particular lesson. The subject matter wasdifficult, but hemade class time fun

When God brought Michael to Notre Dame we were sent an angel. EXCEPTIONAL PROF with knowledge beyond compare. Assistance provided to students is unmatched even at the Golden Dome. Helpful regardless of the simplicity of complexity of the question asked. I was saddend to learn that Michael retired from UND. He was/is the best there ever was!
Best algorithm class ever
he is one of the great teacher!
Master Yoda of the CSE Dept.

comment_Rating: Very good professor, explains concepts pretty well

Father Streit's class is as confusing as it is boring. Although his grading criteria isn't difficult, it is extremely confusing and convoluted. If you're looking for a topical science credit, I would highly suggest taking another one.
Best teacher ever.
I wish I could have her for Moreau again.

The material is difficult, but he makes it much easier to understand. There's homework due every lecture, but it's definitely manageable, and the exams are straightforward. He's a really great person, and he won't let you fail if you've put in the effort.
Good professor. Would take again.
Wonderful teacher - speaks a bit fast and rambles but besides that is very helpful and very easy to follow in terms of taking notes. Very nice guy in general. Would take his class again.
Take his course! An incredible, inspirational man and a great prof.
Great Class! a must in ND Law School

Thomas and learned so much in her class. Expect to be taught by a professor who is passionate and well-versed in the subject of the course. Highest praise for her.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Such a nice prof who really cares about all of her students. She's passionate about her work and it shows. She does want you to conform to her favored writing and conduct styles, but if you do that and make a genuine effort to connect to the material, you will succeed. Probably the best personal connection I've made with a teacher. Recommended!
Cares ddeply about students; good lectures; challenging and interesting!
He is a great professor.
Best PE teacher, he is a very cool dude
Amazing and brilliant prof - one of the best at Notre Dame full stop.

Professor Martin is an excellent teacher. She is kind, caring, and extremely personable. Her class was interesting and thought-provoking. You could tell she genuinely cared for all of her students and was very passionate about her work. Cannot recommend her enough!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Inspirational--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: prof martin is one of the best! this class is participation based with lots of readings but trust me its all worth it. shes a phenomenal writer and genuinely cares about her students. would recommend her class to anyone.

Really sweet & Inspiring professor. Genuinely cares about her students. Definitely a reading/writing intensive course, but she helps students break it down to size. She's incredibly intelligent and makes students feel at east. She's never judgmental or makes students feel awkward about their point of view. Her class encourages growth!

Recommend for non-humanities majors. I didn't expect the best class I took at Notre Dame to be a required core course, last semester of senior year. I have zero interest in religion and picked the class for the time slot. Romero combines theory with practical stories, which I liked. I wish he had returned our exams more quickly. Nice guy.

Dr. Romero's Theology and Disability course is a good class: highly recommended. I signed up for the class as my second theology requirement because it looked interesting. He made we want to change my minor to theology. The class was a little harder than I expected, but it was worth it. He only had us buy two novels and everything else was PDF.
Awesome class! Awesome person who cares!

The only thing I can say about the disaster that was an International Business Transaction, is that I got a better grade because I had the right font size and did not forget to double space. Emailing an entire class during finals week 2 days after we've taken an exam with pointless exam tips for different classes is not cool
Not very well organized. Exam questions are very confusing and, convoluted. Her communication style is not helpful to the subject matter.
Not very well organized. Her exam was very confusing.

I took his young adult novel course and loved it! In addition to being a fun class with fun readings, we also had very good discussions of important topical issues. Felt like the work load was reasonable and he had fair expectations for papers

Took his Young Adult fiction class and LOVED IT! The class had a really fun and up-to-date reading list of YA novels. We had such good discussions and I was truly excited to write my final paper for the class, which has never happened to me before.
Take his class! Was amazing!
I took this class spring of 2013 and it is easily one of the best classes I have taken at Notre Dame in my two years here.
Such a good course. I would highly encourage anyone to take WR with him if you can. Great class discussions, and we watched fun movies too.
Truly an excellent teacher. Take his class if you can!
His assignments are sometimes challenging and very time consuming but overall I really learned a lot in this class. He is fun and very helpful. Visit him during office hours, it helps!
This class helped me so much as a writer and thinker. I am so grateful for having taken this course - it was also really fun and had great discussions!

Sets unrealistically high standards for engaging with the material to succeed (focus questions, must reread, pop quizzes). Exams are doable but he tells you nothing about how they'll be formatted. Papers are long and scheduled so that the brunt of writing must happen over breaks. Great guy & really cares about the content, but I wouldn't recommend.
Professor Newlands really values helping his students learn and seeing them grow.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: I am currently taking Dan's Composition 101 class at Holy Cross. He is very friendly and you can tell he really enjoys literature and his job. His icebreakers are my favorite and I think of a clever answer days prior to class. Dan often talks about superman and I suspect he knows that he looks exactly like a young Christopher Reeve. He's wonderful.

I loved his media and lit class. Dan is so funny and enthusiastic. I thought the course would be more about journalism, news, and media bias instead of a seminar on lit, movies, and pop culture, but it was really fun! I will never look at movies the same way. Also, he might actually be Indiana Jones.

Dan's class was my favorite course at ND my first year. I always struggled in english classes and I don't particularly like writing essays, but the class was fun and it helped me a lot with college writing . Dan is funny and chill, and we covered a lot of cool contemporary things in pop-culture from an academic viewpoint.

Dan is a great teacher. Very enthusiastic about the material and super encouraging. He is funny and SO goodlooking too. I am a much better reader and critical thinker after his course. Never will watch movies the same way again!

I am really enjoying the class. It has honestly been a lot of fun! The ice-breakers in particular are so funny and over-the-top. Dan is hilarious and has a laid back teaching style, which is conducive to good class discussions because he mixes serious high level discussion with humor and weird references. He is also quite handsome. Like really.

Dans is really funny. In all, the course as a whole was laid back and fun. The icebreakers are great. The class is almost like a English/philosophy class, though, in case that’s not your thing. As someone else mentioned, he is not an easy grader at all.  And girls, he’s really cute ;) I would take the class again in a heartbeat.

Dan is a good teacher and I ended up liking his class a lot; he is young, relateable and funny. The atmosphere in class was always relaxed even though the material is heavy. A word of warning, Dan is a tough grader. I never got higher than a B on any of my essays, even though I tried hard and went to the Writing Center a lot for help.
Been a great class so far. Fun discussions and we watch lots of good new movies. Dan is sometimes a bit too abstract, but he is very approachable and open if you meet with him outside of class.
Down to earth and funny Professor. He is really excited about english and movies and has a laid back and enthusiastic demeanor. Very encouraging and patient. And srsly, hot.
So much reading! I hate everything about leadership now!

Awesome professor. Teaches in an  engaging and progressive fashion. Has a lot of knowledge to share. My only regret was taking this during the summer for one week and not getting the full experience. Highly recommend taking him.
Philosophy of religion with Dr Rettler is the best philosophy class I've taken at Baylor. He was very fair to both sides of all the issues, and he seemed like he had a lot of fun arguing with us.
He's super fun and very flexible. Class is discussion-based, and you get to pick a lot of the topics.

Make sure that you do everything according to the syllabus. Do not sit in the back of class. If he says something in the syllabus, he means it. Do not use a computer in this class. He will assume you are surfing the web. Go with his opinion on everything. The teacher is always right in this class. Show strong effort on papers and you will do well.

Discussions were really thought provoking and he did a good job of leading them, teaching the class how to argue and keeping it interesting. Also very helpful with everything. Not a big workload. Definitely take this class
He set up a great class and ran it well. Promoted good discussion and encouraged students to express their opinions in well formulated papers. Great 2nd philo. Highly suggested.
Definitely the best second philo you can take. The topic changes every week, and he does a great job of leading an interesting discussion.

It is a little difficult to understand what he wants at first as far as papers go, but if you go into his office hours and talk about it he makes it pretty straightforward.  Also what we do in class is pretty consistent with how our papers should be structured.

The most effective aspect of Dr. Rettler's teaching is his ability to stimulate, moderate, and guide discussion.  As a result, while I don't always leave a class with a new opinion on the topic being discussed, I always have a new way of looking at the issue. He's also really interested in his students opinions and considers them thoroughly.
I really enjoy this class.  There is not too much work, and the class discussions have really helped my form solid opinions on some issues that are relevant.  Professor is very helpful and fair.

He is an extremely good guy. Very accessible to students via email or office hours. He grades fairly and is careful to represent all sides of an argument. The class served its purpose as a philo course, which is to consistently challenge a student's beliefs about current moral issues and teach the proper way to construct and defend an argument.

This was a wonderful class. It definitely made me think about my opinions on hot-topic issues and be able to justify them. There's no textbook for this class, only online readings or videos. Workload is fairly light. Class discussions are in depth, and he does a great job of addressing all sides of an issue. 10/10 would take again.
Very insightful. Develops sound arguments and allows for class participation. Great professor for second philo. Good reviews on papers. Gives perfect amount of homework. Keeps class interested.

This class was great as a 2nd Philo. Only 5 or 6 short 1 page critical reports. Pretty simple, he makes it clear what he wants. One essay and hes very helpful if you go in office hours. Rettler is a great guy, super nice. He is open about his opinions but definitely NOT judgmental at all. Grading is very fair. He lets conversation flow organically.
He is very opinionated and very intolerant of others' opinions. Not helpful comments on papers and not clear. Marked down for having opinions other than his.
I love Professor West! The assignments are interesting and relevant. Class discussions are fun & he is always available when help is needed.

One of the easier USEM's compared to what I've heard. Three papers, she gives heavy feedback on all to improve. On the first one, she lets you resubmit an edited version with a lot of feedback/revisions. Essays are based on one book you read that's easy to understand and on her lectures. She's straightforward and is really enthusiastic/passionate.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Reading and writing intensive. Tough class but prof gives lots of feedback. She really cares about helping us.

I HATE writing but prof Jansen is AMAZNIG. We talked about music videos a lot and I literally wrote a paper on the Weeknd but he is not an easIy grader.. If u want a A or B be reayd to spend ALOT of time on revising ur papers.
Professor Jansen was a tough grader but his class was awesome! Take his class. There was a lot of work but he was very helpful.

This woman is one of the rudest and most condescending professors I have ever had. She teaches as if she is reading off of a script, which is the case for the majority of the time. She doesn't take questions during lectures, and she just seems like she would rather do anything else but teach.

This woman is one of the rudest and most condescending professors I have ever had. She teaches as if she is reading off of a script, which is the case for the majority of the time. She doesn't take questions during lectures, and she just seems like she would rather do anything else but teach. I pray for whoever will be taking her module next year.

I was very disappointed in this module.  The content is very evolution heavy and more philosophical than biological, the homework is a big time sink (1-2 hours per concept check), and the TA review sessions are the only source of my success.  I was not the biggest fan of Professor Hollocher; she can be moody, rude, and condescending to her TAs.

I took this module for intro bio and didn't enjoy it. Very uninteresting lectures that don't really get to the point. Very vague and unclear about content that you're supposed to know for the quizzes. Also sometimes rude when asked question

The TA does all of the grading, so go to his review sessions.

Professor Hollocher is kind of hit or miss. Some days she can be nice and easygoing, but more often than not she is slightly condescending. The concept checks take 1hr+ and the quizzes are not accurate assessments of material. Get ready to spend way too much time doing assignments and stressing over even little stuff.

Homework is absurdly long and worth little credit. Lectures were either reading off PowerPoint slides or discussing the homework questions. Quizzes were not reflective of the content learned. Population genetics was a great course and Hope made it so. She strongly encourages participation and will call you out if you are not. If you are going to take geographic information systems, it will be from Matt. Good thing he is awesome! His class was incredibly useful and well-organized. He is approachable and his dry humor is perfect.
Super accommodating, and always very gracious! Wonderful professor for creative writing and/or literature--gives great feedback on papers or manuscripts. 10/10 would take any class she taught.

One of my favorite professors at Notre Dame. An S-tier metaphysician. He's funny, gives interesting lectures, and only grades on three papers. He's also really smart and helpful. I would highly recommend you take his courses if given the chance.

very interesting class if you pay attention, but paying attention isn't all that necessary. comment_Rating: A pretty boring class. He had a tendency to ramble on. Grading was based on participation and 3, maybe 4, papers.

I was also in her first class, and thought it was great. Professor Hartland tries to make you think outside the box, and wanted us to push our creativity. For me, it was a nice change of pace. I also read a lot of stuff I never heard of, which was interesting. She definitely had an unconventional approach to teaching, but I really appreciated that.

I enjoyed the class, but that's because I loved the opportunity to explore poetry, with no real assignments or lesson plans. Patricia is a sweetheart, but she let the class walk all over her (not showing up, not doing work). All of her plans fell apart and it was a mess in general. The teacher is nice but give a decent amount of homework, she also accepts late work but deducts points off.

comment_Rating: Tim is knowledgeable and genuine. In his introductory course, he gives two essays and two tests. If you do the essays in advance, he can give you feedback before your final submissions, which is very helpful. Truthfully, in this class you get out what you put in. You can coast or you can engage with the readings and speak in class.

Professor Judy was amazing in my opinion. She was very understanding of students. If you were struggling or stressed, she was willing to extend deadlines as long as you came to her for help before the due date. She facilitated class discussion very well. Anytime you speak, she really listens and makes you feel heard. There are no dumb answers.

I really loved Professor Dinkelman. I think she understands that metrics is a hard class and everyone is just trying to get through it. She was pretty light on grading, I thought at least. I tried hard to understand the material but I don't think I really got there. It was pretty dull. Nevertheless, I would highly recommend her for metrics.

Dinkelman is amazing at explaining concepts, but there is some disconnect between the lectures and the homework. Dinkelman seems very passionate about the subject which helps make econometrics slightly better. Her class was structured different from other metrics classes that I've heard of in that she assigns a group paper.

comment_Rating: literally the kindest professor ever!

comment_Rating: Burns does not screw around when it comes to participation. She expects you to come to class having done the reading (which are almost always on a social or political issue) and prepared some kind of talking points or questions to share with the class, which means more work, but also some really fun discussions.

Burns was the best. Although we had papers (duh, it's a writing class), they are pass/fail at first, and only actually graded on how well you revise them all at the end of the year. She is very caring and kind to all of her students and really just a great professor and person.

Burns is really good at using student feedback about her class. She is a really good professor and it is my favorite class to go to all week. Not too much work and not too difficult of a class grade wise.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Though he is a graduate student, he has been my best calculus professor so far. He is very sweet and charming during lectures, while still explaining the concepts really well. He even told us when we did not have to pay attention to certain concepts. Calculus II is tough by itself, but he really helped out. He also replies to emails really fast.

Great professor who cares about her students. Had her for CFR. She is a good lecturer who does her best to explain complicated concepts in a crammed course. She was helpful outside of class and always willing to help students. Difficulty of the course is not a product of her teaching but rather the course itself. Do the work and you will do well.

This is a class from hell. She throws at you nearly every single problem created by the the textbook, then she proceeds to give you excels, judgement cases, and quizzes. The class is horrible she just gives meaningless worksheets before you even learn the material and noone even does them. Then she gives test questions, that are barely discussed.

Professor Watkins is great! She is always very clear when explaining and gives time to work through and go over practice problems in class. She is very caring and really cares about all of her students. Definitely recommend!!

Brian is a wonderful professor! He really cares about giving unique assignments and is always available outside of class. He gives great feedback too! There can be a lot of reading and some quizzes, but the information is good to know. Overall, great professor and a really fun course!

Great guy! Very funny and entertaining, very helpful both inside and outside the classroom. A few group projects but they're very straightforward. Everyone loves him and he makes sure everyone's engaged and understands. If you show up and pay attention, studying for tests is easy. Assignments are easy (took me less than an hour usually). Love him!

Philosophy as a concept is pretty challenging but if you show up and pay attention, you'll be fine. Participation is important so he learns your name. Lots of reading assigned but you can easily get by without doing it because his lectures summarize the readings. Online quizzes randomly assigned based on readings can be done with Sparknotes.

Professor Grillo is incredibly knowledgeable and passionate about Latin and will do his best to increase your knowledge of Latin. comment_Rating: This queen really is a real gem. She is subtly funny. The only thing is she talks really quickly, but she is willing to repeat herself many times if needed.

Pat is probably the best math professor I've ever had. For brief periods of time, his explanations of concepts could make me understand why someone would want to be a math major. In a course with some seriously tough material, he did a great job of helping us all to understand well enough to succeed. His office hours are great, too.

Prof. Heslin brought an unexpected amount of positive energy to calculus 1. His explainations were clear and accurate. Having taken the class before in high school, I thought I didn't have much to learn. But Heslin eaily provided new, often easier ways to think about things. Very clear and often makes good jokes.

Bright guy, very helpful and understanding. When you have an issue he is extremely reasonable. Brings energy to the classroom, makes some good jokes and does a great job teaching the content of the course. He really understands how to meet each student at the level they are at and teach them from there.

Mitch is a great, caring guy who genuinely loves marketing, and it shows. His class was pretty boring, though, and, as much as I studied for the exams, memorization only got me half-way as they are all application-based (much to my demise). The participation grade seems a bit arbitrary to me. Not much homework, thankfully.

Lectures are awesome- he mixes in a lot of examples and is really entertaining himself. He's engaging, even with the 100+ people in my section. It can be hard to participate in the big class, though. Exams are challenging and have some math. You can pick your group project members, and it's a good way to apply the content you're learning.

One of the best professors I've ever had! His lectures are really engaging and makes learning the content enjoyable. He really cares about his students and learned everyone's names within 2 weeks in a 70+ person class. His exams are a little challenging, but definitely tolerable if you take good notes during class and study for them.

I really liked Professor Olsen as a guy--he's witty, wholesome, and kind. While a lot of my friends enjoyed the class, I personally did not like this class at all. It is SUPER subjective and you only get graded on a few things. The exams are super tough. It isn't memorization based, so if you want an easier marketing class, don't take Olsen.

A big chunk of his grading is extremely biased, participation accounts for 10% and he's not going to give you full credit in a 100+ student lecture hall. Getting good exam scores are easy in his class if you study, but if he doesn't like you he's gonna screw you over other grading portions that have nothing to do with the course content.

Marketing's boring but Olsen's the best you're gonna get. He's enthusiastic and goes over the slides well in class. The tests are mostly conceptual and tough, but the curve helps at the end. The group project is time-consuming so don't procrastinate until the last week if possible. Also, take the class with friends because you can pick your team.
Olsen super passionate about marketing, and it clearly shows in his teaching. I really enjoyed his class, and I didn't find it too difficult, though I did take it online over the summer.

Even though his grading was easier than most, he rather focus on the quality of the students' work. From the very beginning, you can tell that he's passionate about his craft. You can also tell that he wants to share his love for that with the students he interacts with. I would definitely recommend this class to other people.

Although Olsen is awkward, it's obvious he makes a genuine effort to connect to students & share his passion for marketing. Somewhat different than other intro classes, his class consists of a large ongoing group project, multiple difficult case studies, & some math-based assignments. There is no memorization on his tests, which makes them easier.

Amazing teacher who really cares about the class as a whole! Each individual matters to him and will do whatever he can to help each person understand. Definitely take this class if you want an overall great professor who doesnt make it easy but not hard. A professor that is fair in every way he teaches.

I had Dr. Squires at Notre Dame where he taught my Ethics course. Class was always so fun and such a great discussion. He makes Kant, Nietzsche, and Plato as accessible to students as reading the New York Times

Professor Squires was an excellent Professor who taught philosophy in a respectful, engaging, and relatable manner. He was challenging, yet forgiving. I learned so much in his class that it has inspired future endeavors in philosophy.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Great lecturer. Broke down complex topics into things that are more accessible. Super helpful outside of class. Great teacher overall. Do what is asked of you and you will get out of the class so much more.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Very chill professor who cares about you learning the material rather than focusing only on the grades. Really enjoyed my first philosophy class and highly recommend as a professor.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment_Rating: I took a philosophy class with Prof. Squires. He chose interesting, challenging primary texts for us to read. He did not tell us what to think or have us just memorize what the authors were saying. Instead, he helped us wrestle with the ideas themselves. I always left class with a lot to think about. He pushed us to think and to write clearly.

Prof. Squires is always available outside class and held office hours every weekday while I was taking his course. He is always willing to discuss just about any topic in Philosophy, and is very steadfast in his positions. He is extremely receptive to active students, and will give back to the students as much as they're willing to put in and more.

Professor Squires is brilliant, and he makes complicated topics easily understandable to non-majors in his field. He is an engaging lecturer, always available and interested to talk outside of class, and attentive to detail but not scrupulously harsh. It's evident he really cares about his students.

Professor Squires was very good at teaching this introductory philosophy class many of that basic logical structures of language and argumentation, in addition to having us read interesting texts from classical Greece to modern Europe. He's great to talk to outside of class as well. Super interesting, recommend him.

Professor Squires' class was focused around group discussion of materials read outside of class. In my opinion, most of my learning came from the discussion of these readings, not the readings themselves. Squires likes to add humor to class, and is always happy to meet to discuss class, or whatever else might be on your mind. Well worth taking.

Professor Squires is a great guy. He took what was some pretty esoteric subject matter and made it into a class that was consistently engaging and interesting. He gives excellent feedback and facilitated great discussion during class. I would recommend to any student looking to dive deeper into a philosophy class.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Squires is awesome. He made class super interesting and was very reasonable about the workload. Definitely take anything he teaches!

Squires gives great feedback! Any question will be answered with a thoughtful and thorough response. He provides excellent instruction and critique of papers. You can tell he goes to great lengths to make his classes intellectually stimulating and fun for students. Professor Squires was the best philo prof I have had. Certainly, recommend.

Professor Squires' Ancient Philosophy class was the first exposure I had to real, unfiltered philosophy, and even a year after finishing the course I find myself still considering those major topics we discussed. The course content was given in full and explained with great thoroughness; his challenges demanded serious philosophical engagement.

Amazing professor! Super smart and very approachable. He makes tough material easy to understand and organizes his class well. Talk to him after class! He is always willing to discuss philosophy with students. Even when sometimes you only have a limited understanding of a topic, he listens to you with respect. Workload and papers not bad at all.

Prof. Squires class was perhaps the most meaningful of my time at university. He built his ethics class around a few different texts, and though the reading was sometimes hard, it was all worth it for the high quality of in-class discussion that he cultivates. He conveys philosophical concepts accessibly, and quite honestly changed my life.

Prof. Squires is a professor with deep knowledge of philosophy and a great willingness to share it with others. Although the course was difficult content-wise (Aristotle is never easy to read), he always made himself available to help with any difficulties. He taught me a variety useful skills that have carried into other philosophy course.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Professor Seachris is one of the kindest profs I've had. His USEM gave us a good overview of core philosophical issues but didn't require rigorous homework/discussion. If you want a good but easy class that double counts for philo and a USEM, take him! However, if you're looking for more of an intellectual challenge, I would choose another course.
Great professor, really makes you think hard. Very interesting class, amazing guy, take him.
Amazing professor that really cares about his students. Class was full of interesting discussions. Readings were mostly modern philosophers, and pretty short / clear.

Prof. Seachris is a great choice. I had him my freshman year for my Philo USEM and it was relatively little work and also very interesting. There are weekly readings that are used in class and weekly take-home quizzes over the readings and class discussions but they are super easy if you do the readings. Two longer essays at the midterm and final.
Dr. Seachris is a captivating lecturer, empathetic teacher, and a good man. If you can, take his class.
Such a great professor who cares about philosophy and how his students are doing. A very kind person in general. Good material delivery.

Professor Sedmak is an incredible and brilliant individual. In class discussion, he provokes thoughtful discussion and doesn't let anyone get away with lackadaisical answers. His in-class activities are challenging and never have a clear black-and-white answer. He also lets you choose your own pathway to the grade which is awesome.
Exams are tough but not graded terribly hard. The projects and homeworks are very time consuming yet worthwhile.

Hard class, but his humor and dedication made it an exciting challenge rather than a slog. Attendance isn't mandatory, but might as well be since the lectures are crucial to understanding, and the textbook is only used as a source for homeworks.

A very difficult yet rewarding professor. He is very passionate about circuits and does a great job getting to know individual students. Although this was one of the hardest courses I took, his humor and support helped me through it. Also, the homework and weekly quizes make this more like a 3 credit course than a 2 credit.

Lectures are EXTREMELY boring, but make sure to write down everything he says. He will put the most random things on the exams, so this course is memorization heavy. That said, I would take it again because it is not difficult. Make sure to read the textbook because at least 5 questions from there will be on the exam. Homeworks are free 100s.

He may be extremely boring, but if you get to know him he's so quirky and funny. His class was so easy, he literally gives a 100% on every homework assignment, and the tests are not bad if you take good notes.

Exams are the only grade, based on a combination of lectures and assigned reading. Readings and lectures sometimes diverge, usually based on the same things though, but you need to know both. Seems like he cares about his students but it doesn't translate into quality teaching. Really bad at answering questions and doesn't keep up with schedule.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Lousy professor. Puts no preparation into class.

I'm an ME who took his CE Fluid Mechanics. He is clear and to-the-point, and really simplifies complex topics. Hw: 4-7 textbook problems each week, and it never took me more than 3 hours to finish. You'll feel like you're in high school again! Not saying it's an easy class, but seemingly much-easier than the other alternative we had.
Awful professor, class was a mess.
Professor Hui is a great professor, but you have to do a lot of work for the class. If you do the work, she will make sure that you get an A in the course

She only speaks in Chinese the whole class, which would be helpful if we knew what she was saying, but it is tough when she uses phrases we don't know to explain the meaning of another that we don't know. You have to figure out how to avoid her asking you questions so you have time to figure out what is going on in class.

Took him for foundations of strategy. Super smart guy with a lot of industry knowledge. partially my fault, but never did any reading (assigned random 40 page pdfs before every class), and had to study a lot for the final because didn't retain much during the course. large part of your grade is online simulation of a business that you runwithagroup
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Group projects

comment_Rating: I really enjoyed Michel's class. I had him for both Strategic Management and Foresight. Most of the time, the assigned readings and case studies were relevant and interesting. He also does a really good job of connecting with students and making them comfortable to share ideas in class. He also has a few dad jokes that kept everyone entertained.
I love Professor Hall as his lectures are humorous and well organized. He offers reasoning for every concept covered, which was super helpful for me to understand.
The best math teacher I have had in my time at ND, will be taking more of his classes in the future

Ochem is notoriously tough, but Melander made it ten times harder. Very unorganized notes; I ended up going to Jim Parise's lectures even though I was not enrolled in his course. Take anyone else for orgo 1 if you can (besides maybe Helquist). This class is hard enough, and so a good teacher can make or break it. He unfortunately was not good.
