comment_Rating: Professor Kang is a wonderful instructor. I took her Elementary Korean class and I have made so much progress. The workload is manageable, the assignments are always relevant, and she is a very kind, funny, and sweet person. She encourages students to learn in various ways.

Professor Kang is a very kind woman and is genuinely trying to help her students learn Korean. She just wants more people to appreciate her language and culture and is very caring in class and outside of it because of that. I wish more students would take Korean because it's not super hard to learn. The Korean professors are all so helpful.
Great guy. Cultivated a welcoming environment.
Great teacher - highly recommend
Unrealistic teachings, can't be applied to real life
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--So many papers--Respected

comment_Rating: This professor has a very specific way he thinks about things, and he expects everyone to think along the same lines as he does. He often tries to explain concepts in roundabout and convoluted ways, leaving the entire class confused. Then when students ask him to explain it differently, he just refuses and criticizes us for not thinking like him.

Prof. Betson is fine in class, just gives long rambling lectures that don't seem to matter very much. The exams are always super confusingly worded, so the class avgs are low, but the curve is pretty good. However, an A in his class is 95-100, so I'd say expect an A- unless you put a lot of work in.

One of my favorite professors that I have had so far at Notre Dame. Professor McKenny cares a lot about his students and does a great job of making them think and consider issues in a new light. There is a bit of reading and a few 4-5 page papers, but as a whole, his class was my favorite of the semester.

Hands down one of my favorite teachers at Notre Dame. You have reading assignments for each class which isn't bad. You are given 10 short answer questions on a study guide and there 3 of the questions are your quiz. (5 quizzes overall) There are also 4 (5-7 page) papers. Amazing teacher! He cares about the students, so participating helps.

Professor DeLorenzo is a great teacher for foundations of theology. His lectures are amazing, and I learned a lot through his class. There is not much work besides a test and a decent amount of projects/long writing assignments. His course is not an easy A, but I would still recommend taking it as he offers a thorough understanding of theology.

I took his class for ND Vision (a theological based summer camp at ND where ND students mentor high schoolers) and he was one of the best teachers I've ever had. He grades exactly how you deserve, his lectures are inspirational, and as long as you pay attention and take notes, the midterm and final will be (deservingly) easier than most!

Charismatic and engaging lecturer, and wants to make the class enjoyable for his students. Series of readings and short responses, plus midterm and a final. Tough grader so not a guaranteed A, but definitely a possible one. The theme of the class seemed a little all over the place at times, but you leave the course well-read and knowledgeable.

An engaging and highly skilled lecturer. He really makes the most of your time by packing a lot of information into lectures and keeping the reading to the essentials, and so the class is easier than those of some of the other great Theo faculty while still helping you learn a lot. Definitely don't take Foundations with a random grad student.

I took this class to fulfill a theo requirement, so I wasn't particularly interested in the material. That being said, the class was definitely manageable. There is a lot of reading to prepare for class discussion, but it is fairly easy to do well in class and on papers if you take good notes. Overall a great intro theology class.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: The professor has an incredibly difficult course that is neither helpful nor supportive. It is not for the faint of heart and I would highly recommend against it.

Incredibly intelligent and thought-provoking, and wants to help students learn how to think. Very accessible outside of class, and excellent at encouraging students to share their thoughts and at listening to their views. If you're looking to do no work, he's not the right professor; if you're looking to learn, you couldn't ask for better.

The class itself was easy but there were constant things that were unclear. She never seemed to know what would be on the exams and didn't organize the class in a way that made it easy to be successful. The homework assignments sometimes had difficult calculations that we didn't go over in class which was pretty frustrating.

Earth Focus: She is a super nice lady and definitely overqualified to be teaching earth focus. The class was relatively easy and focused more on concepts around climate change than actual science or math relating to it, she had a really hard time communicating with students about assignments, we never really knew what was going to be on exams.

Earth Focus was a very easy course, but the assignments and lectures get very boring and repetitive. She teaches some very insightful things on the science of climate change. She is extremely overqualified to teach the class as a nuclear physicist. There is a disconnect between her and students as science majors cannot take the class.

Islamic Law and International Relations is a freshman USEM I highly recommend. Professor Powell does a great job teaching a very nuanced topic. If you read the book and come to class prepared to talk, you will get an A. Professor was very respectful.
Ghada is a very kind and understanding professor. As long as you participate and show effort, you can end with an A.

Professor Bualuan truly loves her students and is dedicated to helping them learn Arabic. If you struggle, she'll help. She makes learning this immensely difficult language so easy and honestly fun. Highly recommend.

Professor Stolz genuinely cares for his students. He posts his notes and lectures to a Google Drive, so they're easily acceptable. As someone who didn't take Calculus in high school, I had to put in extra effort to understand the material, and although Stolz may not be the *absolute* best professor, he provides you with the resources to succeed.
stolz is great, he almost entirely uses examples to teach which makes it a lot more applicable to the exams/quizzes. Calc B is hard no matter what, stolz is good

Honestly he is the sweetest guy ever but his style of teaching is just so all over the place. He never goes into concepts and will straight up just dive into examples without telling the class what exactly we are doing. Be prepared to be teaching yourself a lot of the content outside of class.

Physics Two for Life Sciences is a hard course, especially if you have never taken physics. Out of the teachers that taught this course at ND, he was by far the best lecturer and was the funniest and nicest. This is a hard course and you will have to study and prepare out of class, but he was an amazing teacher that I would recommend taking.

The class child and adolescent psychopathology was an interesting class but a little boring at times, just lectures with powerpoints. Professor Miller-Graff is one of my favorite professors I've had. She's such a nice person and you can tell she really cares about what she's teaching. Great, interesting professor!
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Caring

comment_Rating: Great lectures, really enjoyed Professor Del Valle's class for Orgo 1. Great guy, made material simpler than the textbook, and office hours were really helpful. Definitely recommend reading the book before lecture and going to office hours when material is confusing, you will save a lot of time. Class material is brutal, but great professor.

Overall good professor but often, some things that end up on the exam are sentences she only says once very quickly and they're easy to miss. You need to be writing down nearly everything she says. If you have an average writing speed like me, recording the lectures is essential in doing well in her exams.

Took her NSBH40300 course and this was the most entertaining class i have ever taken. She does give GREAT feedback on all of the assignments. Read her comments and improve over course. It is simple to pass if you adapt in her class.
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Ok hear me out on the rating. She is a good Prof. and lecturer - lectures are straightforward and exams match that and the reading. Now, she could be a questionable person in kindness. She deliberately scheduled all the neuro exams during orgo. If anyone asked if she moved them, she would get upset. You have to take her, not that bad but painful.

Sunny Boyd is my favorite professor ever. Just watching her teach makes my day. She loves frogs and she gave us bagels. You have to take her class as a neuroscience major, so you don't have a choice but that's good because she is the best.

-Disorganized class
-Interesting material
-Not difficult but lots of reading and typing
-Unclear grading criteria on hwk
-interesting readings and videos
-good elective for the entrepreneurship minor

Hurst's class is not hard at all, but she is a tough grader and difficult to please for your assignments/submissions. She's not afraid to give out bad grades if she doesn't receive what she wants. The class was easy and interesting itself but difficult to get an A in.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Group projects--Tough grader

comment_Rating: I enjoyed Professor Himelright's class. I really liked the way his lectures were structured and that he provided the PowerPoints for each class. I took Moral Problems with him, and most of the readings were interesting, relevant, and understandable. There are only three four-page papers, and they just asked to summarize one of the readings.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Specht is an amazing professor. He makes lectures very interesting and relevant to real life. The class is not too much work and the work there is is interesting. He makes assignment creative and fun. I would strongly recommend him and his classes.

Professor Rowland is great. A real Italian woman who knows everything about Rome that you could ever imagine. She is very caring for her students and is more than willing to help on any paper or research. She is also a great mentor and a person who can help you along the way on your college iist

This Theo class is the most work intensive class that I have taken at ND. You get long long readings every class which you must respond to in the form of reader reflections. These are due every class. I can not stress enough the amount of work this is. He is a swell guy, who gives very solid lectures but the workload is incomprehensible. Be ready!
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: What he writes on board is just exactly copied from the textbook. Don't think he truly understands what he is teaching. Can't answer student questions.
Class lacks substance. Monotonous. No guidance. He roughly edits papers but does not explain what is wrong/ how to fix it. Whole class based on one paper.

Prof Barber is a highly respected scholar in constitutional studies. His lectures are incredibly interesting, but your attendance has little bearing on class grade. Your grade is solely based on a midterm and final exam.

I took his On the Road university seminar and loved it. There are reading or film assignments for each class, but they are always manageable. Discussion is fascinating. Grade is based on 4 main papers of varying length, always got great feedback on the papers. Did not get deductions for small errors, very encouraging and accessible.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: I cannot say enough good things about Professor Wu. She is incredibly organized and clear in her expectations. She is a great lecturer and does a phenomenal job of explaining complex economic concepts. If you pay attention to her lectures, you will learn a lot and do well. Very approachable, but does not really try to get to know students.

Professor Bordogna was very passionate about the subject material, but as a first semester freshman, the quantity of work for this class was insane. She was a stickler on grammar and very picky with papers, but she would let you redo them sometimes and would always be willing to meet to discuss. Participation was a large factor of the grade.

Prof Bordogna is caring and takes participation into account heavily when determining grades. Lots of reading outside of class but are fairly interesting. Classes are student lead discussions. Harsh grader on writing but gives helpful, specific feedback. Encourages you to share your opinion and curves final grade if you show you put in the effort.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: One of the nicest guys ever. He was a super easy grader. The reading is optional. The class itself was kind of boring, but I would encourage you to sit through it because the class is an easy A. You get 2 extensions to use throughout the term.

Rocio is suuuch an awesome professor. Super energetic, caring, and very knowledgeable. She really cares about both her subject and her students, and she put in a lot of work to help us to succeed. Very fair grader, and the readings for the class weren't too heavy.

I really liked Gibbs' Economics of Education class. I thought that her lectures and the subject matter was very interesting, and Prof. Gibbs was very flexible and understanding throughout the semester. There isn't a lot of homework, and the tests are pretty easy.

Barron's sports analytics class was ok. I personally didn't have a ton of sports knowledge going into the class, and I was unable to understand a lot of the analysis. The lectures felt like he was just showing us a cool project he did, but we didn't actually learn the skills. Little homework + big project where you can work in group or by yourself.
I took Ceramics II with Bill, and I felt like he was good at figuring out when to step in and offer help and when to let us figure it out ourselves.

His lectures were extremely difficult to understand. He might as well be teaching in Russian. The textbook made more logical sense than what was said in class. Be prepared to teach yourself everything and still do poorly on the exams.

The course is lecture heavy and uses images from papers. Though, he does not necessarily give you those papers and all information is given while in class. As per the last comment, he may forget to record the lecture.

If you can avoid taking a class with him, I highly recommend that. Your grades are mostly determined by the tests, and it's almost impossible to study for them. He has powerpoints for his lectures, but they only have images from papers on them. If you miss a lecture, you'll be lucky if he remembered to turn on the audio for the recording.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: I just don't like the set up of the class

EG 10116 was formerly Intro to Programming for EG, learning MatLab and Python. Dr. Meyers does a great job coming to morning classes with enthusiasm and finding good ways to keep the class engaged through useful examples. She provides notes to watch before lectures. Do the assignments and attend class, and you learn the material. Very kind person.
Professor Meyers is caring and wants everyone to do well. Engineering Design has something for everyone, so it will be interesting for any true engineer at some point.

Really nice and really cares about her students. She understands material can be tough for inexperienced students and tries to help. She can get you an internship or a job if you just ask her. Great person. Course itself is tough if you have no prior coding experience.

Dr. Meyers is a solid choice for the first year engineering course. She cares about her students and does a good job relating engineering concepts to how they're applied. She also welcomes student feedback after projects, emphasizing how useful it is for her.

Corey is such a caring guy! He really wants us all to succeed and likes to joke around with all of his students. His lectures are all from the textbook so you don't really need to read it but you should be able to access it for some references for homework problems. Easy grader. Cares about our mental health. Con: goes on tangents in class a LOT.

Professor Pennycuff really cares about his students. You can see it in his lectures, his assignments, his exams, and his grading. Lectures are well-planned, funny, and he's willing to take time to explain things. Assignments and exams are well-specified, and he's never trying to trick you or get you for forgetting some edge case.

Overall a very entertaining professor. He did a good job running us through live examples of coding during lecture and directed us to useful resources. The primary drawback is that he tends to get stuck on tangents during class. Take home tests were awesome and reflective of what coding is actually like.

Professor Johnson is awesome! I took his class for Foundations and really enjoyed it. Your grade is mostly based on papers and the tests (which 75% of the test grade is an essay). He shows up to class every day excited to teach and wants everyone to learn. I definitely worked harder than my friends in other foundations but got a lot more out of it.

Very good! He clearly cares for his students and is dedicated to the course. There is an above-average level of reading, but it is a Theology class. Essays are vital but you'll do well once you realize what analysis he's looking for. Not an easy A, but not your hardest class, take if interested in getting something from class past the requirement.

She really cares about helping everyone. Even though there is a lot of reading, it is truly necessary for the lectures and discussions which are engaging. Draws from a lot of sources and topics. Overall, no exams, only papers or projects.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Prof Shrout was alright, but really couldnt care less about individuals. Because of COVID, our exams were online, but I had technology issues which caused the system to give me a failing grade, when my work and answers were actually enough to do really well. When I emailed her to ask for help fixing this issue, she ghosted me. Thanks for nothing.

There is a lot of reading for this class, but the reading is always very interesting. Make sure to attend the lectures. As long as you are attending class regularly you will ace every quiz and test. Theres no trick questions. His class is very interesting and I would 100% take again
very interesting
He has great notes and uploads them to allow you to print them out and follow along. Funny guy too
easy A, best professor ever, very understanding

Professor Cholak is a great man, but gets a little lost sometimes when he is in lecture. Especially when running out of time, he tends to rush and do a poor job explaining difficult concepts. He makes up for it with his smiley attitude, always willing to crack a joke.

I was in Professor Cholak's 8am lecture and he honestly made it interesting to come to class. He always cracks jokes and tries to make the class engaging. I feel like he could have done a bit better in going over more examples in class as he likes to show students proofs of what we're learning instead of how to apply it. But he was overall great!

Cholak was a hoot. Easier than AP Calc, but you'll have to put in a little extra work if you haven't taken calc before. Attendance is not mandatory, but he enjoys seeing people come. Homework is consistent but manageable. Tests aren't bad, but each mc question is worth 4-6pts w/ no partial credit. On the frqs, he is generous on partial credit.

I enjoyed Prof. Cholak's course on Multivariable Calc. Homework was designed really well and was due Friday, with a quiz on the prior week's material Monday. Easy format to follow, and made comprehension easy instead of big exams. Goes out of his way to help students.

He's caring and funny and often cracks jokes in class. If you tell him "ive taken math for years and still can't divide by zero" he'll love you. His Elements of Calc class is literally AP calc. Homework is simple w/ 10 tries on every problem and the tests are exactly like the practice tests he gives you. Sometimes he's difficult to understand
Good guy who cares about students and won't kill you with homework. Quizzes and tests are easy and completely taken from in class problems. No surprises

Professor Sullivan makes an attempt at getting to know her students  both in and out of class. Makes lectures very engaging and is very high energy (great pick-me-up for early lectures). After talking to friends with different philo professors, it is easy to see Sullivan's curriculum is both the easiest and most fun.

Great, interesting professor who seems to really care about her students. Diff TAs grade differently so that sucks a bit. Attending class isn't mandatory but there are 7 surprise quizzes (you can drop your lowest 2). While there is a lot of hw/readings, you can do well without actually doing it all. Pretty easy class, minimal assignments, fun prof!

I took Professor Sullivan for GGL and it's such a chill class. The class is interesting, so even though it's 9 am you're paying attention not falling asleep. Not too much work, there's a few major assignments and then thats really it. You have a tutorial once a week, which is at 8 pm either on Monday or Tuesday, I really liked mine so no complaints

Had her for GGL and loved her! The class taught me so much about myself and really helped me think deeply about my life. Professor Sullivan is clearly passionate about teaching and cares about us. She delivers the material very well and the course website makes organization easy. Not a lot of work and easy to get an A. Would take again if I could!

I question the wisdom of teaching Intro to Philo to 100 freshmen, but that can hardly be blamed on Professor Sullivan. My real objection was her unconcern for students' grades. Her grading system is very convoluted and often misleading. If you have a question about the details she is simply not interested; all you get is "read the syllabus."

He's not the best professor I've had, but not near the worst either. Taking his calculus class is probably a solid bet. He's not particularly engaging, but then again, neither is calculus, at least for me.

Professor Myers really cares about his students. His classes are fun, and the small class size encourages a sense of community. He is not the easiest grader, but he likes to see improvement and strong effort. Hard work pays off. I felt like I definitely got better at writing as a result of his class. Would recommend.

Professor Myers is genuinely one of the best professors I have ever had at Notre Dame. If you can, take this class. He cares about his students and really wants to help them learn and become better writers. The skills I learned have been super helpful in higher level classes.

Prof. Myers is a genuinely great guy. His class completely changed my relationship with English- I had always hated it in high school. The course load is manageable, maybe an hour total outside of class every week on top of three papers for the entire semester. He is very understanding and makes an effort to have a relationship with his students.

He is simply amazing!! Please, please take his class. I am pretty sure you are going to love writing after taking his class even if you don't like it right now. He is super sweet, accessible and caring - if you work hard and progress well it will definitely pay off.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I cannot recommend Professor Myers highly enough. He makes you earn your grade, but he is very accessible outside of class and willing to help out. I genuinely learned a lot from his Writing and Rhetoric multimedia class. He's an outstanding professor, but also just a good person who cares about his students.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment_Rating: I took one of Dr. Quesadas university seminar and hands down it was my favorite class freshman year. She is very passionate about her teachings and she always makes lectures interesting somehow. The books I read in her class are probably ones that Ill always remember because of how unique and amusing they are.

Very engaging lecturer & interesting class. Cares about students and willing to help out. There was no homework and I did not do the readings. 5 writing assignments ranging from 1000-2000 words. Took some time to write them. Not the easiest grader, you have to put in effort to get an A on the assignments but not hard to get A- esp. with grade boost
kind of boring and the essay prompts were so open-ended lots of kids got poor grades (don't know if he grades below a 75% tho)

Nuptial Mystery with Tim was extremely easy. Your grade was determined by 5 papers, each worth 20%. There was no other homework. I never did the reading, went on my phone during the class, wrote gibberish on the essays, and I still easily got an A. Tim took like a month to grade the assignments, but he always pushed the due date back.
One of the most interesting and engaging classes, and it's not that difficult to receive a good grade.

O'Malley and Nuptial Mystery are great. Def one of the best second theos to take. You can go on a date for extra credit to boost your grade (like A- to A, B+ to A-). I took it fall 2020 so things were different because of covid but we had weekly zoom discussions (you choose group) and weekly 2-3 page reflections, and then an oral group final. EZ
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Galvin is an incredibly kind human being and I was going through a mental health crisis the semester I was in his class (that I never told him about) and I did get my worst college grade in his class. That said, he's a great lecturer and wants to make sure students are understanding the material. I love his accent and he's just a positive, good guy
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Hardest and most time-intensive course I'm taken, but if you have to take honors calc 1 and 2, you're gonna wanna take it with Galvin. Funny, genuinely good guy who wants to help all of his students
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--Caring

comment_Rating: Professor Galvin is one of my favorite professor at ND. The material and quizzes wan't hard at all. Exams are based on homework and the grading is lenient. He was always willing to make his students to higher levels by giving challenging questions during the class. You will get an A if you want and put time in it.
Profesor Galvin is an amazing teacher but the class he teaches is insanely hard. I would recommend him as a professor but I would not recommend his class.
Probably the hardest class I have ever taken, but Galvin was great and hilarious, which kept me interested in the topics. Like I said, though, SUPER tough class.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Honors calc is the hardest class I have ever taken but Galvin's lectures are really good and entertaining and that got me through the class. Office hours and math bunker are definitely the best things for honors calc, though.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Hilarious

comment_Rating: Galvin will make you love doing the hardest stuff you have ever encountered in your young life.
DGalv  best professor
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Enthusiastic in teaching but the stuff he taught was a bit too easy.

I was so glad I had Corcelli freshman year. He was very clear and did enough examples to make sure I understood things without belaboring the point. He clearly cares about his students and wants them to succeed even in what is slightly considered to be a weed-out course freshman year. But seriously, Corcelli is great and the best gen chem prof IMO

One of my favorite professors ever. Hilarious, energetic, and really really cared about making sure that we learned things. Made a tough subject like chemistry more understandable. Would 100% take again (wish I could've taken his class 3x instead of doing physics for two semesters).

This man is the BEST professor for Chem. He is clear during lectures and gives lots of examples. He is also extremely charming. I highly suggest going to lecture, because then you don't even have to read the textbook to understand.

Great professor, definitely would miss him when I finish the semester. Very accessible after class too, I was having troubles with Chem the first few weeks of college. He helped me improve my grade, and send me an email to congratulate me on getting an A on my next exam. Hilarious professor, did a self-carving pumpkin experiment in class.
This man is a saint... if you have the chance to take any of his courses, you are blessed! Not only is he an amazing teacher but hes hilarious and just an all-around great guy.
He's an absolute monster. Always brings the energy and made gen chem bearable. Complete goat
His lecture are fun and he has a great southern accent.

Love this man. Gen chem is ND's biggest lecture hall but Corcelli really cares about his students. Right before class he always just looks so happy to be there. After his lectures my section usually had applause. He tells jokes, keeps you interested, does fun demonstrations, and explains things clearly and understandably. He's accessible too.

Certainly not a blow-off class. Thick readings for every class. Enthusiasm for Irish literature is not helpful but practically necessary to be successful. Really hard--almost impossible, in fact--to get an A. Nice woman but only take her class if you really like medieval Irish and like deep textual analysis

Professor Polini gives great lectures, makes the class fun and engaging and is always willing to slow down if it means her students will understand more. She is by far the most accessible professor I have ever had, and will help you in any way you need it. Enjoyed her class so much I'm taking her again next semester!

Professor Polini is very kind and entertaining. She is intelligent and evidently excels in her area. However, I would not recommend taking this class unless you truly enjoy math, and are good at it already. I struggled a lot with the homework assignments, and 70% of the grade is determined by two exams. 
There is a textbook, but it is not required.

Her class was incredibly interesting, but difficult. It completely changes the way I viewed the world and greatly improved my critical thinking. The most rewarding class I have ever taken at this school. I would highly recommend.

I think Polini's favorite thing ever is proofs. That's fine if you like that, but I struggled a lot because I've never been good at proofs. Between her handwriting and accent, I struggled with taking good notes in class. However, she was super passionate &overall I would recommend her - you just need to be attentive and seek help asap if u need it
This professor is absolutely amazing and inspirational. She is super caring and understanding. Be ready to work hard though!

Prof. Polini and her class inspired me to study math. She makes her class very difficult, but if you put in the time and effort, you will learn a ton. Compared to other teachers who taught Introduction to Math Reasoning, I would choose Prof. Polini again without hesitation.

She cares SO MUCH about her students. During COVID year I was stressed about life in general and got behind on homeworks. She reached out to me and offered to meet on  weekends so answer any questions I had and make sure I really understood the material so I would be successful going forward. Believed in me a lot.

Dr. Woodard is one of the best ACMS faculty at Notre Dame. She is truly caring about both her students and the material she is teaching. She is accessible in and outside of class, answering many questions very well. She is by far the most organized professor I have had! Her tests are very similar to practice problems and things in class. Must take!

Woodard is an awesome professor in the ACMS department. She is very personable and a great lecturer. Her Intro to Probability class was not bad at all. Very reasonable HW's due once a week that definitely prepare you for the tests. There's 3 midterms (that you can use a notecard on) and her notes prepare you very well for these exams.

Prof Woodard has organized note outlines that she goes over in class. She is a clear teacher and her homework is similar to class examples. About a 1.5 hour workload each week. Exams are easy as long as you study and understand concepts (she allows notecards).
Fun and energetic. Teaches everything you need to know for exams. No complaints--HW levels are reasonable.

sometimes goes off on tangents and talks a lot but overall this class was very discussion based which is engaging. He likes to press students for deeper answers--sometimes it feels like he's putting you on the spot and trying to embarrass you, but its probably because he wants you to reach your potential of developing thoughts.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Do not expect an easy humanities class from him. Knows his stuff, and expects you to know it, too. Doesn't seem like too bad a guy but research rather than teaching seems to be his forte. Essays are on complex topics and force you to do stuff you'd expect from actual history majors

This is by far the worst class I have ever taken at Notre Dame. The lectures are extremely boring and confusing. So, in the end, everyone has to read the long textbook to understand what is happening in this class. Especially if you compare this class to intermediate micro, you will see why the prof is bad at teaching.
The entire course depend on one textbook. Lectures are extremely vague and unnecessary. Taking this class = reading the textbook
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: There are so many questions on the problem set that he did not teach. You have to read the super long and boring textbook my yourself to understand the material. Like if you can study the entire course by reading the textbook, what is the point of the lecture and making the attendance mandatory? Avoid this professor at all cost.

There are 10 long problem sets and three exams. Lectures are also really long and kinda boring, but he really does care about his students. He is always available outside of class, but you'll mostly be learning on your own. He is smart and compassionate but not very engaging.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Not great. Lectures are hard to follow, and the slides and textbook do not help much. Long, hard weekly problem sets that do not reflect what you learn in class, but they are similar to the problems in the exam. Exams are hard too. He posts practice problems, but does not give answers to most problems. Cares about you learning, though.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Pugsley is a great guy! He takes the time to learn all his students names and is incredibly smart and patient. The class has lots of homework and the exams are tough, but it is doable with many collab sessions and office hours available throughout the week.

He clearly cares about his students and puts in a good effort, but has his faults. Lectures are calculus heavy, so developing the intuition is mostly on you. He is also a deliberate, careful speaker, but definitely not the most engaging, so sleep well or have coffee ready. Beware of hours-long weekly problem sets, but you can do them in groups.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Doesn't explain the material well. Exams and problem sets are not reflective of the material learned in the lecture.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Obviously smart and well-meaning in teaching. But a lot of his explanations go right over your head because they're honestly not dumbed down enough. Very calculus-heavy. Problem sets are difficult--had to go to office hours every week. I did well on the tests only with help from people who've taken him before.
Obnoxiously hard class, not made any easier by his 8-hour homework assignments (he takes a sense pride in how difficult they are) and exams so long it's almost comical. Avoid at all costs.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment_Rating: This class was really hard. Pugsley isn't the best lecturer, & it was difficult for me to comprehend the lessons, even when I read the textbook. He allows students to work on the problem sets in groups, but they're really hard still. Pugsley seems like a good guy, and he made the effort to learn everyone's name, but I was confused the whole time.

prof tweed is the best. such a nice guy and genuinely makes lectures so interesting. hard grader when it comes to papers, but you only write one or two. fair amount of reading for each class but you can kind of pick and choose which ones seem interesting to you. only need a 250ish word journal for each class

Easily one of the best professors I have had. His teaching style is great and he prioritizes learning. He is a realllly good person, very kind and patient. Take him. He makes the class very easy and the tests are open note.

Nice guy, solid teacher. M&D isn't very interesting but he definitely cares about teaching. His lectures plus HW should leave you prepared for tests but tends to throw in some tricks to the concepts. Big fan of corny jokes and inspirational quotes

Interesting lectures but LOTS OF READING!!! Additionally, be prepared to have the smallest pieces of information from the readings show up on the tests in the multiple choice. What he calls "quizzes" are really pretty intense tests, do not take them lightly you have to study. Participation matters a lot and is a decent percentage of the grade.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Lectures were always awesome. Lots of reading for homework.

Any classes Magister Mazurek teaches are fantastic. For Latin II, translation and vocabulary lists are very manageable. Tests and vocab quizzes are fair and do not require a lot of preparation. There are online exercises for extra practice and he is frequently available outside of class for any questions. Overall, a great experience.
Prof Mazurek is amazing. 10/10 recommend any of his classes.

I would miss Professor Mazurek after I finish this semester! You can tell he loves his job, gave us extra credits when he wanted us to come to a event about the classics just so we can have fun. Very accessible outside class, I like sharing Latin songs I am singing with him after class, we would work through the translation and that is always fun.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Best teacher, 10/10
Great guy, difficult class, be ok if you get a lower grade
Wonderful professor, he keeps content interesting. There is a lot of reading, but that shouldn't be a surprise for a classics course.
He is very interested in what he teaches, entusiastic, ect.

He was my professor for Moreau. Sweet man, but the class was silent pretty much. This was just an awkward class because he asked us for participation but a select few rarely responded. Still I aced it. Show up and pass pretty much.
Had him for Calc II. Funny guy, but wasn't clear. Not like the math department at ND has many good professors anyways, but I wouldn't necessarily put him above anyone else.

His lectures were very unclear; he did not do a good job teaching the material. The only way I passed the class was with the help of my amazing TA and by learning the material on my own. There are a lot of online assignments.

The difficulty of Calc III is constant no matter who teaches it. He does make it bearable and he's quite sweet. With that said, I did fall asleep during some lectures. But he's a very cool guy, and probably one of the better options I had.

The class itself I did well in the course, however, this professor does NOT teach well at all. I ended up stopping going to class entirely because I learned more from teaching myself out of the textbook than in class. He teaches as if we are already on the same level of expertise as he is. I recommend another professor like Bentley.
Made Physics I better. Interesting lectures and examples. Definitely a good choice.

One of those profs who treated the lectures as a review of what you read (which I usually did not until right before the homework), so basically she just breezes through the topics. I stopped going to class after a couple weeks.
The best professor for first year engineering. He wants you to succeed.
Great professor who clearly cares for the success of the students both inside and outside of the classroom.

An amazing Intro Engineering professor because he helps you navigate Freshman year, and gives you life advice about things like how to fit academics and the football schedule together, and the best study spots. Beloved by students.
best professor ever!!

Super nice guy and cares so much about his students. The enthusiasm that he brings to class every day is really contagious. He is always available to help outside of class and it's clear that he wants us to find the same love for engineering that he has. If you have the chance to take him for freshman engineering classes you definitely should!

Andrew is an amazing professor, I had him both semesters for Intro to Engineering. Everyone who took his class before wanted to again. He is very clear and puts in more time than he is required to because he really wants you to learn. He gives a lot of detailed feedback and responds to feedback about his teaching. He is a real gem.

Professor Howard is a brilliant, caring man who is a wonderful professor. His lectures are very interesting, and he is very accessible outside of class. He grades fairly and gives wonderful feedback regarding the papers you turn in. Take his class if you can! They is a lot of reading involved with his class, but it is interesting and not boring.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Howard is the ideal professor to have. He is the nicest person ever and will likely give you an A if you try. It can be easy to fall asleep sometimes in his class, but he does offer a lot of cool information if you tune into the lecture. He is very intelligent and excellent at answering questions. Easy class, but just really boring and not engaging so lectures went by slow.

Professor Battin was really kind throughout the semester, I took it during COVID times so it was an online class for me. There were only a few short essays, reflections, and a final paper. I don't know that I would necessarily recommend Professor Battin's class but he's really sweet who knows a lot about Theology, there's short daily homework with 2 papers and 1 project. lots of readings and a daily 'paragraph/question' homework assignment, but super easy grading. No exams, only a midterm and final paper, creative writing assignment (which is fun), and an easy presentation with a partner

Great Lecturer. Extremely Helpful. Difficult Tests.

Prof. Wharton is so nice. I was intimidated by her at first but she is kind and helpful. English is not my first language and she was very patient working with me. Very clear lecturer and good at jumpstarting class discussions

Professor Wharton is kind and very articulate. She can be difficult to understand sometimes but she is really helpful if you come see her after class or in office hours.

Has a very cute dog. Sit next to the aisle and eat beef jerky before class and the dog will come to you.

Collon goes a lot into the derivations and "why?" of physics concepts. Sometimes lecture feels slow, at other times he goes very fast through difficult examples. Homework is very hard. Great human being and great teacher

The best professor in the math department, hands down. Cares deeply about students on top of being an extremely skilled lecturer. Teaches review sessions for classes that he doesn't even teach that are wildly popular. Standards based grading pares down the amount you actually learn, however.
Brian is the best Math professor at this University. His class is a must take for whatever subject he is teaching.

AWESOME teacher. Your best choice for math at ND. 10/10 would take again.  I had him for calc III and while the material can be boring, he makes it interesting. Prefacing by saying that I withdrew, but I urge all Glynn students to not take the second semester without taking the first math seminar. Professor Schommer-Pries was a really nice guy and always took the time to ensure everyone understood the material. Professor SP's lectures were always very entertaining, as he prioritized active learning in the classroom. He always gave study guides before the tests which were incredibly helpful. SP's lectures were incredibly boring and far too focused on small group work. It reminded me more of a high school class than a college lecture. Grading could be incredibly arbitrary, and the professor was very standoffish.

Professor SP is a great professor and genuinely wants you to succeed in his course. The homework can get tedious and annoying at times, but just work hard and you will be fine. The class isn't very difficult. The lectures he gives are long but extremely in depth. Homework 2-3 times a week. If you pay attention in class and do the homeworks you should be fine.

Most impactful class Ive taken at Notre Dame. He cares about what every student thinks. He understands and remembers what it was like to be a college kid. He has a way of drawing meaning out of pages meaning that will leave you with a hole in your chest or some hope on a crappy day.

Professor Meissner's seminar was one of my favorite classes of freshman year. He really cares about the students and facilitated us bonding as a group while facilitating our intellectual growth. The best prof in AMST, hands down. Cares about teaching, discussion, ideas, and relates them to life without the superfluous jargon and ****. Well worth it.

30104- Most worthless professor ever.  No adherence to the syllabus, random papers whenever he felt like it, rambles in class about whatever he feels like.  No coherent direction. By far, he's the best professor in the Writing & Rhetoric department. He does not grade harshly, yet simultaneously he gives extremely good feedback. Please take him, he's great!

Professor Bodnaruk has a passion for finance, which is evident in his approach to teaching. I truly loved his class. He teaches financial principles in a manner that the student can easily apply the knowledge gained in the classroom to their life outside of it.

Professor presents a more human-oriented spin on the finance world. Really interesting subject and great examples

He's one of the best Uic Finance professors that i took. The lectures were interesting and he makes it exciting to learn. He is fair when it comes to exams and grading. Come to class, take notes , listen and you will get an a.

One of the best professors in the UIC Finance Department. You will learn interesting concepts that you never even thought existed while evaluating markets and peoples behaviors. In my opinion it's a must take class in your into finance.

Funny, sarcastic professor who does an excellent job tying financial concepts to real life. Occasional interactive experiments in class. Laid back lecturing style; more concerned with the students actually gaining something than training them to memorize definitions/formulas.

Very passionate about the subject manner, very good at using empirical data to make his point.  Often interspersed his lecture with humorous stories and transitions.  I enjoyed the class and thought it was incredibly useful and profound.
Very funny and made class interesting. Great guy.
He is one of the best professors I have had, a genuinely good guy and really knows his stuff. Cares greatly about his students.

If you've come to check up on JFitzgerald, research no further. This guy is the friendliest, most down to earth professor in Notre Dame. He's clear in his lectures.
