Prof. Stober is a pretty decent professor. The lectures are boring and straight from the notes, but I believe all accounting classes are like that. He's very nice and willing to help students. Class is relatively easy if you do the homework and read the notes.

Stober is solid. Class is kinda dry and slow, but he often lets you out early if the material's done, which is nice. Tests are hardish (esp. the 2nd), but Mendoza curve helps in the end. Do the homeworks, show up to most classes, and study for the tests, and it should be easy enough to get a B+ or so. A- is a little harder, but not by much.

Extremely dry professor, reads his powerpoint lectures verbatim. Class average on the second test was 63%, so expect Mendoza curve to likely help you in the overall grade. Often tests on material that is briefly/not mentioned in lecture, so I prob look at the textbook before class. Class is relatively easy, but he does little to help
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Stober is a really nice guy. His class can be a little dry, but what intro to accounting class isnt? Mendoza curve will save you in the end so dont be surprised if one or two of the exams dont go your way. Three exams, one final and a few group projects. He does take attendance so try to not miss class.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Test heavy

comment_Rating: The class is all about a research project. There are no exams and weekly one page blog posts. Professor Beatty is very caring and kind and an overall great professor. Class material can be a little dry at times if you do not enjoy engineering history. You can send Professor Beatty drafts of your blog posts to get feedback before submission.

Pretty challenging class with lots of homework. Enjoyed the class a lot and I'm definitely way better at Spanish but it was not easy. Participate in class because she notes when you do or don't speak. Probably won't take another Spanish class but Professor Botero is genuinely very nice and cares for all of her students.

The most unprofessional professor I have ever had at Notre Dame. Her course is incredibly disorganized, yet she has insane expectations for her students. She picks favorites, is incredibly rude, and is not well-versed on the subject of immigration. She will also continuously remind you that her time is more precious than yours.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: If you want to enjoy your semester, don't take Immigration and the Construction of Memory and, above all, stay away from Tatiana Botero! Insufferably arrogant. Course is very disorganized, assignments lack specific objectives and she provides no instruction. Above all, she allows little to no room for objections. AVOID HER AT ALL COSTS!

She is a very kind and caring person, but she has very high expectations. There is a substantial amount of homework every class and participation is closely monitored. The class is taught entirely in Spanish, with little English. That being said, the subject matter is interesting and well-selected.
She gives out more work and projects in comparison to other Intermediate Spanish 1 classes. She is very caring and nice, but a harsh grader. You have to participate to get a good grade.

I had her for Cultural Conversations and Writings (covid times so online). She is an amazing professor- clearly cares about her students, the information is so interesting and opens your eyes to issues you didn't know about, some hw doesn't feel like homework. Def my fav prof and class! Say something every class and she grades tough so proofread!

I took 20202 and this is my major so I got a good grade, but the course is fairly difficult. She will grade oddly at times, but she makes up for it with many extra credit opportunities. She is arrogant, and she flexes on her teaching achievements, and she makes her left wig political views very clear, but she is passionate about her craft.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Profe Botero was an excellent Spanish professor.  She speaks clearly and slowly to where even basic speakers can understand.  I'd recommend her class to anyone at any level of Spanish.

THE BEST! Literally the kindest, nicest and most amazing professor I have ever had. She is so smart and her classes are super engaging. Also, she really cares about her students. I wish I could take a class with her every year!

I had her for Criminology. She is deeply passionate about the subject and about conveying it to students. Tests and reading reflections are easy. Final papers was slightly harder but not by much. Fun class, athlete-heavy.
I love Mim for a discussion heavy course, but sometimes the lectures can be slightly hard to follow. She cares so much about her students and will do anything you ask for. She is truly the best.

Mim is one of (if not THE) the best professors at Notre Dame. She is laid back, understanding, and clear about her content. I've had two classes with her actually, and the class structures were pretty much the same: homework question once a week, 3 exams, and a paper due at the end of the semester. She has made me excited to learn, which says a lot

Mim is literally the best. She is completely understanding, if you ever are going through something and need an extension she'll give it with no complaints. There's a good amount of reading, but if you listen during the lectures she covers most of the material so if you pay attention to the lectures and don't read as attentively you'll be fine.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Mim is a very nice professor and does care a lot about her students. However, the lectures are incredibly dry for criminology. Lots of black text on plain white slides for 1 hour and 15 minutes twice per week. It's hard to sit through at points. Tests are fair but the paper due in the middle of the year really kills when there's little direction

Professor Coloma is extremely kind and caring. She laughs a lot and really wants to get to know her students. She cares a lot about participation, so make sure to raise your hand at least once a class. The only downsides are that she struggles a lot with technology and takes forever to grade papers and tests and return them.

Prof. Coloma is extremely kind and clearly cares about her students. Just a few things to be aware of - she was somewhat disorganized throughout the semester - sending assignments via email days after we were supposed to begin them per the syllabus. The exams were pretty difficult so taking the other section without exams is probably preferable.

Professor Coloma truly cares about the class, material, and her students. You can tell she cares about Hispanic history and culture. However, she is very bad with technology and changes the syllabus pretty often. Overall a great teacher and a great course, especially because the movies we watched were entertaining.

One of the best Spanish professors at ND. Super caring. Gives a good amount of hw but has long due dates. Study guides are exactly like test. Super accessible, holds office hours everyday. Will get a good grade if you show that you try.

Profe Coloma was a pretty good professor. For my class, she only talked in Spanish and talked quickly at times. She gives decent lectures and seems to really care about teaching. She is pretty bad with technology tho, and does not grade the quickest.

The absolute sweetest man. He is flexible with grading and super understanding of his students. Lectures tended to be kind of boring, but you can tell he really loves the subject and wants people to succeed
While he is a very quiet guy which can be difficult during lectures, he is a genius. He is also very helpful and nice! I had him for Calc III and I was happy with him.
Super super sweet guy (he's also a genius). I do think he sometimes overcomplicates things and his lectures can make the material more confusing than it really is. Not a bad professor though.
Insanely talented while also being insanely good at explaining and drawing (very helpful for Calc 3). You cannot go wrong with O'Dorney

O'Dorney basically just lectured and wasn't anything special. The occasional joke, but he mostly lectures and does examples. I'd recommend some small studying of the topic he'll teach the next day, because typically he'd do a quick overview of the topic and then get right into examples. Class was fine, the guy is clearly a math genius

McWill is super old and the class is a little slow because of it. He basically just reads off a slide and that's it. He's a really nice guy and a funny guy, but in terms of course material he's useless. It feels like he has no idea what he's talking about. The class is really an easy A though.

I've had him for Cath and Pol and Why the Church.  I liked him a lot.  You don't find too many conservative profs anymore so this was a nice change of pace.  Grades somewhat tough and the material can be challenging, but he is a really nice guy who gets way too much flak from people imo.  Amazing lectures and would recommend.

Prof. Philpott is a classic right-leaning political science professor at ND, so he's very vocal about his beliefs about abortion, gay marriage, etc. He is a pretty tough grader and doesn't do a very good job of explaining complex theoretical topics.

Professor is a gem. He invests in students. He holds us to an academic standard when it comes to writing, but makes sure to give plenty of feedback/advice before the grade. He is VERY good about representing/hearing all students' viewpoints. He encourages students to argue (respectfully) to learn. Take him for organization and personability.

Professor Philpott is so kind! Unfortunately, his content is very dated. He also can't answer many of your questions. Not much homework but your entire grade is 2 exams and a debate. Def don't take him if you don't want a difficult philosophy class. Definitely don't recommend for anything poli sci!!!!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Group projects

comment_Rating: Your grade is primarily made up of two exams (also a paper and 3 pop quizzes) and is entirely dependent on your TA (I was fortunate to have a nice one). Content is very challenging, so make sure to do the readings. Attending lectures is critical for success, but generally I was confused about what was expected for studying and writing the paper.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Beware of pop quizzes--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Two tests, one essay, and three quizzes are the ultimate grade. Content is challenging and hard to read, hence why you should go to TA's once every two weeks if possible. Lectures are important to understand the content, but slides are just a quote on a screen. Feels like a level 3 course. But very engageful, interesting, necessary, and enjoyable.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Prof Deneen is so dry and the lectures were boring. The readings are long and boring. I had a really tough TA who graded harshly. 0/10 wouldn't recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: 40-50 pages of reading per week, no turn in homework or papers so hard to gauge your understanding of material. overall pretty difficult; not a throw away class.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Dr. Deneen was an amazing lecturer and was very insightful about the material covered in class. He did a great job of promoting my interest in the subject matter and the topic for our class (Utopian and Dystopian Literature) was a lot of fun. This class is reading and paper heavy, but it pays off in the end.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: This was an amazing class. My classmates were great, but Deneen was definitely what made this course special. His lectures and insight were astounding and he really got me into the material, even though this wasn't a class I was taking by choice. I would recommend Prof. Deneen to anyone. I will say, there was a lot of reading and papers.
Deneen is a very knowledgable guy. Political theory with him is really an adventure. Lots of reading though, and a few papers.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Get ready to read--SO MANY PAPERS

comment_Rating: Prof Jancha spoke exclusively in Spanish, but she would explain questions asked in English as well as important directions. I felt the course covered a lot, but I also think she did a good job explaining all the concepts. If you have no prior Spanish, I would not recommend taking ROSP10110 with her, but take her as a prof.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Great professor. She is very clear on grading criteria and doesn't screw you over on tests or compositions. If you take some time every few weeks to study the vocab you will do well in the class. Class time is very engaging and never feels too boring.

I cannot say enough good things about Professor Jancha!! She is so sweet, always available, and wants her student to do well. I had her for two semesters, and I'm so sad I can't have her again. Definitely recommend to all looking to improve their Spanish!!!
Really nice professor, easy grader, fairly easy class as long as you do the assignments. Participation matters, but the class was fine, I definitely recommend her as a professor.
Shes very nice easy grader. HW and tests are very fair. Pay attention and try and participate and youll be fine.
He taught well and gave a packet with the notes which helped when reviewing for tests.

Had Prof. Salter for calc 2 and he was pretty good. His lectures are pretty easy to follow, he uses the same packet to teach from that he passes out so you just need to copy the notes down. Some of the concepts are difficult but he's really accessible during office hours and email. I'd take his class again
I hated BLAW, but Professor Murphy made it generally easy to follow and understand.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Class is difficult with any prof. Take notes during reading to learn material, take notes based on her lecture for areas to focus on. Wants to see students succeed. Participation is worth 15% of entire grade, speak each class. Put in the work and you will be rewarded. Murphy is incredible
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I really enjoyed Prof. Murphy's class and think she is a really solid option for business law. Class is graded from two exams (that she provides past exams for beforehand to study), a group paper, some participation/homework completion, and the final. A lot of reading (it is law) but manageable. Lectures are pretty good and she's really nice!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Caring

comment_Rating:
Dr. Gerdon's Writing and Rhetoric class was my favorite class this semester.

It was undoubtedly a difficult class that pushed me. However, each class was engaging and I liked how he took time to get to know us.

He is a tough grader, but let's you rewrite papers; he makes you a better writer. My advice would be to participate as much as possible.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Don't take this class if you are looking for an easy A. Gerdon is an outstanding person and lecturer, but this comes at the cost of a more difficult and thorough understanding of theology. I greatly enjoyed the class and deepened my understanding of theology, and it set me up for future theology classes well. Great availability away from class.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: As a pre-med, I thought this class was more difficult than organic chemistry. He's a good lecturer but the long readings, tedious assignments due each class, and the various essays graded on no clear criteria made this class a massive headache. However, he's accessible outside of class and very willing to help, especially with essays.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: VERY knowledgeable professor. I have taken Theo my whole life and was worried I would be bored, but he gave a lot of new insight to the class. Definitely take this class if you want a great understanding of theology. But if you want an EASY A, DO NOT take this class. He grades fairly hard and you need to know a lot of information for exams.

Strict and intense but you will definitely be engaged in his lectures. Tough grader but good feedback, allows you to redo the first three. Tough to get an A but should get a B at the bare minimum. Would stay away from the class if you are looking for the easy A or just to fulfill the requirement. 
GRADES YOUR PAPERS DURING AN INDIVIDUAL MEETING

I have never been a big writing/English person, but I loved Dr. Gerdon's class. He is a tough grader, but he gives really good feedback and lets you redo papers. He is a very engaging lecturer and ties everything together really well. Even though I didn't get an A in the class, he made me a much better writer and I learned a lot.

I've never had a lecturer as good as him. Asked students lots of questions, no slides no notes. He'd just weave everything together in his head and make it a cohesive story that covered a pretty rigorous breadth of theology. It's not an easy intro to theo, but it sets a great foundation. Tough but fair. You'll have to be a good writer to do well.

I like Professor Gerdon a lot, his class is just a lot more than I needed out of a basic university requirement for all freshmen. He requires participation and encourages you to think much more than other profs that my friends took did. If you are just trying to take this to get a requirement out of the way, I do not recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Amazing. I never really liked writing/English classes, and I have never had more fun and learned so much in one before Dr. Gerdon. I will definitely take one of his courses again.

I'm sitting in this guy's class right now. Gerdon is so smart and clearly loves his job. The only problem is homework readings are ridiculously long so if you don't have time to read 100 pages and write a response on them before class then you will be lost during lecture because he talks fast and flows through ideas quickly.
He really challenged his students to work hard in foundations of theo. There are a lot of papers. I think it helped me in the end, but it was a lot of work.

Bad teacher. I would avoid if I were you. I learned nothing but Aristotle over and over again. He should remain a theo professor and nothing else. I'm sad because I genuinely wanted to improve my writing. He graded the entire into 30 points. An A- on one paper is minus one point and a 29/30 is a ready a 96% in the class, 2 A- and you can forget it

He is the worst teacher I have EVER had! I was one of the most talkative students in his Writing and Rhetoric class and yet he would tell me that I did not get full participation credit. We had 5+ papers and it took half a semester for him to grade the 1st paper. He says that there are regrades but that's only true for the first 3. Learned nothing.
GREAT professor, kind of a lot of work. Easy A if you try.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: All-time favorite professor. I took him for foundations of theo. Perfect choice. His class was more than just a religion class - he explained the history behind everything. He's always very nicely dressed and calls everyone by their last name. He seems overly formal, but you can mess with him. And he would quote lotr all the time! Best prof ever.

She is sooo sweet, and works super hard to make sure class is engaging and unintimidating. She'll bend over backwards just to make sure you get the support you need. One of my favorites in the Chinese department for sure!

I've taken language classes my whole life and she is the best I've ever had. She engages all students' multiple times a class and really makes sure you process, understand, and learn the material. You can tell she loves her job, and cares for her students. I am definitely taking more of her classes in the future.
He doesn't explain stuff clearly enough but goes through a lot of examples. You can tell he is very intelligent and does most of the work in his head, and doesn't explain it.
Lots of in-class examples
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Makes calculus much easier to learn. The class is hard, but he is very clear with his lectures and will not let a student have a question go unanswered.

Professor Mclean is great. While his class is lecture heavy, he provides note guides that are very helpful. As long as you pat attention in class, engage in the assigned readings, and complete the minimal homework, you will succeed.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Great professor! Very knowledgable of the subject. Kind and patient, will expand your knowledge of the Bible. Lots of reading, but manageable and worth it!
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating:
Meyer is one of the best profs in Mendoza. Your grade is almost entirely dependent on 3 exams for CFR, which he makes purposely difficult to separate the good students from the best. No busy work or projects.

The class is super interesting and Meyer is extremely funny. For all finance majors, if Meyer is teaching CFR, take it with him.

His Accounting 2 class is my favorite class to attend this semester! The tests are hard but fair. He makes the lectures so interesting and applicable to our lives, and he does a great job keeping us engaged in class.

Don't know about Accounting I but I wouldn't recommend for Accounting II. Goes through lecture notes very fast. Isn't a very organized course. Exams are overly difficult. Attendance is mandatory and I don't feel like I gain much from it. Overall, just hard to keep up.

Three exams. The material isn't hard but you're competing with your classmates on the curve. Meyer is enthusiastic and ALWAYS brings the energy to the class. The more you give to him, the more he'll give back. His lectures never last more than half the class, so he puts The Profit on to show real-life applications and tells stories about material.

Michael Meyer is by far the best teacher I have had in my time at Notre Dame. He is very energetic and passionate about both accounting and Notre Dame, and it makes his lectures easy to sit through. He is a huge fan of group work, and a truly excellent teacher

I've heard that Meyer is the best introductory accounting professor (but now that each prof makes their own test it doesn't matter as much). I like how he sets up class where he lectures for the first part and then gives a problem to work on as a group. He is also a very funny person and seems to care about his students.

Meyer is fantastic, and he teaches the material way better than the other professors.  He gives you a little 4 point quiz each week, but honestly they are not a big deal, and they help you to keep up with the material.  He is super full of energy and very loud, probably good to take him in the morning because he will wake you up.
All of the accounting professors give the same test and it is written by Meyer so if you want to be prepared for the exam make sure you get him

Avoid at all costs. If you are the type of student that relies on office hours and needs additional help, do not take a class of his. On top of being condescending, he simply does not teach well. He also is unwilling to accommodate to unforeseen circumstances (being very sick, etc.). Wouldn't recommend him to my worst enemy.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Luan is not only bad at explaining math, hes bad at English. This makes his class pretty dull. I would not recommend him if you have never taken calculus before because he breezes through he material. He does occasionally do kahoot however it does not make up for his teaching.
Nice person. Hard grader and very particular. Essay tests and papers.
Gives bad grades nicely.

Even though I didnt want to really take this class, it wasnt as bad as I expected. While she gives lectures every class you arent really expected to know the material extremely well. She does assign a lot of reading and is a harsh grader, however she makes the class interesting and you can tell she is very knowledgeable on the subject.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: He really cares about his students and wants them to succeed. Gave a lot of opportunities to improve our grades. I didn't love the lecture style and lack of any type of visual aids, and he does cold call a lot.
He is a wonderful person. He truly cares about the students and getting to know us. The class wasn't that hard, he provides a lot of guidance.

He has an awesome personality, and he really connects with students well. His lectures are very insightful, and he offers very funny mnemonics to remember specific details. He has 'blog posts' assigned for each class day, but they don't take very long and are very collaborative. He does ask for quite a few things to be printed out. 10/10

Professor Howard is a great guy and he is really passionate about the topic. He talks pretty fast in lectures so sometimes you might have to review some topics on your own if you missed them in class. The class itself was very interesting although I found it to be kind of difficult. Homework wasn't too crazy but took forever
Nice lectures. group projects.
He obviously cared about the course material. He was extremely engaging and did a good job of answering questions. However, his lectures were sometimes pretty scattered and hard to follow.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Hilarious

comment_Rating: Professor Kelsey is extremely intelligent and dedicated to helping his students understand difficult concepts. He gives great examples and simplifies complicated ideas. Lectures were sometimes hard to follow, but his notes were really helpful and he does a good job answering questions. Pay attention and go to office hours and you will be fine.
ratingTags_Rating: Hilarious--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Kelsey is one of the best teachers ever, but sadly the material didn't interest me so i didn't spend much time working hard. Definitely possible to get an A, just go to his office hours. He is just such a smart and interesting guy, even though I wasn't always engaged in class, i loved going every time
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: My favorite Prof that I have had to date. I took his seminar and was not initially excited but his passion and knowledge about the subject matter make the class worth while and fun. He seems to know everything. He wants you to do well and he will help you do so - although its not the letter grade that is important to him. Great teacher, great guy!

Mooney is absolutely amazing. He's a young guy so he is definitely pretty chill. But he's so clear and concise, I'm always impressed with his lectures. There's a bit of reading but it's a theo class so what do you expect. Definitely possible to get an A, just stay on top of things. Go to his office hours! He's great to talk to.

Great prof if you are looking for an extremely in-depth intro Theo course. He makes you work for it--the tests are more difficult than most other intro Theo courses, and is not always an easy grader. Be prepared for a lot of memorization. He is very available outside of class and gives great feedback.

Chris was a nice guy. His lectures were clear. If anything was unclear, he provided a summary after every class via email. The class has a good amount of homework - an assignment before every class. Tests aren't terribly hard - not easy. Fairly easy essay grader. He takes himself a little too seriously. Attendance is always taken.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: every calc 3 class takes the same tests, so the tests weren't rlly a factor in my rating. Behrens is a very smart guy, and if you can keep up with him, he's probably great. but he did too many proofs and difficult examples in class that i couldn't understand him very well. great prof if you're a fast learner, i'm just not
Behrens is a pretty funny guy, and he made the class pretty enjoyable. He always answered questions very well and made sure that everyone was understanding the lecture.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: I was struggling with my mental health my first semester, but Seelinger was truly understanding and caring. Do not be afraid to reach out. He seems to enjoy teaching first and second years as he loves to seem them grow.  He also loves making connections with his students. #ourengineeringfather
He's a genuine guy and really loves his students. Would recommend to any engineers getting there feet wet at ND!

Seelinger is an awesome man. I've met with him outside of class for lunch to pick his brain and for advice, and he was so helpful. He always has great advice and takes care of his students. However, for Mechanics II, his tests were extremely difficult. Do the S problems and pay attention, it's important. Great teacher, but very tough class

Seelinger is one of the chillest professors I've had. Homework is easy, lectures are usually engaging and are only dull when the content is, and the group project wasn't easy, but it was pretty close. He tells great stories, is very learned in engineering, and a good guy overall. 10/10 would take again.
great guy, very easy going and wants you to learn. the class is pretty easy so if you can take seelinger, go for it

Prof. Seelinger is carrying the AME department. He is purely a teaching professor and it shows; his presentations and lectures are finely tuned learning bombs and he might be the most accessible professor on campus. No free As in his class, but there is never a bad learning curve nor do you ever feel alone in tackling the material.
Prof Seelinger makes a genuine effort to get to know and support students. Best Intro EG prof out there.
He is just the greatest. Takes really hard material and makes it much easier to understand. Really cares that you understand what is going on. Best professor I have ever had.
If you want to know the material and understand it, he gives you every opportunity. Available outside class a lot, nice and interesting lectures. Great guy overall.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Very little homework, tests are take home short response, interesting lectures.

Prof Morrison is the most caring professor I've met in the department. He wants all his students to excel in the class and tech interviews. I would say the pre-lecture readings are the most important part for this course, and as long as you understand the concepts covered in the readings, you are in good shape for the exams.
Morrison really cares about his students and constantly asks for their feedback. not the greatest lecturer, but slides are uploaded and homework is similar to exams and review guide.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Morrison is without a doubt one of the most caring and responsive instructors in the department. He prioritizes the success and well-being of his students and is constantly improving his course and adapting to student feedback. The preternship project is an awesome industry experience as well. Not the clearest lecturer, but I'm sure he'll improve.
Morrison is a really good guy, his lectures are just way too fast and typically unclear. He is super accessible outside of class and wishes the best for his students

Prof Morrison is a really good guy overall. He just throws an excessive volume of information at you on new concepts, it can be overwhelming. Professor Bui, I think, does a much better job of teaching challenging concepts in a clear and concise format. The Preternship is great, though.

A lot of work for this class felt like busy work. I felt like I learned very little for a class that's supposed to be super important for CS. However, Morrison has only been teaching for a couple years at ND and he improves the class each year. I took it in Spring 2020 and he had like 15 office hours a week. & he truly cares about his students

Professor Morrison really cares about having his students understand the material so he's almost always available whenever you have a question which is nice. All of the class material is uploaded online before and after class so it really helps you prepare for the course if you really like the stuff he's teaching

Professor Morrison sometimes isn't the clearest in lecture but he truly does care about all of his students understanding the material and is very helpful in OH. His animations in class help everyone visualize what he is teaching and he does a good job of helping students network and prepare for industry. Easy grader so you get out what you put in.

Great professor who really cares about his students. Listens to students and adjusts assignments/expectations based on feedback. Would recommend starting assignments as early as possible. Also definitely recommend going to his/TA office hours. Super helpful!

Dr. Morrison is a solid professor. He started out the semester assigning a bit too much work, but he listened to student feedback and quickly scaled things back, even canceling a few longer assignments and class days. He and his TAs didn't grade particularly harshly either.
Professor Morrison wants all of his students to succeed and will go to extreme lengths to ensure it. Awesome teacher/mentor
Lectures are not clear and barely help, workload is twice that of all other classes combined with insane lab deadlines. Avoid at all costs.

He's relatively new to the school and still is getting accustomed to the culture and figuring out the best way to teach his courses. A lot of people didn't like him, but I think he has some potential.

LITERAL QUEEN. the grading of labs is so fair. not a hard class literally just follow the procedures and do the post/pre labs and you'll be perfect

Your grade is pretty dependent on your TA, but it usually works out well if you put enough effort into your writing. From my own personal experience, as well as from what I understand from my peers, it is easy to get an A- in the class, but relatively difficult to get an A.

You're able to suggest songs for extra credit so make sure to take advantage of that. Grading is 100% reliant on TAs so make sure that you ask for help when needed. Take advantage of the chance for TAs to give feedback on your papers before turning them in.

Prof. Wolbrecht was super nice and funny during lecture- unfortunately, I really didn't get much out of her class.  I enjoyed the section meetings with my TA more than I enjoyed her lectures. She is really funny during lecture but it was 100 students so she won't know you personally unless u ask to meet with her. The essays had engaging prompts but were sometimes open-ended/confusing. no exams but writing heavy.

She was a new professor, so she wasn't good at explaining things at all. I assume that she will get better as time goes on because she is really smart and clearly knows what she is talking about, she just gets confused when explaining it. Most of the class is doing in-class problems instead of lecturing. Students teach more than she does.

Professor Sabety truly adapts to the needs of every student. She tries to make sure that everyone gets the most out of her lectures and readings. She is very attentive to what is happening in the classroom and cold calls to assert that students have understood. Her course creates a fun learning environment for students.

Great and caring professor. Having taken micro in high school, I came into the class knowing most of the material, so it was not too hard. However, I feel like she often overcomplicated things and struggled to explain the material. She made up for it in different ways, and as a new professor it will come. Would recommend :)

Prof. Sabety is a great person- super nice and caring, but not the best teacher. She gets confused when explaining things, and lets her students do most of the teaching. She's just TOO smart that she can't explain the entry-level course well. She gives extra credit and brought in presenting panels, but I would definitely recommend reading the text.

A very kind, funny, and welcoming guy. I took his Intro to Design Thinking course and absolutely loved it. An overall awesome guy, if you take his class, be sure to chat with him about football and just get to know him.

Prof. Goehler is a great, down-to-earth guy who ran an engaging class. Make sure to get a group you like/can work with for your semester project. Although the class is labeled 2 credits, it's more like 3. However, the work is not hard. If you go to lecture and do the homework, you will do fine on the exams.

My second class with Prof Goehler was DoME. Hearing about the class from upperclassman and his past in teaching more difficult classes, I was worried about how hard it would be. However in his first time teaching it he did a really good job of making sometimes boring material easy to grasp, and made the series of projects to help us learn well.

Professor Goehler is great and you can tell he really loves what he does! Wants to get to know his students by name, and is an ND grad so really likes to talk about football and engage with students. If you do the work you'll do well. The semester project is career/design oriented and great to bring up in interviews. Made friends in the class too!

Go to class and you will learn SO much. He makes learning fun. He's super available for meeting/emails. -good class but taught primarily online where you essentially teach yourself

great professor, really makes you want to produce your best work

comment_Rating: I took Brian Krostenko's class "Words in Time" during my senior year.  One of the most memorable, interesting, and enjoyable classes of college.  Perhaps the best class I ever took.  Worth the price of tuition.
the best profesor I have ever seen

Dr. Krostenko is the best prof I had at ND.  His classes were amazing.  He was almost good enough to keep me at Notre Dame after my masters.  How he manages to stay around the bleak scene at ND is beyond me.

Prof. Krostenko is the most approachable, competent, lucid, and interesting classics professor in the entire world.  He's also a skilled linguist.  If you don't take Professor Krostenko, or if you do and don't work hard enough to pass, shame on you.
Outstanding teacher in the classroom . . . unbelievable.  But don't try to contact him during office hours, very inaccessible and unaccommodating.
Great overall class structure, caring and accessible outside of class. Easy A if you put in the work.
Very chill professor and genuinely cares about students. Lets you write about really anything that you want. Would definitely recommend for multimedia w&r

She bothered me a little when talking to the class because her voice fluctuates like she's talking to middle schoolers but otherwise fine. She will grade the initial inquiry hard but just follow her feedback and you'll be okay. As long as you submit all your assignments with some effort you'll finish with an A or A-. She cares about the students.

Class was very easy for a writing and rhetoric. Only project that really took a while was the research paper (7-10 pages). Other than that, homework was completion-based and other projects were easily graded and easy to complete. Would recommend taking multimedia for an easy W+R, especially Whitney's.

I loved having Professor James; she is very enthusiastic and willing to provide help with assignments. It is also evident that she genuinely cares for her students. Assignments are clearly laid out and deadlines are manageable.

Great professor and a really sweet guy. He made most topics easy to follow through his lectures. Homework is optional but great to use as a study guide. Occasional pop quizzes from pre-class videos (easy to go through on 2x speed). Exams are surprise-free and look like the homework (no time crunch). Overall made me love accounting, great class
ratingTags_Rating: Beware of pop quizzes--Caring--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Out of all the Accounting 1 professors, he is probably the worst. The lectures bored me to sleep and I just couldn't seem to do well no matter what. I attended his office hours and met with him to see what I could do to improve. After telling him what I did to prepare, he said "I don't know why you're not doing well." Avoid.

Prof. Miller does a good job of explaining accounting topics for a newcomer to understand. He emphasizes building a foundation for the subject as a whole and then fitting new pieces of information into that foundation. If you want to do well, keep up with the reading and recommended homework.

TAKE HER. she's super accessible outside of class and just overall is very sweet and caring. you get graded on 2 exams, 1 cumulative final exam, a group project, and some homework/quizzing/participation stuff. hw and quizzing is based on multiple choice canvas quizzes that you can retake up to 4 total attempts. you get a notecard on exams!

Great professor who cares about her students. I wish it wasn't a lecture so that I could've gotten to know her more but she was very kind to all her students. Very easy class that requires studying for exams, but they are not very difficult. Mainly averages of 80-90%. Would recommend!
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Very good at explaining the information, always supportive and helpful.

Professor Walsh's lectures weren't the most clear explanations of the material, but she gave you every possible material you need to succeed. In-class notes, chapter summaries, video recaps of lectures, and more are all available to the students. Take advantage of those support systems and you'll do well.

Amazing experience in Elements of Statistics. Clear lectures and organized notes which help greatly with the concepts. Always accessible before and after class. Exams are not too bad and you get a notecard on them. Knows how to use technology very effectively as well. Reading/HW quizzes somewhat difficult but multiple attempts offered.

Dont need to attend class if you watch her lectures online but class offers many more helpful examples/explanations. Very helpful in explaining different concepts or going over questions. The concepts will get you, not the math, but 3/4 exams are fairly easy. I attended about half the classes and relied on her online lectures, turned out fine

Professor Walsh did a great job of making statistics accessible to the mostly engineering students in her class. Everything was heavily example based in class, and she allowed stuff like a notecard on tests so that it wasn't just a memorization exam. If you can do the homework, you can probably do the quizzes and then the tests with some studying.
She's a nice professor. I found myself drifting off a lot during her lectures. You really need to make sure you understand the content on your own. I don't have too many complaints
Such a great stats professor. Lecture videos are posted in case you miss class and she does a great job of giving thorough explanations and step-by-step examples. Would definitely recommend!

Professor Walsh was a very knowledgeable, kind and dedicated teacher. It was evident that she cared about her students. The lectures in class followed guided notes which made it easy to follow along, and she tried her best to engage students in class. If given the option, I definitely recommend taking her.
She's a good teacher, stats just isn't my thing personally. She teaches the material relatively well and the tests are fair. If you are required to take a stats class, she is not a bad option.

Incredibly easy class. She is also a saint and a gem. The lecture itself is kind of boring and the structure is always the same, but she is the best for Business Stats and Engineering Stats. Free A. Guided notes for every chapter. Online tests (at least during 2020-2021 year) - except an in-person, 20% final. Take her if you can.

Professor Walsh is an amazing teacher. She truly cares about her students and learns all of their names. Her guided notes are very clear and easy to understand, and she's always willing to help her students understand. Your grade is mostly comprised of your three midterm exam and final exam grades.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment_Rating: Professor Walsh explains concepts well in lecture and is careful not to take too much/too little time on individual topics. Easy class.

Francalanci is super nice, understanding, and always willing to explain something you don't understand and answer questions. Pretty easy grader, just make sure you participate. Enjoyed this class a lot more than I anticipated--highly recommend taking it with Francalanci.

I took him for Intermediate Spanish 1. He does things exactly by the book, so just check the calendar on Canvas to make sure you're keeping up. Lots of VHL homework, but that is the course, not him. Tests are simple and he is an easy grader. Very kind man as well, always willing to answer questions. He is a great choice for a Spanish professor!
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Francalanci is an extremely nice guy, and it's clear that he cares about his students, but honestly his class was SO boring. We had a ton of reading and then just talked about a poem ad nauseum all class. I don't feel like my Spanish improved and I lost a lot of my interest in learning Spanish.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Profe was an amazing Spanish professor. Although I am pretty horrible at Spanish, he was a very lenient grader and I ended up doing pretty well. Overall, we did not have much homework day to day, and besides a few papers and tests, the course was fairly easy. Definitely would recommend taking.

Most of the learning is done online and outside of class, which was very difficult for me personally. The tests weren't too bad; writing assignments were graded leniently. My main complaint was that we mainly did online activities in class rather than explaining the concept to us. He is very good at explaining but should do it more!

He truly cares about our learning. He speaks in English when he needs to explain important things but overall speaks Spanish. You read a couple chapters (of an English book) every week and get credit for discussing it in Spanish. The only flaw is that he is an extremely slow grader. We have 1 week left of school and he's only graded one assignment.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Caring

comment_Rating: Solid professor. He's a cool guy who really cares about his students and the content. His participation expectations are a little excessive, but he's pretty lenient when it comes to grading papers and extensions for assignments.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: This man is such a sweetheart who CARES about his students. Very understanding and will talk in English to clarify important points. I am praying that I can take this man again. This class I took actually had no tests (only papers, participation, and presentation).

Love Professor Francalanci. Super understanding of all students' spanish level and creates a welcoming and comfortable class environment. Slow to return papers (2-6 weeks) so not really sure where you are grade wise until the end of the semester. Regardless, minimal homework and great overall class to take - Leo is the best!

Professor Francalanci was awesome! I've had four different professors in the Spanish department so far and they've all been amazing and caring! Show up, do your work, and participate and you'll be totally fine in his class.

Maybe my favorite prof at Notre Dame! I've now had him twice and really enjoyed both classes. He's super understanding of your level of Spanish and makes sure everyone feels comfortable. He's also very intelligent and generally a thoughtful guy. As long as you bounce back his care for the material you will succeed in the class. Take him!

Leonardo truly cares about each one of his students. He wants everyone to enjoy Hispanic Literature and tries to make in-class activities as intriguing as possible. Tests pretty easy and straightforward. Overall a quality professor.

Class is very introductory, so if you aren't very interesting in theology in general the lecture may be boring and repetitive (which was often the case). However, she is very respectful, professional, cares about her students, knowledgeable about the topic, and definitely a great easy first theo.

You need to do the readings at some point even if it isn't right when they are assigned to do well on the tests. However, she gives students study guides and holds review sessions before tests so tests are pretty manageable/easy. The class isn't the most enjoyable, but it's great for the 1st theology requirement because she is insanely positive.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Caring

comment_Rating: Professor Cavadini is genuinely the sweetest lady. The class wasn't too difficult but the lectures were pretty boring. It's fine if you're fulfilling a requirement, but probably wouldn't recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Cavadini has been my favorite professor at ND. She's incredibly passionate and eloquent and truly cares about her students, even in a larger class. While the workload was pretty standard for a 4000 level class, she had creative assignments that I really enjoyed. Can't recommend her enough.

While I don't find theology particularly interesting, Prof. Cavadini maintained a positive attitude and was able to keep the students engaged in her lectures. Short reflections before each class (simple) and short essays (average to difficult).
She is truly a wonderful professor. She is very understanding and adaptable. I always looked forward to her class. Definitely take one of her classes if possible.
She is a true gem. Super enthusiastic and loves what she is teaching. If given the opportunity, take her class!

Professor Riedl clearly cared about what he was teaching, but was rather dull in teaching it. He was available outside of class and was helpful and responsive overall, but if you're prone to falling asleep in class Professor Riedl is not the professor for you.

I recommend taking advantage of office hours, doing extra practice problems and getting to know the TAs; use the resources at your disposal. Exams are moderately difficult but are doable if you take good notes and study. Dr. Del Valle wasn't perfect (she makes mistakes frequently), but she was a good teacher who made chemistry enjoyable.

Del Valle is awesome! She's very accessible to students and works to connect with them despite the large lecture size. Gen Chem 1 is a difficult course, especially if your high school chemistry background is not very extensive, but her clear notes and organized slides are easy to follow. She makes lectures interesting by doing lots of demos.

I absolutely adore Professor Del Valle. She has a strong, relentless commitment to her students and cares about them so deeply. I sat in on other lectures at time and none are nearly as good of a teacher as her. She writes her notes very clearly and organizes them, providing high-quality explanations of the material.

Cannot recommend Prof. Del Valle enough. Truly cares about the success of all of her students, whether or not you actually have her for lecture. She's extremely helpful in office hours and promptly answers emails. Always enthusiastic and positive. Lectures are thorough without being redundant, and we often got ahead of the course schedule.
She is really nice
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Caring

comment_Rating: If you like to have organized, written notes, this is the best gen chem professor imo. I had no AP chem background going into the class, and she was very accommodating for people like me. Her lectures felt less rushed than the other profs, but we always got through the same material.

CHEM 10122 was BioChem for EG students. Prof. DelValle does a great job leading the class with detailed notes that she planned ahead, and often uploaded online. Tutorials for this class varied based on TA, but lectures were structured and she respected your time. Friendly and not a harsh grader.

Overall, she was a good teacher for Gen Chem. There were only a few moments that I felt I was falling behind friends with other teachers. Attendance is not technically mandatory, but the slides she posted don't help if you miss class.
Dr. Del Valle is incompetent. She has woefully underprepared students for their first class of organic chemistry.

She's very sweet and would bring another professor in to show my class demos which other chem professors wouldn't do. She teaches well but you definitely need to read the textbook along with her lectures to understand everything well. If you attend lectures and make sure to learn the material well outside of class you should have a good grade.

Professor Del Valle always seemed a little frantic and frazzled during lectures. She'd make mistakes and sometimes not understand why an equation wasn't working out the way it was. In comparison to other gen chem teachers, though, I think she was good. She has a good teaching style.

While I did well in the class and learned everything I needed to know, I often came away from Professor Del Valle's lectures feeling like one crucial piece of information was missing. This was slightly frustrating, but I overall it didn't affect my ability to perform well in the class.

She's okay. She's really sweet and I have no problem with her class but based on how some other students describe their professors it seems that there's some better options. However I can always do the online homework after lessons, but sometimes her examples don't fully reflect the homework so it can be confusing.
Del Valle was very nice and willing to help students. While her lectures weren't boring, they weren't very helpful because she tended to ramble.

A professor who really cares about her class despite the sheer amount of people. Unfortunately, there are strange things to note, like how she records lectures but doesn't say where they went and her refusal to share notes with the students. Just pay attention and study, and you should be able to get an A if you are studious enough.

Prof. Del Valle is such an awesome professor that I actually didn't mind morning lectures. Definitely attend class if you're confused, but if you know chemistry (like AP Chemistry) then the class shouldn't be bad. She actually cares about the students, so if you email her about a question, you can feel the passion in her response. 10/10 professor.
She was pretty good for gen chem. Very nice and wanted her students to do well.
Super smart guy, but the workload is ridiculous. Would not recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--So many papers

comment_Rating: He's amiable and approachable, yet a strict grader with unattainable expectations. The sheer volume of homework he assigns is overwhelming. Balancing his demands with other coursework and responsibilities is a struggle. While I appreciate his dedication to academic excellence, I wish he would be more mindful of his students' time and workload.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating: Professor Gregory is outstanding at teaching. A true and passionate scholar, his classes are entertaining and he's usually available to answer any questions. Lots of reading, and papers are harshly graded, but he truly pushes you to your limit (in the best way possible). Would definitely recommend if you're up for a challenge.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Cares about his students and tries his best to get to know everyone. Very knowledgeable and really enjoys what he teaches. Lectures are interesting but can be convoluted. Lots of reading each week for discussion. The tests are pretty straightforward however there is a lot of information covered and they are graded fairly strictly.

Professor Gregory may be the most intelligent professor I've had. His lectures are very detailed and intentionally constructed, and you have to pay close attention to them to be successful. The assessments, however, were very clear in terms of requirements. Doing well in this class is very dependent on simply how much work you're willing to put in.

Honestly my favorite professor I had this semester. So kind and clearly LOVES his subject. However, don't schedule classes right after his lectures because he tends to run about five minutes over. Lots of reading but it's only for discussion posts, and we only have 2-3 tests and papers. Great guy and fun to listen to.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Easily the greatest professor I have had at Notre Dame. There is an absurd amount amount of reading (can be upwards of 200 pages a week), but he is a fantastic lecturer and facilitates very insightful discussions. This class is a lot of work, but it is life changing.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Best lecturer that I have ever had. Super helpful. Tons of reading, but by far favorite class I have had. Incredibly helpful and understanding with due dates and student conflicts

I took his Christianity, Commerce, and Consumerism class. By far the best lecturer I have ever had; very knowledgeable about his subject. His class requires a LOT of work. You have at least 100 pages of primary-source reading a week and have to read three books. His class is really only graded on two very hard midterms and two lengthy papers.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Get ready to read--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment_Rating: Class is only for those who took AP calc in high school. If you haven't taken calc before, good luck. Prof doesn't explain concepts  and accent makes understanding very hard. He teaches like we all have a PhD. There are 3 lengthy homeworks a week.The online quizzes are also bad, and mark anything w/ typo as wrong, and he doesn't double check them.

Yikes. He is a nice guy but would not recommend taking class with him. His lectures make the material 10x harder than necessary and he calls on students relentlessly. His accent makes communication hard and he takes roundabout routes around fairly easy concepts. For a math class based around simple concepts this class has a gross amount of work

English is not his first language so he is often difficult to understand. He's funny and entertaining but he singles kids out which is uncomfortable. Tried to get help outside of class and he wasn't very willing to answer my questions. He teaches from his own textbook and forgets that not all of us are math professors

Terrible lecturer; makes the topic way harder. With that being said, the course is easy and the guided notes available on the website help. Problems on homework/quiz/tests come straight from guided notes. Half of what he says you wont understand. He talks away from the class. He doesnt take attendance, so a good class to skip.
Super interesting course and not very difficult, especially for a science course. 100% worth your time.

she offers a ton of extra credit - if u want an A u can get it. u can literally look up a summary for the book report over fall break and get a 100 on it; her reflections were due Monday and posted Friday and was A TON of reading and videos to analyze; midterm is fine and can correct for 1/2 back; she communicates pretty fast too and is super nice.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--EXTRA CREDIT--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Prof Goodson was not necessarily bad for Big History it's just a ton of homework for people who aren't used to the content. If you r looking for ur Glynn science credit j take it.its not that bad. Goodson is low-key funny but lectures get tiring and nothing in them matters..midterm is entirely problem sets; the reading for reflections is INSANE btw
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--EXTRA CREDIT--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Lectures can sometimes be a bit bland, but Dr. Goodson has a real passion for her class. While Big History can sometimes seem a bit foreign, she always does a great job to foster understanding. She is oftentimes unknowingly funny, so lectures keep students on their toes. I would totally recommend to Glynn students seeking their science credit.

Professor Goodson is not a great professor. Trying to get a hold of her on email is difficult, and she is very inconsiderate with student's time as she sometimes wouldn't post the homework until a night before it was due. She also assigned a book to read over break which is not cool. The class isn't difficult, but it is needlessly annoying.

My BIGGEST issue with Dr. Goodson, and I emailed her a few times about this during our class, was that she posts homework at the very last minute. The weekend assignment of three HOURS of lectures and 50pgs of reading was always posted Saturday or Sunday, so getting ahead was never an option. She is highly inconsiderate of students' time.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: She was my only option for a required course, Fundamental Principles and Biological Processes (aka Biochem). She treats lecture as a "review of what you read in the textbook," aka "I will fly through this stuff and assume that you're already familiar with it." You also must be present so you can answer her polls, and it counts as participation.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: She is a pleasant professor and makes her lectures fun with activities. However, grades kind of harsh on assignments, of which there are a lot of, which means a lot of minuscule errors lead to multiple points removed. Wish there was less assignments. Participation also is huge for her.

Very fun class with an AMAZING professor. Most grades were done through projects, and I promise that your level of effort directly correlates to a good grade. The homework was dense at times, but overall I would highly recommend this class to anyone seeking to expand their French knowledge and/or their business knowledge!

I loved her Intermediate I class and would definitely take it again. She encourages participation and is extremely kind. It had been a while since I had taken French and she was extremely accessible. This is the professor you want in the French department. A LOT of assignments and the class isn't easy, but you really learn so much and enjoy it.

Prof. Schaefer is an incredible French professor that I would happily take again. She makes her classes engaging, she heavily encourages participation, and uses a wide variety of content from books to movies to broaden your understanding of French culture. I would highly recommend this class, you will learn so much French surprisingly fast.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: This class is centered on French cinema, so don't be surprised when you're given movies to watch for homework! Dr. Schaefer is a tough grader, but the homework and tests are manageable. You can tell that she cares about her students, not just the subject. She re-ignited a love of French that I lost years ago. Couldn't recommend her more highly!

All the information is given through lectures so you have to attend each lecture. She is engaged and knowledgeable in everything she discusses, so she keeps the class interesting with her examples and jokes. There's a lot of reading, but I didn't do any of them and still passed with an A as she discusses all the readings/concepts in class.

Prof. Rosato's International Relations course is amazing. The material is very interesting, and she does a great job of explaining each concept. The class is very easy and the only homework is doing some readings. Her lectures are also very fun as she tells a lot of jokes and provides good examples of each concepts.

Great Lecturer and very friendly professor. She is captivating and I enjoyed going to class even if it wasn't mandatory. The grading was only three exams and an essay so just study and you will do fine.
Rosato is one of my favorite professors at Notre Dame. Her lectures are fun and exciting and also very informative. As long as you do the readings you will do very well in the class.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Professor Rosato is an amazing Professor all around. She is super kind and funny; it is clear that she cares about her students and wants to make the class enjoyable. Also, her lectures are entirely understandable and always engaged and interested me. One more thing-Rasheed (TA) is amazing. I will miss Professor Rosato and her class a lot!

cannot recommend a better professor to start with for poli sci reqs. literally, ND give her a raise, make her department head, in fact, give her Jenkins ' job. 1000/10. straight forward tests and lectures in a way that makes complicated theories simple. also Madeline best TA ever. loved this class.

Professor Rosato is seriously the gem of the polisci department! Her lectures are amazing and she makes sure that everything you need to know for her exams is covered. She is also eager to help her students by meeting outside of class to discuss major considerations, giving course recommendations, etc. By far the best intro polisci class!!!

This woman is seriously one of the best professors at Notre Dame. Political Science students looking to get their breadth requirement - take IR with Susan Rosato. Her class is lecture-based but they are seriously so interesting and funny; you have 3 tests which are all memorization and based on the lectures. She goes over the homework readings too.

Professor Rosato was great for IR. She makes the lectures fun and the content easy to learn. Her class has 3 exams (which cover a lot of info, so be sure to study) and 1 paper (5pg). For the discussion session, make sure you do the readings (or at least know the basic ideas of the readings). The workload is very manageable. I would 100% recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Amazing lectures --Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Dr. Rosato is a gem within Political Science department. While her lectures aren't mandatory, her lectures are interesting enough to want to come. The reading is dense, but the discussion sections help to understand. Ultimately, if you come to the lectures, take notes, and do the reading, you are essentially guaranteed some sort of A.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Rosato is a fantastic professor. She is incredibly knowledgeable, willing to talk to her students and is a funny person. I would absolutely recommend taking her class. The course is based entirely off of the lectures, so make sure that you go to class. The tests are all memorization; however, if you take the time to study, you'll get an A

Professor Rosato is one of the best in the Poli Sci department. This was my first class in the major and it was great. The tests are mostly memorization, and the readings directly correlate to the lectures.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Rosato is amazing. The class was super easy, but also so interesting. It was a great intro class - the content wasn't too difficult and she's always available to clear up questions. Mostly tested based on memorization. 10/10/.

Professor Rosato is great. She gives good lectures and does a great job at being clear and concise in delivering content. Class should be a pretty easy A as long as you do the readings, take notes, and show up to class. Tests are heavily based on memorization (definitions, significance). Good intro class.

Professor Rosato is an AMAZING lecturer. She is funny, approachable, and will talk with you before class and just be very open. However, her class is very memorization centered. The tests are VERY memorization oriented, but if you pay more attention than I did you'll hopefully get an A but I don't personally know anyone who did. She's cool though!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: She used to wait 3 minutes every morning because I'd show up late (it was an 8:20). Looked me in the eyes on multiple occasions to tell me she was proud of me for showing up. Easy tests, minimal studying necessary, definitely should read the readings or attend the lectures. Everything on the test is in the lectures and she doesn't want to trick you

She's a hilarious teacher who made learning the material interesting and engaging. There is a lot of assigned reading but I would just skim over them and I did just fine. Only the discussion sections have mandatory attendance. There are only three midterms (which aren't too hard) and no final which is always nice
Makes an effort to give good lectures, which end up being hilarious. She is also very kind and helpful. She does however give a ton of reading, tho I didn't do most of them and still got an A.

Great professor. Only gives three exams over the entire semester that were straightforward. As long as you know the readings, participate in the discussions, and make a moderate effort in the class, you will be fine. She is also super funny.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Hilarious--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment_Rating: She was awesome! Very funny and relatable and not overly difficult if you pay attention and make an effort. Would definitely take her classes in the future.

excellent teacher! No final exam, just 3 midterms that were really straightforward (ID, short answer, essay) and a short final paper. Very approachable, and her lectures are always interesting and relevant!

Good professor! She's funny and crazy smart. The readings don't always need to be read because discussion sections each Friday tell you everything you need to know. She's a really nice person as well. I would recommend her for sure, just be careful, subjective grading can screw you.

Professor Duarte is a tough professor. Readings were very dense, and he was rather cold during discussions. He is a very harsh grader and has no problem critiquing a paper word by word. If you are looking for an easy A class to fulfill the university Philo requirement, do not take Duarte, you have better luck with GGL.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: His in-class presence is fine, and discussions are sometimes informative/interesting. However, he is an incredibly tough grader who did not elaborate on grading when asked. After putting in countless hours for his papers, asking for his help, and still performing poorly, his class has neither improved my skills nor prepared me for more.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Great professor, engaging, experienced, will take more of his classes.
Perfect Moreau for those who don't care. Basically an automatic A if you submit the assignments and hit the word minimum.
Nice guy. Strangely, I dont think he is a very good percussionist, but he seems to enjoy his job and is likeable
His moreau section was very easy. You basically can get full credit just for submitting the assignments.
Definitely take him for Moreau. I copy and pasted Taylor Swift lyrics every time for the weekly prompts and got 100% in the class.
Sam is my favorite person in the entire world, cares about as much as we do about Moreau, and he has the cutest dog named Edwin.
Great director, and a superb conductor. Manages the concert band extremely well in rehearsals and concerts, and is also excellent with the marching band
The guy who graduated but could never leave.  Still thinks he's an undergrad and tries to be one even tho he's not.
I love his sunglasses.
Sam's awesome.

Prof. Ashfeld cares about his students so much. It's so easy to get help outside of class as he offers review sessions and office hours. Orgo is the most difficult course I've taken at this school, but he makes it bearable! Attendance is not mandatory but if you skip a lecture you're screwed. Would totally take him again!
He cares. He gives you every tool you need, its just up to you to use them. Would recommend and would take again if I could. Best possible teacher for Orgo 2 here.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Ashfeld cares so much about his students and goes above and beyond for them. He knew everyone's name in our class of 70 and made Orgo 2 fascinating and entertaining. Orgo 2 has a nasty reputation but I always looked forward to his lectures. Hands down the hardest class I've taken but would take again no doubt. I cried a little when it was over.

comment_Rating: Best professor I've had at Notre Dame so far. Even though the material was difficult, I looked forward to going to his class. Very fair professor with a great sense of humor and extremely good at explaining tough concepts.
