His exams were easier than his homework sets and straightforward, so you feel well prepared. He is a really amazing, smart, funny, and engaging lecturer and learned everyone's name even in the huge lecture hall.

I don't really agree with the previous rater, Dr. Cronin was a very tough grader and had a difficult class with difficult problems sets but it was definitely worth it.  He gave pretty good lectures and I learned a lot in his class, and I'm performing better in Macro than my peers who took the other Micro teacher
ratingTags_Rating: Tough Grader--Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: An absolute, without a doubt, in every sense of the phrase, "must-avoid teacher." Makes the class far harder than it needs to be- the sections with other teachers had no idea how to do the work we were doing.  He is impossible, self-righteous, and downright unbearable.  Take him at your own risk.

Great guy, very passionate and excited about the subject. Lectures are interesting and slides are posted. Reviews are posted before exams. Grading is mostly the three exams with some points from homework assignments and participation-graded quizzes. An hour of homework every other week.

I loved this class. I hadn't taken a stats class in high school, so I was really concerned, but this class was great. The weekly tutorials are also really helpful for clearing up any doubts. The problem sets were long, and a lecture definitely put me to sleep at some point, but overall, the class and the professor weren't as scary as they seemed.

Professor Dunne is really smart and a super nice guy. The course material is difficult to make interesting so I don't blame him for often dry lectures, though he definitely strives to be engaging. He explains the material very well and makes it very understandable. Homeworks are manageable and beneficial for grasping the material.
Really interesting guy who is clearly passionate about the subject. The class isn't too hard and grading is extremely generous.

I really liked Professor Dunne because he was always very clear about the material. However, I often felt that going to lectures and tutorials was not super useful because all of the slides are posted, which helps make revising for exams easy. Exams can be somewhat tricky with the MC and T/F, but the other portions are pretty straightforward.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: While the lectures for Macro are a bit dry, the content is all in the lectures and textbook. He is easy to understand and makes his points clear. Definitely read the book because he pulls questions from there that don't come up in lectures. Homeworks aren't bad and he answers questions on them.

One of the best professors I've had here. Very accessible lectures that are very specific and clean. He gives great examples, the homeworks are very fair and based on the lectures, and he is a really nice guy.

He is very comprehensive in his lectures, makes sure that his students understand what the material is. Tests can be a little tricky with some true and false questions, but they aren't too hard. Weekly homework is straightforward and tutorial exercises are easy as long as you show up to the Friday session. Super nice guy and seems to enjoy class.

He's a nice enough guy, but I didn't learn that much from the lectures - I mostly relied on the textbook. The homework is short and good practice. The tutorials are the worst, very hard to understand, and TAs are useless - not his fault but doesn't help.

His lectures and slides are very boring. Black text on a white background. Bullet points with sentences. He talks, you listen. Problem sets are not bad but they take some time and effort. You learn a lot if you can force yourself to stay engaged in lectures, which is not always easy.

Professor Dunne is an excellent professor. Very clear lectures and assignments, and he leaves nothing to the imagination regarding what he expects from you in the course. He really cares a lot for his students and is willing to go the extra mile to ensure their success.

Dunne is great if you already know the course material. However, I did not have any experience with the material before the class, and he looked down on me the entire semester. I went into his office hours asking for help on specific questions and he just said "do the readings." Incredibly disrespectful to me; treated me as if I was an infant.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Dunne is a great guy who really cares about helping everyone out. I've now had him for two classes and he's known my name since the first week or so of the first class. His classes are definitely lecture heavy but he talks with enthusiasm and clear knowledge of the subject so it is rarely boring. I'd definitely recommend him!

Dunne was a good professor. I think he relied too heavily on the supplemental book required. But he explained the concepts very well. Sometimes he can be funny here and there in class, but generally he's mainly interested in the stock market & the likes. He's incredibly smart and can't wait to retire :) I recommend taking him if you have the choice
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: I like Prof. Dunne so far. He has a lot of office hours so if you need help, hes accessible. He is also a very personable teacher and tries to learn the srudents names which I always appreciate. The homework and tests are very manageable. Prof. Dunne does a good job of communicating the material and is very good at answering questions.
ratingTags_Rating: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: His logic class is brutal. The midterm and final aren't worth a lot of your grade but are extraordinarily difficult. You will likely be unprepared for them. His lectures are very difficult to digest, and the homeworks can often be very difficult. However, he holds times to work on these homeworks with him or a TA, which are very helpful.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Dr. Franks earnestly cares about his class, but he oftentimes goes on tangents that take up more than half of the class. There are three papers to write, but they determine your entire grade. There's no pressure while writing them, but if you don't take them seriously, you will not get the grade you probably deserve.

Very sweet and caring teacher. She really cares and tries to make the content engaging. As long as you put effort into the textbook homework and participate in class, you'll do well. She's on the student's side and tries to help us out (like giving us hints for what to study for tests). I highly recommend Profe Navia.
Not the most helpful lectures, but she is very kind and interesting.

Overall a good professor. The only noteworthy negatives are that she does not necessarily answer questions well and can get frustrated if students are not understanding the things she is teaching. It is pretty easy to get an A-/B+ but I would say hard to get an A.

Professor Navia really cares about her students and takes the time to make sure everyone is on the same page. I definitely recommend her class. She also spoke mostly in English, which was appreciated.

I love Professor Navia! 100% recommend. She's very sweet and caring toward her students and a great teacher. She taught the class in English too, with some things spoken in Spanish. Very detailed in her explanations and lectures, and tests were fair.

Kim is a very nice professor. She's kind of strange and laughs at her own jokes a lot. Her class is easy though. Would recommend. The class itself was fairly boring but she allowed computers so I just went on my computer the whole time and got an A still. You had to go to 4 liturgies outside of class. She did not give a compensating day off.

Class is a lot of work especially if you have no background in coding in Python. There are LONG homework assignments due every Sunday, and the grading TAs are not the same as the TAs that hold office hours. Lots of readings on Perusall in the beginning. Otherwise easy A if you do the busywork, and exams are not difficult.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: Truly incredible and so inspiring to girls in computer science and tech related fields. She really cares about your individual learning and is available for help, just ask for it! People tend to say she goes too fast or grades harsh, but those are also the people that don't pay attention or engage in class. Pay attention and you'll  do great!

Professor Kumar is really great. She does give a decent amount of homework, as there usually is not enough time to cover the "participation" assignments in class so that must be done before the next class along with the homework. In class she generally programs for the entire time as she explains all of the examples. She's very caring and flexible.

Shreya is one of the worst professors I have ever had. Spends way too much time going over useless concepts, and does a terrible job of explaining difficult topics. Shreya gives little to no resources for exams, and frequently laughs while explaining how hard the tests are going to be. Overall, make sure to avoid Shreya at all costs.

Attendance is 10% of your grade, which stinks because you learn nothing from lecture. Overall the class is fine (for paradigms) and an easy A because it's homework and the tests were open note online (maybe just bc covid tho), but I exclusively learned from doing the homework and just zoned out in class.

Dr. Kumar is SO intelligent and experienced in her work and you can clearly tell in the way she helps her students and the assigned work she has you do. The projects and homeworks she assigns help you understand the course material soo well if you enjoy the topics, plus she's an incredibly inspirational person all around and really easy to talk to
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Group projects--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: She did her best, I think, but her lectures were boring and not particularly helpful. Her homework and project assignment documents weren't particularly clear. Overall, not a *bad* professor, but wouldn't take her again if it can be avoided.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Shreya is da goat!!! Great professor who truly goes out of her way to engage with her students on an individual basis. Her clarity is top-notch, too!

I agree strongly with the other review for this class. I'll add that she gave a "take-home" final exam that was pretty much straight essay questions, and she had the nerve to say it could be finished in class time. I've had arts/letters essay exams that took less time - people have other classes they have to attend while trying to finish it.

Actually one of the worst classes and worst professors I've ever had. I strongly felt the need to register her onto RateMyProfessors just to give her this review. I genuinely don't understand how she is still teaching sometimes. Her lectures can be found online sometimes and she is absolutely awful at explaining even the simplest concepts.

Your entire grade is determined by only your midterm and final. If you do poor on one there goes your grade. He also can move you up or down two full letter grades based on "participation" but in reality it is a way of control over your grade. Watch out for this course! You have no idea your grade until it comes out on your transcript.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: My favorite class that I've taken at Notre Dame. Professor Valenzuela is incredibly knowledgeable about so many world events. Great opportunity to gain a better perspective of the world.
his class is not entertaining and its just him talking

This is the least organized professor I have ever had. No rubrics. He still has yet to give us any feedback on anything and it's November. Our class started with 15 kids and has been cut in half because of how unorganized he is. No conversation. He assigns an absurd amount of reading every week, but never gives any guide to understanding it.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: Took him on word that his class was an easy University Seminar. Minimal writing for a seminar (not sure how it counted as one) which was fine by me (science major)! He is EXTREMELY knowledgeable in history of all types. Very relaxed atmosphere, and get to read the Times as "homework". Good discussion of many issues. Easy, fun seminar of learning.
He was a nice person and offered extra credit. He had us do homework in groups, which helped to make sure no one fell behind. His lectures were sometimes hard to follow.

Prof. Kraus gives clear lectures to explain the readings and is good at clarifying points of confusion. Most of her assignments are short papers on key concepts. Her exams are pretty straightforward. This class was a good foundation for understanding the history of philosophy.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Amazing professor! He's great at starting class discussions and makes you think about the texts you're reading from multiple perspectives. The workload was reasonable and the tests/papers were focused on making you think about prominent themes rather than memorization. He's an engaging lecturer and values student input.

Professor Griffith is one of the best professors at Notre Dame. Extremely funny and engaging speaker who combines his professional knowledge in a way that is still accessible to a first-semester freshman. The class itself has a few case studies that are a little onerous but other than that the exams are pretty straightforward.

I'm really happy I had Griffith for marketing! He is a tough grader on case studies and the presentation, but his entertaining and passionate lectures, and industry experience, make up for it. He also discusses companies that are relevant to us (Chick fil A, Amazon, Disney), connecting the content to our lives and making the class more engaging.

Makes the class really entertaining with humor & personal anecdotes. Tries hard to make even the dull material fun. You have to participate once per class but he provides a lot of easy chances. The tests are pure memorization from the slides, but not too hard if you are diligent about it. Tough grader with presentations and case studies but fair.

Genuinely nice guy.  Showed compassion for my situation and helped me through it.  Fair but tough grader on papers.  Lecture heavy, but sense of humor helps make class interesting.  Brings years of industry experience to the classroom.  Was planning a career in another discipline, but this course made me reconsider and switch to marketing.

Griffith is a wonderful professor who makes sure all of his lectures are engaging. He pulls excellent examples for all of the topics he is talking about, and is truly an expert in his field.
For this class, keep in mind that participation matters (but he makes it really easy to do so!) and the tests are mostly memorization.

Tries to engage the class with humor and real world anecdotes.  Seems to enjoy what he does.  Lecture-heavy class that covers A LOT of material.  Has high standards for grading, especially on the case study projects.  If you're willing to work hard, you can learn a lot about marketing from Professor Griffith.
Fantastic at answering questions.  Genuinely funny.  I'm not a marketing major, but I enjoyed this course much more than I expected, largely because of him.

Professor Griffith is a swell guy, but the class was definitely tough with him. The midterms were pretty much just memorization, and he can sometimes fly through lectures. The group projects felt out of my control, as my grade usually fell a bit due to the other members. I wouldn't say to not take this class, but be prepared to work

Wow, I really loved Professor Griffith. He was a tough grader at certain points, and his exams required a lot of studying, but I learned more in this class than I have in any other class at ND so far. I loved his lecture style and use of personal anecdotes and visual/auditory examples to increase understanding. Great class and professor. Take him.

Each class was just one lecture after the next. Midterms are solely memorization. Ur only other grades are group projects and a final exam. So if you get a bad group you're screwed. I worked really hard for this class and got my first B. The amount of effort you put into this class is not reflected by ur grade. I highly DO NOT RECOMMEND taking him.

Griffith is a good choice if you are INTERESTED in marketing, but he is one of the harder professors. In a typical class, he gives a lecture for the entirety of the period. Make sure you ask questions. There are 4 case studies done in groups worth 20% (graded toughly) and teammates are randomly assigned. Lastly, the final is only application based.

Exams are heavily based on memorization. The final exam is application-based, but a cheat sheet is allowed. There are about 4 case study group projects which are not bad. He has a lot of real-world experience and he integrates that into the course which is really nice. Lectures consist of going over the textbook chapter he asks you to read.

Scott was entertaining and funny. Nice guy. For tests, you will have to memorize 400 slides or 1000 for the final. Lots of memorizing lists. 2 midterms and a final. Also, 4 fairly large group projects and an individual presentation. Projects will be a pain if your assigned group is lazy. More work than other marketing classes.

Professor Griffith is a very entertaining lecturer and really is able to engage his students in class. Although he is not necessarily easier than the other principles of marketing professors, he is a great option for people who want to major in marketing. He worked in marketing for decades and has a lot of stories and insight to give.

I took Intro to Biocomputing with Dr. Jones and really enjoyed it. He had us read through the lessons before class and had supplemental lectures and practice problems during class. Dr. Jones is approachable, explains the concepts well, and his office hours were helpful the few times I went. If you do all the assigned work it's not hard to get an A.

Class was fairly easy, and mostly covered by AP Bio. The class was online, so it was easy to get distracted and zone out. But the notes were posted afterward for easy review. The tests accurately reflected the difficulty of material taught in class. Group project was frustrating (as are all) due to uneven quality of work but still good for review.

Dr. Jones is great. I've taken 3 different classes from him and gotten an A in each. If you put in the work, you will get an A. He is also really approachable and willing to sit down with you to help you understand any of the material. I highly recommend his courses.
ratingTags_Rating: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria--GROUP PROJECTS

comment_Rating: While Dr. Jones still needs to improve his test writing skills, it's obvious that he cares about his students and about what he's teaching
There is a lot of work, but it's all very worthwhile. He is very available to help students. Class participation is encouraged, and the lectures are very engaging.

Professor Jones is a good instructor, especially for those interested in Aquatic Ecology or the Environmental Sciences. Labs are easy: no write ups and you pretty much just play in the lakes on campus most of the time. Tests are easy and straightforward, everything that's on the tests is in the powerpoints. Friendly guy.

Professor Jones is terrible at teaching.  No amount of studying will allow you to get an A in this class not only because he's so incompetent but because his tests are so poorly and ambiguously written and graded.  Jones himself is an inconsiderate and awkward person, and does not care about students. The lab is also a joke, and a lot of work.

Professor Serrano is a very intelligent chemist. However, he seems to be either unable/unwilling to translate his skills toward teaching undergraduates. The homework assignments are unnecessarily difficult, and he sounds like he would rather be anywhere else when lecturing. His only saving graces are the easy exams and plenty of extra credits.

This statistics course was not the hardest. The class was boring and attendance was mandatory, but you could tell Professor Roya gave it her all. She really cares about her students, and the material is not the most difficult. The tests can be a bit confusing, and the tutorial is can be annoying, but overall she was an amazing professor.

Moasser did a great job explaining the material and preparing for tests. It's a hard course, so you'll need to study out of class. MAKE SURE TO GO TO LECTURES. If you showed up to class every time, you thought he was a good teacher, and if you didn't, he wasn't. His lectures can be boring at times, but he is a very sweet and amazing teacher/person.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Moasser is easily one of my favorite professors in the College of Science. Makes every effort to assist students in and out of class. Very common for him to make lectures in stories so that they are easier to grasp. Tests are very similar to practice exam, utilize problem sets as extra practice. Would highly recommend.

Prof. Moasser is an absolutely amazing person and prof. He's always willing to help and wants everyone to do well and understand the material. There were 6 major lab reports due over the semester and were REALLY time consuming (DON'T WAIT TIL THE NIGHT BEFORE!) but overall manageable. TAs gave good feedback and were quite generous with grades.

I love Moasser. He is such a kind and caring professor. His beginning of lab lectures can get a little boring and his answers to your questions are always really long, but he always wants to make sure you understand the material. On the last day of lab we did watercolors and he complemented everyone's art.

I love this man!! He is absolutely one of the greatest professors at ND. He is very inspirational and his lectures are good. He is very passionate and a person that is easy to talk to during office hrs.
He is one of the kindest and smartest professor I have had on this campus! Highly recommended!

I've had Moasser twice now for two chemistry courses. He has been a great and thorough explainer of concepts that are difficult to learn. Extremely kind and considerate, he genuinely wants every student to succeed in his class. His tests are very straightforward and fair, not designed to trick or "catch" students off guard. I highly recommend him.

Expanding on my previous rating. His class notes are on the chalk board, and Parker writes so fast and small that half the class is taken up by students having to ask what something is or correcting his mistakes. His test reviews were inefficient. Homework that was correct was marked wrong. He taught all of Eigen values/vectors/decomp in one day.

If I could rate Parker Edwards at a 0, I would. He is the worst professor that I have taken at Notre Dame. There is no doubt that he is a smart guy, but he is terrible at conveying this in any way. He's unavailable to meet if you have classes during office hours. He doesn't test on what he covers in class. He's bad at communicating with students.

This man is truly tragic! Do not take his class. It is a crime that he is teaching an applied math class. Be prepared to memorize definitions and theorems. He once told us if we don't properly punctuate our definitions, he will take off "a few points." Seems like a nice guy, but truly would rate a 0/5 if I could.
Very interesting class, learned a lot!

This class was the best class I took at Notre Dame in relation to how much I use the information taught in my job after school. Viva is an amazing professor especially if you take the time to get to know her. Don't take this class if you are looking for an easy credit - you will work hard but it pays off.
Far and away the most valuable of all my classes.  I regularly use the framework for problem solving and it has made me a better employee and manager.

Viva is absolutely a star. Took the course as an elective in the EMBA program; wish I'd had a chance to take it in its more-intensive iteration through the regular MBA program. Absolutely, unquestionably, and unequivocally brilliant, and equally genuine. If you're not up to the challenge of staying with her, you should either shut up or stay home.

The worst teacher I had in all of business school, by far.  I felt like she was trying to prove that she was smarter than the class, which she obviously was because she was the professor.  And I felt like she was in competition with us; trying to show she was better than us.  Bottom line is she's weird and she wears beige clothes every day.
One of the best professors I ever had!!! Not only a professor butshe could also be a great friend and mentor in life!
My favorite instructor in all of business school.
Brilliant professor who challenges you to learn more but is there every step of the way to offer guidance and advice!
Prof was super demanding but was the best prof I have ever had.  Also, the most approachable  prof I have ever had.  Real world expertise finally used in class.
Interesting class.  Teacher is demanding, but the covered material is self-serving.
Problem solving is a true beast of a class. But mandatory. 90% of it is just surviving until mod 2.
No Comments
No Comments
I've taken multiple classes with Olivier Morel and I continue thinking about in-class discussions long after the classes have ended. Well worth taking.

Olivier had the opportunity to make this class very interesting and relevant but instead it makes me want to blow my brains out. He talks in circles and never arrives at a final point. He expects everyone to be as knowledgable about films and current events. He expects us to spend 8-10 hours preparing for this class outside of class & is unhelpful.

A brilliant and caring professor. This seminar was difficult at times, but in the best kind of way where you leave as a much better questioner and writer (huge for law school). She took complex readings and presented them in a way which we could understand as undergrads, while using the socratic method in a fun way. Take her class!!!!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Had Prof. Bambrick for her Comparative Constitutionalism Junior Seminar. The class was really interesting and the readings weren't bad at all for a political science class. She's very knowledgable about her subject and does a really good job explaining complex legal and theoretical topics to students.

An overall amazing professor! She is so kind and makes everyone feel welcome. The material is somewhat difficult depending on the person you are, but she teaches it in a way that students are better able to understand the material. Papers are graded a bit tough, but overall she gives amazing feedback and wants to help you learn!
Professor Bohrer is a great lecturer! She chose very interesting readings and explained them well at an introductory level. Make sure to do the readings and you should do well in her class.
Great professor! Really cares about his students and wants you to succeed in college.

Had him for American politics freshman year. Wasn't really a fan tbh. Wanted to make his exams "cheat-proof" cause of Covid (he made them harder), when he could've just had us take them in person (the class was in person except for exams).  Exams were tough, and only had open-ended questions.  Nice guy though and I hope he has a nice retirement.

Best professor at Notre Dame. Truly passionate about teaching, and any class you take with him will give you a truly unique insight into the subject that other professor's would not produce. Each class I have taken with him, although somewhat more challenging than the typical polisci class, leaves me feeling I learned what truly mattered.

This class was great! We had to read a lot of different books, but Kaplan made sure to choose interesting ones. You must attend lectures, and if you pay attention exams should be easy. He sends out a very thorough study guide before each test. He is super kind and cares about his students success. He shares his lecture slides with students.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I absolutely loved Prof. Kaplan's class. Though it was slow at times, he was always so excited to share his thoughts on the readings (especially Thucydides). DO THE READINGS and listen closely to his tips and notes during class and you will do just fine.

Super kind, clearly is passionate about the material, and makes the lectures both funny and engaging. Took his Political Theory course for my second philosophy credit and absolutely loved it. Be prepared to do a lot of the readings to stay on top of things!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I have taken Prof Kaplan for American Politics and Political Theory. He is a great thinker and always provokes interesting thoughts on the subject matter. I would recommend him to anyone, and he is a very nice, approachable man. He is a tough grader. Learn the content the way he wants it learned.

Truly an awesome professor. He fostered my interest in the subject matter and is actually the reason I am now doing a Political Science double major. Material itself really isn't that hard and neither are the tests or papers he just grades very harshly. Expect a B or less if you put in normal effort.
extremely nice guy. grading is a bit difficult and there is quite a bit of reading.
Long lectures and subjective grading. Nice enough guy.
Definitely one of the best professors I've had. Makes you work for the grade, but he's always accessible and has a ridiculous amount of office hours.

Best professor of my college career.  Helpful, kind, easy to get to know and very good at making difficult material easier to understand.  Don't let your four years go by without taking a class with him.

Prof. Kaplan is the nicest professor I've ever had. He really cares about his students. He had our seminar over for BBQ during the semester and even the next year. He's very helpful and will grant extensions if you need them. If never seemed bothered by anyone being late, but I'd go just out of respect for him. Exam was a research paper, wasn't bad

He is very knowledgeable. However, I found his lectures very hard to follow. He doesn't use slides and he assumes that his students have a high level of background knowledge. You must do all the readings to do well, but I feel like his readings weren't introductory level, and would've been more appropriate to assign to an intermediate class.

Very very easy class. Based on four exams, homework with answers in textbook. Prof LoSecco is very kind and tries to engage the class, but it can get a bit boring just because of the topic. He does try and I appreciated that. Just read the textbook and you'll get an A+/

Prof. LoSecco was a decent professor in my cosmology course but his lectures can oftentimes be boring. Grading is broken into two exams, a book report, and weekly quizzes. He gives a good amount of extra credit as well. Overall an easy course and moderately interesting but the lectures were a bit lackluster.

Professor LoSecco was great! He is very passionate about physics and makes it accessible to non-STEM majors. He is very kind and funny. He can be hard to hear at times during lecture, but as long as you keep up with the readings this shouldn't be a problem. This is an amazing class to take if you need to fulfill your science requirement.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Caring

comment_Rating: Lim's class is very hard if you have not taken calculus before. He expects prior knowledge in the subject and can be rude when you ask for help. He isn't super accessible. He is good at simplifying complex concepts, but spends too much time on proofs that are not on the exams rather than working through examples. His class is not worth the 8am.
Goes super fast and is so hard to understand. Would never take again. Expect to put in 12+ hours a week of work for this one class.

Such a good teacher. Goes fast, but once you get the hang of his pace, you learn so much. If you need to take Calc B, I would try to get Professor Lim bc he's the course head. Tests are easier than the homework so most students get good scores.
Focuses on learning math for your career, rather than memorizing formulas. Overall, my fave teacher.

Most degrading professor ever. If you do bad, rather than him working thorgh where you went wrong, he questions your career choice and ask whether or not you're capable of pursing that said career for yourself. I'm sturggling in the class due to me having no experience of Calc in high school. He made me cry and I'm never taking him again.

One of worst classes I've ever had; way too much homework, so time consuming and so much harder then tests. Teacher who is bad at teaching; very smart guy but cannot teach an intro course. Please don't take this class with Lim, it's so time consuming and not easy to understand even if you took BC in high school.
He's just great. Love the accent
Best math professor at Notre Dame!!

Professor Lim is very knowledgable about calculus. He also tries to add in humor to his lectures. Be ready to spend a significant amount of time on Mobius homework. But, if you can do the homework with no problem, then you will be fine on tests. The tests are very similar to the review sheets done in class.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Arthur Lim was the only reason that got me to do calculus at 8am in the morning. He tends to go through lectures very fast, and learning is dependent on notes. There's a lot of homework assigned in Mobius which you should do ahead of time. He does his best to explain things. Also, he has an attendance sheet and will notice if you aren't showing up.
While sometimes tough, Lim is very good at explaining hard topics.

Professor Lim is very knowledgable about Calculus. I had him for Calc B. He brings lots of energy to class each day. The tests are pretty much straightforward. The homework can get annoying quickly. But, just do it, because it will help in the long run. This class if difficult, so it is important to review material outside of class.

Lim is hilarious! Love this man! Lots of homework, but it helps so much if you do it. Tests are straightforward and EXACTLY like the in-class review that he does. This man explained calculus so well. You'll do well in this class if you do all the homework and ask for help when you need it.

Professor Lim is the course chair for Calculus A meaning he assigns/ creates all the homework and tests for the course. The Mobius homework is absurd. They take me a minimum of 2-3 hours (for ten questions), and talking to other peers in the class, this is pretty standard. The questions are extremely difficult, unrelated, and incredibly frustrating
Brings the energy to class. Explains difficult topics well. Difficulty score is just because it's calculus which is hard no matter who you have. Good grading system.

I switched from the Calc I-II track to the Calc A-B track. It is essential to complete the review sheets and practice problems as soon as Lim sends them. I found this class especially frustrating because there are many mistakes on the solution sets and practice exams. Class times are also not long enough. Overall, I would recommend taking Calc II.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Test heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Prof. Lim was always honest with the class. He started off saying that Calc B would be a lot of work, and he was 100% right. You have lots of practice problems for homework, but I thought it was always useful in prep. for exams. Do the summary sheets and go to office hours! He really wants you to understand and master concepts rather than memorize.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Prof. Lim is the best Calc A/B professor at ND. He's knowledgeable, super funny in lecture, and really cares about his students. He set up extra tutoring specifically for Calc B this semester and is very helpful in office hours. If you are struggling, reach out and he is happy to help. Show up to his class and engage if you can and you will be ok.
SO hard to communicate with and disregards any concerns you bring to him. Crazy Crazy amount of homework - impossible to do it all. terrible, never ever again never
Tons of homework.  Lectures have mistakes and very few practice problems.

Very good at explaining difficult material and an amazing communicator. Attendance is mandatory and he takes it almost every class but a very nice professor and knows how to teach very well. Cares about his students and the subject. Take his class if you have the chance.

Funniest professor I've ever had. He often goes off on tangents about proofs that you don't need to know but the exams are fair and don't cover the proofs. Challenging class but the drop policy is very helpful.

Class is set up very poorly for an introductory calc class required by social science majors. As someone who did well in high school calc the math in this class is much harder and much of the difficulty in this course comes from the insane amount of homework. My tip to anyone: study the reviews heavily because they are similar to how the tests are.

Was a pretty decent teacher. Not really that great if you dont have a background in calculus tho. The midterms were pretty straightforward if you paid attention in class. However, he made the final ridiculously hard compared to the midterms so beware of some curveballs

Homework had absolutely no relation to class material or tests and quizzes, I had a TA who made errors in every practice problem, and Lim did not teach any sections. If you dont have to take this class for your major DO NOT TAKE IT!!!

He was not my actual professor, but was the course head for Calc B. The main issue was the construction of the lectures. There were barely any practice problems in the lectures. This means u learn a concept, but u dont actually learn how to apply it. By the end of the semester I was only going to the tutorial because the lectures were useless.

Prof. Lim brings lots of energy and passion to the lectures, and at the time of writing this review is definitely the professor you want to have for Calc A. Even if he's only teaching an 8AM, his passion for and familiarity with the material more than makes up for the early class time. I advise doing everything you can to get Lim's Calc A section.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Very energetic and makes morning lectures enjoyable. If you are taking Calculus A or B, this is the teacher you want.

Very organized but overrated. His teaching style didn't match mine too well but I understand why so many people like him. I often had to teach myself the material because the lectures didn't help me that much. Would still recommend because not all students learn the same way.
Professor Lim is a gem at 8 am in the morning. Most of the time I wouldn't go to lecture, but the days I did go, it was because I knew that he would be happy to have a fuller class!
Cares a lot and is willing to help students outside of class. Can take you through a proof or long way at times instead of just teaching the "how to." Very funny!
Professor Lim is by far the best calculus A teacher- he is very passionate about math and is very willing to help students who need it.
Amazing math teacher, lots of homework, really funny guy. Definitely hope for him if you're taking Calc

Professor Favorite is an AMAZING accounting teacher, super funny and gets to know each student in the class. Though the material may be difficult, he does his best to make it fun. The exams are difficult but manageable. No outside homework outside of class, just suggested assignments to become familiar with concepts.

Favorite's a funny guy and actually made me somewhat enjoy Accounting II. Tests are kinda hard and time-consuming, but the curve should help you at the end. Show up to class or else you'll miss problems that will be on the test. Reading the textbook isn't mandatory. Homework is light and easy.

Prof Favorite mainly teaches through the PPTs. Pretty light workload of average 20-30 minutes each week; exams are based on his lectures, but can be a little long. Pay attention in class and study powerpoint slides to do well (no need to read textbook). He knows every student's name and takes attendance. Very fun prof who does casual Fridays.

Doesn't really go back over examples if students are confused. We had to beg for a study guide Nice guy, but has a seriously outdated teaching style. He curved immensely at the end, but because we all struggled so much. Curves are weird, it's kind of an excuse for teachers who have absurdly difficult courses. You'll survive in the end.

He just reads off slides from Pearson. They're more than often arithmetically incorrect, but he doesn't bother correcting them. Glides through topics and doesn't explain them.
Gives a ton of homework throughout the semester, and each homework takes a few hours at least.
Not the best course to enroll in, wouldn't recommend anyone.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Bern is a real life audio book that reads off of 100+ unorganized slides. He did not do any arithmetic on the whiteboard throughout the entire course. You're better off taking an online class. His Pearson assignments take about 3 hours to complete. Everyone fell asleep during lectures because he made no sense.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Gao's notes are hard to understand and he rarely writes words. I found myself having to watch youtube lectures after each class because I basically understood nothing from him.

Professor Gao is a very direct and concise teacher which makes learning complex material, such as organic chemistry, much easier. I would STRONGLY recommend that, after each lecture, you should go over the lecture material and ensure that you understand the topics at hand thoroughly. In this class (regardless of professor) it is easy to fall behind
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: I took him for Orgo 1, and I thought he did a good job at teaching. Orgo is hard, so no matter who teaches it, so be warned, but Gao was clear and comprehensive. He also did practice problems that helped see what the reactions did in real time, instead of just doing a powerpoint. Whatever you do, MAKE SURE TO DO THE EXTRA READINGS
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Better than Helquist
Nothing can be learned from his class.

Professor Gao often says in class he fears that his students take away nothing from attending his lectures. His fear undoubtedly became true for myself and the rest of the class, maybe except for a graduate student in his own research group.

He is the worst professor ever. He has strong accent. Its very hard to understand his words. He treat student never equal. He never give student time to ask. His smile makes people uncomfortable. He is stubborn.

hes so sweet! lots of readings but nothing unmanageable. we got a couple of quizzes (but we knew based on syllabus when they were coming), small individual projects, and 2 papers. classes are normally lectures + discussions so just participate and you'll be good! he's very passionate about philosophy and thats clear in his lectures :)

While Professor Thomas was monotonous at times, he enjoys what he does and highly values students' input. The readings were theoretically dense, but you could skip them and not miss anything. His class has 3 papers (5+pgs), which he grades very easily. If you can get through the mundane lectures, you have an A.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Thomas is hilariously eccentric. The material (Lit USEM on Modernity) is somewhat dry, and honestly, Professor Thomas is a little mundane as well. But he is a very sweet and caring guy and when it is time to write papers, he grades fairly easily. Readings definitely enhanced my reading comprehension. Strange but memorable class overall.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Hilarious--So many papers

comment_Rating: Dr Liu was awesome! I learned a lot. She covered not only how to perform Bayesian analysis and computation but also why. I highly recommend her class.  I usually don't rate my professors here, but I accidentally learned about a rating of 1 and don't think it represents Dr Liu's teaching. I could easily find another student who rates her class 5/5.

He's awesome. Prof. Jech tells a lot of stories, and for the most part they relate to the material, but they're so entertaining. I took him for USEM Phil, there were 3 total assignments and one final paper. There are a bunch of readings and they're pretty difficult, but Jech is very good at explaining them and getting to the bigger picture.

Great, quirky guy. Knew he would go on tangents so he had a student time them and cut him off so he could get through the material. He cares a lot about his students. You have to read, but definitely take his class.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Hilarious

comment_Rating: Easy class, but I'm not confident that I learned a whole lot about Archaeology. The class was hyper-focused on cult archaeology and the professor's own research (which is understandable to an extent). The only grades are the papers you submit, so make sure to follow the guidelines for each one. As long as you do that, you'll earn a good grade.

I had Harms for BPS, so the instructor doesn't matter very much. However, Harms gave long, boring lectures about how to work with a team at the start of the semester. He was a nice guy though. It was just tough to sit through those boring lectures during the first three weeks.

This teacher grades in a completely unreasonable way. She has no experience teaching and not only does she lack teaching in class, as she never contributes to why the things we read for class are meaningful, she is also unclear and grades in the worst way I have ever seen. Completely unreasonable! Would never take again. Do not recommend!

Her course is not necessarily the hardest (or most interesting), but definitely this is the most frustrating and confusing course I've ever taken - because she gave you the misperception that you will get an A for the whole damn semester and then you get a much much worse grade that doesn't reflect your real effort and performance at all!!!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Super nice guy. Does his best to make the class interesting and always puts a joke up before class. Marks attendance. Lectures can be a bit dry and some days it takes a lot of effort to keep from zoning out. Overall a really great professor and would recommend!

Bill is such a great guy and is really passionate about accounting. He always starts the class off by giving a few jokes. However, he is very soft-spoken so sometimes he will put you to sleep during lecture. I would suggest reading the textbook prior to lecture to get a better understanding. But other than that, I highly recommend

Prof Fuzesi is so knowledgeable! I highly recommend her classes in the London program. She is a very nice grader, so as long as you keep up with the readings, you should do well in the class. It can be a lot of work, but the classes are definitely manageable.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Prof Tebbit is great! He is very sweet and the assignments are not very difficult. He also makes an effort to make class interesting by having multiple student breakouts during the class. The readings are not very long/difficult, and I would highly recommend staying on top of them. I would 100% take Tebbit again!

My main concern with this class is that the required films were not always easy to access. A lot of them were not available for free online. Supposedly, the library has CDs of all of them, but I heard they weren't the best audio quality. The lectures are a little bland, but Prof Reed is nice and willing to work with you if you reach out to her.

Tessa is a young professor and definitely grades harsher than a seasoned professor would. Her lectures are bland and oftentimes don't relate to the subject we are meant to be studying. She gives out very few A's, however doesn't give good feedback on assignments.

Jacob Lehman is a Grad Student that teaches Drawing I. I took drawing I with very little artistic talent because I needed a fifth class, and I absolutely loved it. The class is very low stress and there is plenty of time to complete each project. Jacob gives sufficient feedback and is really nice and supportive.

Prof. Desch is great! He is very good at leading a seminar. He helps summarize the key points of the reading for the first 20 minutes of the class, then moves into a structured discussion of the reading. He is very kind and loves to joke around. He is also very passionate and knowledgeable

I would not recommend taking him. His lectures were very disorganized and you just ended up listening to other students talk for the entire class period. He does not use slides or go over the readings. Also, he did not put any grades in for the entire semester so I had no idea what my final grade would be.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Sehnert is amazing! His lectures were very well-structured and easy to follow. He was very in tune with what the class did not understand and explained these topics more thoroughly. He is very smart and funny! His class had a good balance between lecture time and small group discussion. Overall, this was a very laidback yet informative class!

Professor Sehnert is a good professor. The course consists of reading roughly 20-30 pages per class, and then a brief lecture at the beginning of class followed by a student presentation and general discussion. The work in the class in minimal. If you need to take a political theory course, this is an easy but interesting option.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Anne Roycroft is the best Moreau teacher! I had the privilege of having Anne as my Moreau teacher and she definitely made the college transition easier. Every week she brought food for someone's birthday, took us on field trips, or offered to drive us to places if we were without access to a car. She is an incredibly kind and generous woman!!
Awesome professor, great teaching style. Explains content well. Willing to be flexible with office hours. Tests can be difficult, but he lets you make up points.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: She'll be there if you need help, if you pay attention in class you will be fine

so far i really like professor mapes. she does speak fairly quickly in class, & it took awhile for me to get used to the speed of her lectures. i have her for calc 3, and she makes great analogies to help us understand how to visualize the math that we are doing in 3d. she responds to emails quickly & encourages questions. highly recommend! :)
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Prof. Mapes made a difficult subject matter, group theory, interesting and built up intuition so that it was understandable. The course required no prior knowledge. It was very clear what was expected on the tests, and similar practice problems were given beforehand. However, it may be better to fulfill a requirement like history with your seminar.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: He is a really knowledgeable professor who cares about his students. The class is structured in an interesting way: lecture on Thursday, a bunch of readings and a 500 ish word response due Monday, and discussion on Tuesday. It is a good class, but more history than theology.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating: Very unimpressive.

Gaski’s class is not a lot of work and the tests are not too difficult. No homework, just readings and exams. However, as a person he is extremely difficult and condescending. Be aware, if you use your phone in class (he has his TA spying from the back of the room), he lowers your final grade an entire letter grade.

Prof Minor is one of the best. I recommend her to anyone. She cares about her students so much and teaches with an enthusiasm you won't find elsewhere. Building Europe is excellent for anyone remotely interested in architecture/history. Her dog Dosso is a frequent visit to class too!

Love Prof. Minor. Her lectures are interesting and made me want to get an art history minor. There is a lot of reading for pre-class but its completion-based and participation matters in class. Her exams are not that bad and you write three essays. She clearly is passionate in the subject and in her field, I would highly recommend taking her class.

Professor Minor was great in gaining my attention in class. She lectured by telling stories and helped you envision the history. She assigns readings for every class and response papers for each one, so be prepared. However, she grades them on completion and is fair otherwise. You can choose which essays/papers and test prompt you want to do too!

Dr. Dhaliwal is the nicest person and deserves all the flowers. The material was challenging, but he didn't mind revisiting topics in class or talking more outside of class. We had the option of taking quizzes or taking a final exam. He was open to adjusting readings if most of the class was having a particularly stressful/heavy week.

Bechler was bomb!!! His class was super straight forward and most of his exams was just vocab from lectures. Make quizlets and you'll ace the class. He's a young guy who's relateable and funny. If you take this class with anyone else you aren't doing it right--- it's Bechler or nothing.
I loved Prof Bechler. He was relatable and made lectures fun with good examples. He seems very excited to work in this topic which adds value to his lectures. Very manageable class and work load.

My class was entirely reading and writing based, which is fine. However, he chose not to grade almost all of the writing assignments we did. As a result, my grade did not even change from fall break to exam week. Bad grader. Too much homework. Over 35 pages of writing all semester only for him to grade about 5 of those pages. Impossible to get an A
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--So many papers

comment_Rating: He's a very caring and nice guy. I took his USEM about America and the World and we only had 4, 2-page papers, and 3, 5-page papers which for a USEM class that is supposed to be focused on writing, it really didn't feel like that much and he grades pretty easy with good feedback. The final was challenging but it was open note so that was nice.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: He's a very nice guy and is super passionate about Notre Dame. He's the perfect Moreau prof. It is super easy to talk in class (even as an introvert I feel comfortable talking in class). He grades well, so if you put in the effort and try to connect with the material you will do fine. He truly cares about his students.

Dr. Morris is one of the most difficult and disrespectful professors I have ever had. Expect to get out of class late every time and for him to yell at you during weekly meetings. Other than his disagreeability, the class is very easy and a cool experience. Great class, awful professor. His poor attitude does not make the immense workload worth it.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Raiha is one of the coolest professors I've ever had at ND. His lectures for sports economics were really great. We had a final capstone for the class, but he gave us a lot of support throughout the semester and many options to complete, with varying degrees of difficulty. He is honestly a great guy. I would easily take the class again.

Professor Raiha is among the mosted skilled and gifted lecturers at Notre Dame, and you truly feel that you have walked away from each lecture having learned something. His Money, Banking, and Mortgage Markets class is incredibly well-structured, and it integrates much of what I have learned in other finance and economics classes.

Very passionate about the subject and does a good job at explaining concepts. The workload is light with one homework assignment a week and only ten total. These are easy points as homework is completion and they double as great study material. Exams are manageable as you are given two front and back cheat sheets in addition to a formula sheet.

I am almost hesitant to give him such a glowing review on here as I hope to take his classes again. Guided by the spirit of Holy Cross in a political science/history crossover, Father Bill looks to give his students a baseline foundation not only in history but in analyzing texts and coming up with arguments. Father Bill is THE MAN
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: TAKE FR. BILL! He is a very interesting guy which makes for great lectures. I had him for a seminar and he led very interesting conversations. He also genuinely cares about his students and requires 1 on 1 meetings with him to get to know you. This is something none of my other professors have done. Live, laugh, love Fr. Bill.

Father Bill is AMAZING. And I am not exaggerating. I don't think there was a single class period where he didn't have the entire class' attention. You can tell by his lectures he's an elite professor who has done in-depth research in what he is teaching. An amazing personality and a great, kind-hearted man. He's a MUST HAVE professor at Notre Dame.

Father Bill has the biggest personality out of anyone I've met. His lectures are entertaining and informative, but there is definitely a strong conservative bias in everything he says. Although his lectures have a conservative bias, the readings he assigns are fairly balanced. Show up to class and participate in discussion and you will be fine!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Hilarious

comment_Rating: Moderately funny, very convinced of his views and the great dead white men he likes.

There is something to be said for learning Australian history from an Australian. Brilliant, personable man who brought such enthusiasm and joy to every class lecture. He seems to be the type of instructor who genuinely cares about each student he meets. Plus, the video on cane toads is a must-watch.
Great guy, great prof.  Nice to see that there are still some brilliant AND Catholic Holy Cross priests around.  Take his classes.

Professor Webber makes a difficult class seem manageable. The individual processes are simple, almost obvious sometimes, but the problems can be so time consuming and difficult to read that the hardest part about the class is time management. Do every practice problem, test, anything as many times as you can to get used to doing algebra so fast.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Professor Ocobock's classes are overall just really fun. I took him for Global Africa and he cares more about you learning something new than trying to achieve a certain grade. The workload can be very inconsistent though and you jump from doing nothing to reading full books out of nowhere, but it's manageable. No homework due for lecture days.

Mr. Ocobock was one of the best teachers I have ever had. He's a super funny and all-around good guy. He jokes around and makes the class a lot of fun. You have to really do well on the papers, but it is overall easy to get an A- or a B+. It's trickier to break through to that perfect A but not impossible if you're confident in your writing. 10/10.

Professor Ocobock is hands down my favorite professor I have had at Notre Dame so far. He is super funny and brings a sense of humor to class discussions that can be based on rather dark readings. He is also not a super tough grader, but you really do have to put effort into your writing regardless because it is 75% of your grade.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Knowledgeable teacher who is flexible with attendance if you are overloaded with work. A lot of reading and a few papers but you'll learn a lot.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Respected

comment_Rating: Prof. Fusezi is a really enthusiastic teacher and she truly cares a lot about political science. She can be cold and strict at times, but she's a pretty easy grader and if you come to her with any concerns she is very open to helping you.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Prof Gurel is such a kind and caring professor. She is very helpful in office hours and knowledgable about her topic. Also is very positive about students' opinions! Lecture could be a bit dull at times but was overall interesting. She truly wants her students to succeed and helps them do so. I recommend her class!
Not a good class.

Professor Gurel is super young and funny, so she makes class relatable. Unfortunately, it's kinda all over the place. I liked the class but didn't like my TA - who made the discussion class portion painful.

Get ready for the most liberal class of all time. This is not exaggeration. Gurel is super nice but she cannot hide her political views in the slightest. The intro class was pretty simple, and there weren't many graded things. If you're a decent writer, you'll get a B+ or better

Her class is highly structured and structured well. However, It is so extreme that she belittles you if you aren't following the exact pattern and process she prescribes. She is extremely condescending when addressing questions, but she is sometimes helpful during office hours. Really wish I didn't have to take 3 classes with her.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Her expectations for her students are beyond what I've ever been asked. The nature of this class was to develop writing skills, yet she required well-revised formal writing for every class (500 words). She gives unclear feedback, although throughout, and grades way too hard. And just likes to listen to herself talk, and her own writing has errors.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Dr. Frymoyer is very good at teaching writing. She was much more critical of my writing than teachers in years past, which helped me a lot with developing my ideas. I will say that at some times, she was a little too critical, but this was not a super common occurrence. The class itself (Music, Gender, and Sexuality) was incredibly interesting.
I felt confused a lot of the time during Dr. Frymoyer's classes. I generally struggle with music theory, but taking her course did not help me improve my knowledge of the subject.

This seems to be Dr. Frymoyer's first semester here at ND. She clearly needs more time here, since her instruction was awful. Her lectures were meandering and confusing, and she had no clear grading criteria whatsoever. Not recommended.
Very helpful and kind; feedback is always very detailed. A little bit tough at grading, though, so an A is not easy
Great lecturer. Genius.  This is the only professor I've had who I can say actually inspires awe.

Awesome class and instructor. Felt like I learned a ton and enjoyed going to class. Really funny guy as well. Not sure if he is teaching again in future, but this was one of my favorite classes at ND. Come to class, go to office hours, and submit good work and you will get a good grade and enjoy the class tremendously. Also he is super funny.

Professor Glibetic is a super engaging and helpful professor. This was a super interesting second theology and she cares a lot about her students. Definitely is a tougher grader, but manageable if you listen and understand expectations. Readings were long and mandatory because she would randomly give reading quizzes at the start of class.

Slightly more reading that I was expecting for a required intro to Theology, but I understand she was really trying to push us to higher standards, which I appreciated. I really liked the lectures and the material. Overall, a great class.

I really enjoyed this class. If you are taking this for your second Theology requirement, just know that it is very focused on topic of women/gender in Church, so if you are interested in that like I was, you'll get a lot out of it.

Prof Glibetic challenges you to think critically. More than just learning the subject material, which I found very interesting, I felt like she was also teaching us a different, deeper and more thoughtful way to approach history and faith. I never thought I would consider a theology major, but now I am.

Arguably the most frustrating class I have ever sat through. I rate it a difficulty of 5 because of how impossible it was to stay interested in the course and how much I dreaded having to slowly rot away in my seat every class. Shockingly boring and the grading was unnecessarily rough for how little effort was put into the class by the professor.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: There is a bit more reading compared to some of the other classes, but it was interesting and Professor Glibetic challenges you to think differently about a lot of different topics. I like how she tried to be balanced and encouraged people with different views to express themselves.

Apart from the reviews here, I haven't met anyone who didn't rank this as one of their least favorite classes. Format for the midterm and final is wildly subjective, readings for the class are incredibly dry, and her lectures make 75 minutes feel like 6 hours. I struggle to find any reason you'd take this class if you had literally any other option

Extremely knowledgeable and open to any kind of discussion. Great professor for those new to religion. Attendance and participation are mandatory, and receiving an A is no easy feat. Not many assignments, but expectations are high and grading is relatively fair. Weekly reading with occasional reading quizzes which are pretty easy. Good first theo.

One of the best professors for first Theo. Reading before each class, but it is much less than others. No homework outside of one group project. Very knowledgable and a great communicator regardless of prior experience with religion. Attendance and participation are MANDATORY. One excused absence and then you go down letter grades.
ratingTags_Rating: Beware of pop quizzes--Caring--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Readings every day and occasional (random) reading quizzes. Class is great and really interesting. Participation matters! Also encourages attending outside lectures for extra credit.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Group projects--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: I would definitely recommend Prof. Glibetic for the first Theo requirement. Compared to the other Theo 1 classes this one had the least amount of work. She was very respectful of everyone's views, and although I had her for an online course, I did not feel like I knew her less than one normally would know their professor. Very personable, caring, and passionate about subject matter.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: She was a fantastic Professor, made me want to pursue a Theo minor. You have Bible readings for each class but that's really the extent of the work. Two easy quizzes, one exam, and one take home final.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Caring

comment_Rating: I had Foundations: Bibl & Hist. of Theology with Prof. Glibetic for her 1st semester teaching at ND. She is incredible. Very knowledgeable, respectful of differing views and encouraged a lot of classroom participation. This was my favorite class all semester and it's only a university requirement for me. Highly highly recommend!!

Unknown grading criteria. All feedback the whole semester was positive, 100%. Somehow ended with a B+. Syllabus was not complete by the start of the semester. Cold calls on people in class. Expected us to meet requirements not specified in his assignment. Readings can reach up to 100 pages per week. Are all the readings helpful/necessary? No.

ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: This class is entertaining, but there will be no grading criteria whatsoever. It wouldn't be a big deal if everyone made an A, but I made a B+ both semesters, and I'm not sure where my grade came from. The class is also very unorganized, so if you like order, don't take it.
