ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Really funny but not for everyone. If you're someone that likes structure, this class will stress you out a lot because it is extremely unorganized, and you'll never be 100% sure about what the homework and expectations are. No assignments were graded the entire semester, yet I didn't get an A so not entirely sure what it was based on.
funny

USEM with Dr. J was a great class. He is so smart, knows interesting facts about everything, loves to teach, and above all loves his students. SO FUNNY- you won't regret taking his class. He puts less emphasis on grades and more on learning something new and engaging in something interesting.
almost impressively bad at teaching.
He makes me confused about topics I've already learned. I'm not sure how. Seems like a nice guy but isn't assertive with his teaching.

Awesome pick for bio lab. Laid back but you learn a lot. TAs aren't tough graders, but you still need to put in the work to get an A. Rubrics for assignments are very clear. Sometimes makes lab procedure unclear but is very understanding if he messes up.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Wang is a solid professor (pun intended). For Design Tools II she does a good job of working with students on their homework and projects and is pretty funny too. Overall a great professor to have.

He is a very funny guy, really cares about his students, and is overall a great person. However, the homework is often ridiculously long, especially when it is a coding assignment. The exams are also very difficult. This class is challenging, but using his notes and examples from the book helps a lot with the homework and exams.

Professor Morris is what I imagined college professors being like. He's pretty funny, very knowledgeable, and works with students by caring about their opinions. However, his class is not easy. In order to get the most out of lecture and understand the material, you NEED to read the book. Otherwise you are screwed for his hard tests.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Test heavy

comment_Rating: This is my second review for Todd (and Mike). They are amazing. For the Advanced class, it is a lot less learning than the Intro class. The Capsim project was very fun and useful to implementing the information learned in both classes. The key is to meet with them outside of class to review strategy. They are the best.

Todd (and Mike Kitz) are simply the best. Their class has outright been my favorite at ND. I cannot say enough good things about them. The only thing is if you are looking for an easy tech elective, this might not be the one. There are a lot of group projects that require meeting. The class is pretty easy, but can be a decent amount of work

ARS Robotica is great because it is easier than a lot of other literature USEMs. There is not too much work and he does not grade super harshly but he can be weirdly picky about certain things which is annoying but he doesn't take too many points off. The classes were fine but I didn't really learn a lot. Definitely would recommend as a USEM

ARS Robotica is one of the best USEM's offered by the school. The course consists of 2 short stories and 1 book along with about 12 movies. You are given a book/movie each week to watch and write a 2 page response to a prompt he emails you. You don't do any research and he only looks to see that you thoughtfully analyzed. Much less work than others

I LOVE Ethan. He is an incredibly kind, smart, and funny person. The class I took with him was probably my favorite class I've taken at ND so far. Be ready to laugh and participate in class. Always available for extra help or just to chat about movies. I loved how he would always start class by playing piano and serenading us.

Ethan was great! He lead the tutorial sessions for my film course, and he was always well prepared with things to discuss, but also very willing to allow for the conversation to go in a different direction. He really tried to get us to think. My favorite thing was his outfits. One time he showed up to class in a Philadelphia Mummers Parade costume.

Ethan Anderson was a wonderful professor! I had him for my Tutorial section of Basics of Film & Television. His class is enjoyable, and his personality is electric and infectious. I always looked forward to the freestyle raps he did for us at the end of each class, too.

Claire is great! She was really good at contextualizing information as she used to work in PA and was really helpful in understanding the intuition behind some weird accounting principles. Claire's practice problems and homework assignments were conducive to learning the material, but in class, she taught almost directly off the slides.

An amazing professor who genuinely cares about students. She was very straightforward. The exams were challenging but there were no surprises and they were fair. Homework is optional but it really helps you to prepare for the exam.

Donovan teaches slowly and clearly, which I appreciated having no accounting experience. She is great in office hours and answers emails quickly. The exams are challenging but not impossible. There are 2 group projects, randomized groups. The hard part is the material, which isn't Donovan's fault. HW is optional but useful in practicing concepts.

She is a great professor and is very accessible outside of class if you need any help. Homework is optional, but it is extremely helpful for studying for her tests. The entire grade is essentially based on 3 tests, but the class is curved.

Good lectures, and she made Accounting 1 as entertaining as possible. My only two issues are that one chapter was taught completely over online videos and that her test roadmaps were rather cryptic compared to other classes that offer them.

Professor Donovan was a great professor. Her style of speaking was easy to follow because she spoke as if she was explaining something to young children (which makes sense because she has some of her own). The only difficult part of the class was the content itself. Do a good job of asking for help where needed and you'll succeed in the class.
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Grade comes from short daily reader responses, a few quizzes, 2 papers, midterm, and final. He provides guided note-taking handouts so studying is easier. Loved the small discussion sections. Reader responses are basically a completion grade. Interesting readings. A great first Theo no matter how much you know/don't know about Catholicism.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: While I 100% agree with the other review, I took PHYS-20220 during the summer and had a MUCH better lecturer (Dr. Becker). Dr. Wayne has horrible lectures that are usually unrelated to homeworks and exams. People prefer him because his tests are easier than the professor who teaches this course on sequence. This is a self-taught course.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: If you're a pre-professional student at Notre Dame, you'll want to take Physics I & II off sequence with Professor Wayne. He's one of those professors who you just grow to really appreciate and enjoy. His class isn't impossible but it isn't easy either. It's a perfect challenge that if you work hard enough in, you can do well in. 5/5 would rec.

Professor Anderson was incredibly helpful, easy to contact, and an engaging lecturer. I think his class was the most beneficial writing course I've taken so far. However, he insisted on displaying all his due dates in Mongolian Standard Time, which I found quite odd...

Prof. was amazing and very engaging. Eccentric and engaging guy. Looked forward to his classes and when he would read his pieces. I grew as a writer as we explored the bounds of the essay. I highly recommend taking this class, though was a bit confused when he'd show up in fairy wings "bippity, boppity, boo-ing" my head when I got a right answer.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Inspirational

comment_Rating: Professor Anderson was an exceptional writing and rhetoric teacher. His feedback was consistently insightful, helping me refine my writing skills. What stood out was his unwavering dedication to his students' success. Always approachable and ready to offer guidance, Professor Anderson created a supportive learning environment.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: This course is a 'choose your own grade' course. Basically, it is extremely easy to get an A. The professor is very chill, and if you need to miss a class you can with no penalty and you can always get an extension. There is a lot of busy work, but none of it is very hard. There were 2 papers and a project, all of which were easy.

Very good professor, but he just speaks fast and goes through his lectures fast. He is always willing to help students out, outside of class, and wants you to succeed. If you ask questions about the problem sets, do not expect clear answers.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Management seems kind of pointless, but he was a fine teacher. I would say that reading the textbook is more beneficial than paying attention in class, as the materials on the midterm and quizzes can easily be found there. Three group projects/presentations, but they're manageable. No final. The class is easy so watch out for the curve.

Mileski changed the class so it's near impossible to get an A. She curves the median test grades to a B+ even though the class should be curved to a 3.6. She does not teach any of the math/stats in the textbook and focuses more on concepts that are intuitive. Half of the class time is spent on unhelpful discussions. Difficult class to sit through.

The class is easy. She's easy-going and lets you decide the format of the exams. My course consisted of 2 exams (one open-note and one take-home) and easy-graded discussion questions. A lot of the exam material is found in the textbook, but some class material is still on it. Problems are more conceptual based than calculation.

One of the best professors I've had. Super kind and very good at providing feedback for papers. She was also very nice about granting extensions for numerous assignments. As long as you put effort into your assignments and participate sometimes, you'll do fine in the course.
Super kind and caring.  Light workload in comparison to other writing and rhetoric courses.

I honestly doubt any non-philo major/minor passed. It was incredibly hard and boring. Electronics were banned and the professor mumbled and wrote sloppy notes. If you did not know the subject matter, you would fail. Your final grade is based off of 3 in class essays (equal weight). I would never recommend this class to anyone.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: shes a great professor! class is very lecture heavy but shes a good lecturer and is passionate abt cognitive psych. the only thing i didnt love was the problem sets, bc some of the grading can be difficult (ex. if you select all but one correct, you get the whole thing wrong). but she herself is very nice and gives great feedback on your projects
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Dr. Chan really cares about your learning and when I took her class, she eliminated traditional exams and had us do consistent online evaluations. They were open book and application based. As long as you attend classes and pay attention, you'll do great. TAs are very helpful if you have questions on the online evaluations before the due date.

Dr. Chan is an amazing professor. She keeps lectures engaging and interesting. She is very accessible for help and wants you to succeed. Dr. Chan is very understanding of different circumstances and while there is a lot of homework, it all relates to the class and is important. Overall, would recommend to everyone.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I love Dr. Chan! She is amazing, interesting, and cares if you succeed. I didn't do as well as I wanted to on my first exam and she agreed if I improved in the course that she would curve my grade. The class is fairly easy because of all the easy assignments and if you study for the exams you will do great!

This was my favorite class ever taken. It was so fun, interesting, and easy. Participation matters but he makes sure everyone succeeds. He does cold call, but he lets you talk over discussions with your table partners first which makes it easy. I recommend this class to everyone!

This is the prof you want for Writing & Rhetoric. Class was easy as long as you put in some effort and do the assignments. A decent amount of homework and a few very manageable essays (it's a writing course after all). She's extremely caring and really accessible. Even if you aren't the best writer, getting an A is pretty easy.

I was very excited about his class and content, but man this guy just sucks the life out of the room when he talks. For some reason decides to grade things excessively harsh as if there is some benefit in that. So many other great profs at ND. Should've retired years ago. Doesn't give a darn about his students.  Don't waste your time with him.

Does not respect school disability services and requires you to break medical confidence to an extreme level to grant any kind of extension from it, when the purpose of the program is to keep confidential information confidential. Stay away.

Otherwise is not flexible. Really easy class that he grades harshly to make life difficult. Not friendly
Really hard class with very little helpful outside resources. Do well on exams and you'll be okay. Study well and with other people
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Miller is undoubtedly the best professor I've had at Notre Dame. Although I struggled immensely with Orgo I, I utilized the Canvas resources much more efficiently in Orgo 2. Reading before lecture AND doing the in-chapter problems helps A LOT. Spacing out your studying before exams (~1 week) also helps. 100% recommend Professor Miller!
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class--Online Savvy

comment_Rating: Professor Miller is a great instructor, and I would 100% recommend for both orgo 1 and orgo 2. His lectures are really good, but I highly, highly recommend reading the book along with the lecture. Miller is also great during one-on-one meetings and office hours, and he wants to help you succeed. Stick it out in orgo 1 and 2!

He really cares about everyone doing well. He is also super energetic in class. If you have an ipad, he makes it really easy to take notes with his slides he posts ahead of class to annotate and follow along with him. This class is hard, but he makes the hard material much easier to understand.

Amazing, amazing professor. He really understands what students need and how they learn best. He repeats questions that were asked before answering them so the entire lecture class can hear. He responds to emails at all hours of the day and is very helpful with his feed back.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: This is the professor you want to take if you are taking organic chem. Lots of worked-out examples in class and available outside of class and office hours. The material is difficult, that's just the subject, but from what I've seen, he is the best at explaining the concepts out of all of the professors that currently teach the course.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Miller is a skilled lecturer and coordinates the Organic Chemistry I course, so his notes are streamlined. He offers quite a few examples and always tries to connect with his students. Always available to make 1 on 1 appointments to nail down concepts. Definitely taking Organic Chemistry II with Miller.

Organic Chemistry Two is one of the hardest classes you will take in college. However, Professor Miller was also the best possible teacher for it. He truly cared about his students and the material. He did a fantastic job teaching. Although it was a hard class, he made it bearable. I would highly recommend, one of the best professor I have had.

Professor Bentley spent most of the time doing practice problems instead of lecturing/describing the material. In physics, you need a good balance of describing and practicing, and he was one extreme. Although we did a lot of problems, they did not seem to help with weekly problem set or tests.

Professor Pierce was an amazing professor. He was very reasonable with grading and gave lots of opportunities to do well in his class. He was also very accessible outside of class, respectful of all questions, and made lectures easy to follow. Would take a class with him again.

Dr. Lane is one of the sweetest professors at ND. She genuinely cares about her students and wants you to succeed. The sheep brain dissection is very difficult, but even if you fail it, you can still get an A in the class if you do well on other assignments.

Dr. Lane is my favorite professor ever. I had her for lab and she was the most kind, helpful, and respectful professor I have ever met. She makes lab very interesting and wants her students to succeed. I am definitely taking one of her lectures in the future. I could not recommend a professor more.

Everyone loves Professor Kilbane. He is the most caring, interesting, and engaging professor I have had. He truly cares about his students and wants us to learn. I looked forwards to going to his class every day. The lectures are cool, projects are fun, and I learned a lot. He created a great environment and would take his class in a heartbeat.

Dr. Morgan was so caring and wanted her students to succeed, however she was not a good lecturer. Lectures were just reading off of power points with no explanations of complex topics. Grading policy was very fair with lots of opportunities to make up points. Concept checks were helpful, but a hassle and too heavily weighted.

She is a really nice person and does want you to succeed. She is really bad at lecturing though. She basically reads straight from the book. It is a struggle to stay awake for her lecture. She sped through mechanisms without really explaining anything.

Dr. Morgan is a caring professor with two priorities. First, that you are doing ok as a student and human being. Secondly, that you are grasping the material. Some lectures are easier to follow than others and there are many resources to practice, get help, and constantly review material. Great professor, very adaptable to help you succeed.

Dr. Morgan is a wonderful person, but her lectures are not the best. She teaches directly from the online textbook, so do not bother reading. I will say, she gives extra credit opportunities in exams and class so there is opportunity to gain points back there. Fair exams, fair homework, good professor!

I have never disliked a professor or teacher to this degree and I actively will never take a class with her again (to the point where I would rather not graduate if it meant that I had to have her as a professor again). The little constructive criticism she gives is helpful, but the rest is borderline bullying and super frustrating.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Online Savvy

comment_Rating: Witnessing Climate Change is an interesting and relevant class. It doesn't require a crazy amount of work. Not too tough of a grader, and you get a point of extra credit for every climate/writing event you go to. I enjoyed how the class was structured: lectures once a week & smaller discussions twice a week. The assignments were interesting too.

Witnessing Climate Change is one of the best courses you could take at ND. You'll learn a ton about climate change and grow immensely as a writer. You can get away with not doing some of the readings but they're really interesting and informative. As long as you put in the work, you'll most likely get an A (it's also easy to get extra credit).
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Zambrana is a great guy. He has so much energy and brings a lot of life to the lectures. Unfortunately, the material sucks. He has you do three fairly intensive group projects and the second test and the final are extremely hard. I did very poorly in the class and somehow ended up with a B+, but the material is hard.

Margaret is great and is very fair. She gives you a great set of lecture notes. Her tests, however, are very hard and determine 81% of your grade. The final was not cumulative. She had a crazy amount of office hours and wanted to see her students succeed. Homework was extremely easy (6 throughout semester, drop one). There was also 1 easy project.
ratingTags_Rating: Test heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: This class felt like two separate courses; The first and second half of the semester do not correlate whatsoever. The latter half (worth ~70% of the grade) is based on one paper on one artwork. There is no clarification about how your grade looks, and he is difficult to contact outside of class. He also changed the syllabus roughly every week.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Prof. Miller is by far the best Orgo professor at ND. You're giving yourself the best shot at succeeding by choosing to go to his lectures. I'm sure other professors are fine, but Prof. Miller is extremely knowledgeable about the topic, and you can tell he really cares. He's great about answering questions over email and during class.

Prof. Miller is great! As good as an orgo professor can get. Lecture is not mandatory but you should attend to do well, you might not even have to read the textbook. He explains the concepts and mechanisms really well and is very accessible outside of class. Do the problem sets and quizzes, they do help your grade. You can tell he loves teaching.
Sometimes a little hard to follow, but genuinely cares for students.
Super nice, she seems stressed out a lot but you won't have any problems with her as a professor.

Professor McKenna is very passionate about what she teaches. I took her CSEM class on renaissance feminism, I thought there was too much work assigned for a class that doesn't count towards your major but still interesting nonetheless. Grading is fair, lots of participation needed. Very clear about her expectations.

Loved her as a professor! Super passionate and understanding. Wouldn't consider the class an easy A - lots of readings (some of which were quite long/tedious) and a discussion-based class so you are graded on participation. If that's not your thing then maybe avoid. Still, class was interesting and she grades fairly if you put in some effort.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Professor Davis is one of the best professors at Notre Dame. His course is challenging, but he is extremely passionate about what he's teaching and he cares about his students. He is hilarious and some of the stories he tells in class are legendary! Take this course if you can! You won't regret it, just be ready to work hard.

Professor Coppedge was not my favorite professor. He is a nice guy but awkward and not great at socializing. He is sometimes too brilliant and struggles to explain difficult concepts in ways that the class can understand. I will say that I did learn how to use the basics of Stata in his course. The class wasn't awful, but I didn't really enjoy it.

Prof. Cajka is such an incredible professor. He is very passionate about the subject he teaches on and is always willing to take other people's points of view into question. I took Witnessing the Sixties with him, and the papers were difficult but he is always willing to help during office hours. Readings are interesting if you like history.

Professor Cajka was amazing. His lectures were super engaging, and he's super passionate about the subject. Discussions were really interesting, and he let students guide the direction of the class. It was easily the most interesting course of my semester. Pay attention to lectures and you will succeed.

Professor Troutner is very polite and understanding.  He love when you participate in class even if you disagree with him.  He is open for discourse on the topics he teaches and will explain different views on the subject.  His daily homework is usually pretty easy and his papers are never too daunting.
Amazing teacher
Heavy reading and heavy lecture course, but this is how 1st Theo goes. He is a fair grader and gives good feedback, helping you improve your theological writing if you ask him.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Troutner is a really great guy. Lectures were sometimes hard to follow and there is a heavy amount of reading and writing to do, but that's just the nature of a theology class. Aside from the content and course itself being a bit tedious, Professor Troutner himself is a good professor, and would recommend him.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Caring

comment_Rating: I had him for my USEM and I am so glad I did. He is an amazing writing teacher and person in general. He is always available to help you with writing after class. He makes the subject very captivating and knows a lot about what he is talking about. Highly recommend taking as USEM!
He is a super nice and engaging professor, there is a decent amount of reading but is very fair when it comes to assessments

Professor O'Conchubhair definitely cares about his students. His classes could be a bit boring at times, but they weren't terribly difficult as long as you did the assigned work. He is very personable and will help you understand the content. The grade is comes only from two papers so definitely take his advice and listen to what he says
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Caring--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Such a great guy and an excellent teacher!  He really knows his stuff and actually got me interested in Irish poetry.  He's really funny and nice, and he even invited our class to his house for pizza!  He also cares a lot about his students and always made sure we were getting through our first semester okay.

I had him for USEM not the one I picked it was the only option lol. He makes you read your papers out loud sometimes, but he is sooo nice. Would 100% recommend. Made so many friends in this class. We watched world cup in class one time. Love this guy.

Take him if you get the option! He's the best! He genuinely cares for the wellbeing of his students and the improvement of their writing. I feel like my writing has improved vastly through the feedback he offers.

Prof. O'Conchubhair is by far the best professor I've had at ND. He genuinely cares about his students and wants to see them succeed, and he tries to help you out in any way possible. His CSEM was very simple, just read speeches from the Irish president and Obama and write questions on them! Then you get to discuss in class. Would 100% recommend!

Professor O'Conchubhair is one of a kind. He is my favorite professor outside of my major at ND. He guides classes and discussions flawlessly, and is very relatable to many students. He even went out of his way to connect with me, and invited me to get coffee and talk about soccer with him! Although somewhat intimidating at first, he is great!

One of the coolest professors you'll ever have. His expertise in Theology is evident but he is also a great lecturer and really entertaining. He's super accessible and helpful outside of class and honestly, as long as you put in some effort you'll get a good grade. Often lets class out early once he's covered all his material. Overall a great guy.

Professor Neal is one of the most energetic and full-of-life people I have ever met. He greeted me by name whenever we passed each other, which is a small thing, but does not go unnoticed. He does his absolute best to fill his students with a true love and passion for engineering.

Can't go wrong with any of the FYE teachers, but highly recommend Neal. His enthusiastic teaching style makes the class less boring. Neal wants to see you succeed and is super helpful in office hours even if what you ask is unrelated to class.
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Never had more of an enthusiastic professor. He cares about his students and most definitely wants you to be successful. He is also super funny ( I laughed too much at his jokes that were both cringe and funny at the same time). It is wonderful that he brings light into the classroom during the most tiring time of the day.
Great professor! The class was kind of boring but he definitely tried to make it interesting and is a super funny guy

Really great professor overall, usually does not assign lots of homework. Likes to get to know his students and is understanding. Take any of his classes if you don't mind participating, you will not regret.

I actually strongly disagree with the person below me -- Stiver was funny and went out of his way to make lectures engaging. He has a more monotone voice, but he is overall a nice guy and willing to help after class. The content is tough but not impossible to learn; helpful for real world too.

Professor Stiver is quite disrespectful towards students--talking about inappropriate subjects in class (especially surprising at a Catholic school), saying politically incorrect things, and generally making students uncomfortable both in and out of the classroom. His class is full of lecture material, but he will only ask about the problem set Q's

Nicholas Edelen is a good guy. One thing he lacks is control over a class. People will talk and he'll try to interject but he just can't. His lectures are fine, nothing too crazy. A bit boring but it's calc 1, you know?

As someone who had already taken calc, I can say that he tends to overcomplicate the material and is quite difficult to understand. In my opinion, he is super rushed and overwhelmed when teaching (and runs over class time frequently). Overall, he cares about his students but most people in the class constantly looked confused.
Many didn't like him but if you're interested in the material he is a very interesting professor. It is true that he goes above the level of learning of most of the students.

Prof Edelen cares a lot about his students' success, but he just goes way over students' heads. Calc 3 does not cover that hard of material but the way he explains it and the abstract, obscure examples he gives confuses most students in the class. I had to look up videos for every unit to understand what we actually were learning.

Overall, way too qualified for his job. His lectures expect that you know everything already and are heavily conceptual with poor explanations (instead of examples). An A is definitely possible, but out of class studying is necessary. Take at your own risk. He's a really nice guy, though, and wants you to succeed.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Somanchi is one of my favorite professors at Notre Dame. Attendance wasn't strictly mandatory but showing up to class was necessary for learning the material. Throughout the lectures there were many practice questions to keep students engaged, and collaboration is encouraged. He truly cares about student learning and jokes around in class.

Some of these are misleading. He is a very nice, funny guy but as a freshman with limited experience I had to go to office hours each week just to complete the homework. He assumes you understand and moves on quickly, so you must be focused all the time. I've heard others had an easier time in Ackermann. I wouldn't take it with him as a freshman

this class was definitely helpful in building my finance knowledge!  short answer exams at first seemed impossible but honestly it ended up being great because of partial credit so i much prefer this exam structure. got a decent grade with some hard work  and enough studying. would recommend

Some tricky exams in my opinion but I appreciate the challenge a lot since I plan to pursue a finance job. i had to try pretty hard to get a B+ (i think) but honestly i could've tried harder . prof chen was always available, i just didn't make the effort to go to his office hours. but overall great prof and would take again

BEST PROFESSOR! I loved his class, he always made learning fun and even brought prizes to class for answering questions and winning kahoots. His exams are not difficult if you put the time into understanding the material. He's a very funny professor and he even got a mullet because he made a deal with our class!

I had a great experience in Prof Chen's class! His lectures were fun and he would bring prizes! He was always available after class and would respond to emails within 5 minutes. He gave me a mock interview for my GS superday (I got the internship). In his class, if you put in the effort, you will do very well. He will help you all along the way!

Really nice guy that's looking out for students' interests. Decent teacher of topics but I can't say explanations are his strong-suit. HW load is pretty low. Exams are not easy and can expand beyond what was discussed in class in unexpected ways
I had Prof Dreyer for another course and this one, and he was always respectful of our time and wanted us to actually engage with the course material, which we did.
Professor Sevov is a very good lecturer. He is well organized and makes sure all the material is taught in the most straight-forward and understandable way possible.

Slavi Sevov is a great professor, has a nice dry humor, and carefully explains to the students what will be on the exams. He'll make some mistakes, but it's all worth it because you get to learn about Bulgaria.

Sevov is a great guy and very funny. He is very knowledgeable on the topic but that sometimes means he forgets we are not. He explains things very well in class but I recommend finding your own way of taking notes during lectures as his notes are not easy to understand when studying or reviewing for tests. Other Profs notes are easier to understand

Slavi makes every class so much fun--he has a great sense of humor! He goes over the material without covering any unnecessary stuff, which is really helpful. I always felt prepared for every test. Just make sure you do the practice tests and you'll do great.
He is great in office hours, you should try to go often.

If you have no knowledge about chem, his style of lecture might be slightly harder to grasp. But if you know the subject, I would recommend him a million times.  He was a great guy, good at communicating, and more than willing to help after class / during office hours ALWAYS!
Was able to communicate the material well with handwritten notes and examples. He's a great guy and could always raise the atmosphere in the room with his funny anecdotes and stories.
Very concise and clear with him lectured but also cared for his students deeply
Absolutely adore him, so kind to students and very understanding. Doing hand written notes rather than slides that are very helpful and easy to follow.

Slavi Sevov is incredible. I took Intro to Chem with him last semester and myself and many others still talk about how amazing he was. Not only was he an efficient lecturer, but he extremely caring, and made our lecture of 200-300 kids all feel loved and cared about.

SLAVI. MF. SEVOV. If you have to take gen chem 1, take it with Slavi. Even if you're not in his section, go to his lectures. Genuinely so nice and gives amazing dad energy. Will roast you but it's always in the name of good fun. You can tell that he wants students to love chemistry as much as he does. Long story short, Slavi is the only answer.

I loved learning from Prof. Sevov. He has great "Dad" vibes, sharing a bit about his personal life throughout the semester which made lectures about Chemistry a bit more bearable. I did not take AP chem in high school, only went to lecture and took notes, and did perfectly fine in the course. Go to class and do the work and you'll be fine.

Professor Sevov gives very good lectures. He makes what you need to know clear and does not clutter the lectures with extra information. He walks through examples with simple step-by-step instructions. He occasionally starts class with a personal story or funny life lesson.

Gen Chem is hard in general, but he did a great job teaching it. No need to read the textbook because he covers everything in class. His teaching style is a little different, but it really helped me. Really helpful at office hours. 10/10 recommend for gen chem.

Professor Sevov is a great person and truly cares about his students, but if you need organized and clear notes his teaching style is difficult to follow. He goes through the material really fast and doesn't clearly answer questions. However, the TA's are VERY helpful during office hours and that is how I learned the most.

Professor Sevov is amazing! I cannot rave about him enough. His lectures were engaging and the exams were very similar to the material covered in lecture. His notes are just words on a blank piece of paper, which I prefer, but if you are someone who prefers powerpoints he might not be the teacher for you.

Sevov is definitely the best chem lecture to have. I had a lot of friends in other sections that came to his section because he was the best at teaching the material. He never keeps you late and always asks how every is doing. Also, he shared his life wisdom and experiences with the class in order to inspire. Overall, a very good man and professor.

Sevov is the best. He cares so much about his students and wants them all to be successful. Lectures moved fast but were extremely clear. He's great at answering questions and is willing to stick around a bit after class. If you take good notes and study, the class will be no problem.

Prof Sevov is the beloved teacher of gen chem. He explains concepts clearly and gives examples. He cares about his students, gives good life advice, is willing to work with you outside of class, and is usually ahead of the other classes which gives him time to answer questions before exams. Come to class and take notes--he prepares you well.
Professor Sevov is certainly a fun teacher. Makes concepts clear and uses plenty of examples throughout his lectures. Definitely have him as your professor for gen chem.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Sevov is undeniably the GOAT. Attend lectures, pay attention, do the homework, and you will succeed.

Easily the best Gen Chem professor. Goes through lots of examples in class, makes the material easy to understand, and is a super nice and funny guy. If possible, Sevov is the professor you'll want to have for gen chem.
Sevov is the Gen Chem 1 professor to have. He teaches only the stuff that you have to know. Great at explaining the information and giving example problems.

Please take Gen Chem with Professor Sevov. Without a doubt one of the greatest professors I will probably have during my time here. He is always straightforward and clear about the content during lectures, and always includes practices problems within them to apply the material we learned. 10/10 no matter what your background in chemistry is.
beloved professor. if you have to take chem 10171 take sevov he's the best of the four.
Chem is a boring, strict class and not very useful for most, but Sevov makes it fun.

Professor Sevov is probably the best professor to have for Chem. He goes through lots of examples in class compared to the other professors. He knows what he is talking about and his notes are very clear, so even if you miss class it is not difficult to follow what happened in class. I would highly recommend him, he just gives off good vibes.
The Lectures are good mostly easy to understand. If you miss some classes it will be harder but you can still catch up, however, tutorials and exams are hard but they don't depend on the professor.
so sweet
30x more personality than any of the other chem teachers, gotta be honest I kind of enjoy the class
Literally the best. Dad energy is off the charts, he explains concepts concisely and memorably. He's hilarious and we all love him. Easily the best chem professor at ND.
He's simply the GOAT.
What a nice and engaging professor! He's Bulgarian but his accent is not hard to understand. He sometimes speeds through topics that are hard to understand, but if you ask questions he'll slow down!

We *literally* cheered when Slavi came back after being substituted by another professor. Cares about students, and is the best of the University's Intro Chem Professors at communicating material effectively.

Great professor! Basically a write-and-talk lecture. Very light-hearted and fun, cracks good jokes and gives off dad energy. Explains the material pretty well but the class can go fast at times and if you did not take AP Chem/have a good background in chem you might struggle a little. His accent is pretty fun to listen to. Had a good time in class!

Favorite prof of the semester, would 100% recommend. His lectures are clear and straightforward and he has a great sense of humor. He tells you everything you need to know and nothing you don't.  Some other profs have unnecessary info in their lectures that arent on the tests. Cares about students and answers questions.
The class is pretty boring but sevov is so nice and funny and really cares about his students. He has the best lecture notes and is very clear.
Absolute gem. so funny, so easy going. posted notes online, went through examples in class, definitely the best chem teacher out there

LOVED HIM! My favorite professor this semester! I've heard gen chem is very tough but his lectures are very straight forward and easy to follow. He gives you the material you need to know for tests with applicable examples. He's funny and cares about his students.

Sevov was one of my favorite profs this semester, his lectures can be a little dry sometimes but they're easy to follow. Just copy the notes that he writes down and you'll be good. He gives enough time to copy them which is nice. Really wants the students to do well. Says some of the funniest stuff sometimes.

A GEM. One of my favorite professors this semester. Uses class time efficiently, and explains concepts so well that students from other classes often skip their classes to come to ours. Hilarious without even trying. Truly cares about his students and willing to help you understand things you're confused about. Protect him at all costs!

Cuts to the chase and says things to the point. Copy his notes and listen to his explanations and that's all you need to do well in the class. He can lack engagement at times but he has a good sense of humor and is good at explaining the important concepts and problem examples that will be on tests.

Professor Montalbano forces you to go beyond understanding the "what" to understanding the "why." He is tough on his students and when he thinks you are giving him a nonsense answer he is unafraid to call you out on it. He treats you like you work for him and pushes students hard to become the best versions of themselves they can be.

Montalbano is a character. Participation matters a lot, but don't get down if you receive a bad initial grade on participation because there is still a chance of doing well in the class. Prepare a lot for the final and you will do well. Meet with Montalbano early on in the semester. Case studies and a group project make up a lot of the class.

I took Professor Montalbano for Foundations of Strategy and I learned a lot from the class, participation matters a lot, be prepared to contribute in class unless you want your grade to suffer. He's a very unique professor, be ready to adjust to his methods and try to have fun in the class. Be prepared for somewhat vague assignment descriptions.

(Found. of Strategy) Montalbano's class will shock you at first. Make sure to carefully read the syllabus. He is a personality, but the case-based learning and group projects will teach you very valuable information about business. Make sure to ask questions and be very respectful with all emails and interactions with him. He is your "boss".

This class WILL put you outside of your comfort zone but it is worth it. Professor Montalbano will question every statement you make and push you to genuinely think. His teaching style may shock you but it has helped me learn so much about business. I highly recommend taking his class if you want to see what the business world is really like.

My favorite professor so far at ND. His real world experience and emphasis on discussion help you take away A LOT from the class. Challenges you to think differently than typical mendoza student Pretty funny, very real dude. That combined with his ability to relate to students makes discussion interesting. You will actually enjoy going to his class

Professor Montalbano is a great professor. His professional experience really shines through in the classroom. He provides clear examples during his lectures that make them engaging. The class is not that difficult if you put the work into it. Participation is necessary to succeed. There is also a group project worked on throughout the semester.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: John is awesome! Would 100% take this class again. He's chill and the lectures are helpful/make sense with reference slides that are clear so you can go back and understand if you happen to miss something. And super engaging!
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: John is a fantastic dude. Really helpful and knowledgeable if you have questions. Also gives really good in-class problems that prepare you for the exam and real-world examples that really help contextualize the material. The King of Partial Credit.

Duan is THE one to take for coding! She is very caring and helpful. Highly recommend going to office hours frequently because she will answer all your questions if you show effort towards starting the problems. Coding has a lot of work but it balances out with the fact that you only have class once a week. Exams and weekly quizzes are open note.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Duan truly cares about her students, she makes an effort to get to know everyone, and encourages you to ask questions. Duan is one of my favorite professors.

Duan is a kind and caring professor. She knows our names and wants everyone to succeed. She is attentive to everyone's questions. She patiently answers questions until you fully understand. She knows how to teach Python well. She is always there to help. I enjoy participating in her lectures which helps me to fully understand the material.
Hardest class I have taken at ND so far.

Professor Duan is very caring and accessible outside of class. Her office hours are a great resource. Graded for completion of tutorials, labs, and quizzes. With her help in office hours and class, the tutorials and labs are easy grades. Quizzes were take home, 5 questions in 5 minutes.

This class is in a flipped format, so you meet once a week to review the assignments that were due in the prior week (Meet on Thursday to review the work from last Friday-this Thursday). Overall a good teacher. Very accessible and helpful outside of class. The tutoring sessions are really helpful if you get stuck on the assignments.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: he is just an idiot. the other reviews below except the obviously fake one with 5 stars are right, he isn't a bad person but horrendous teacher. not helpful, pretty random grades and assignments, would not recommend.

So shocked by the bad reviews on here! I took Prof. Perez-Linan's Quantitative Political Analysis Using R class this semester, and he explained extremely difficult topics with ease. He is a fairly easy grader as well. He really wants his students to succeed and is a really caring person.

comment_Rating: Kind of shocked by the negative reviews; if you work hard and pay attention, it should be a piece of cake because he's an easy grader and class expectations are clear. yeah no. just don't take him, his syllabus and assignments are so unclear it gives you a headache. His final grades were kind of randomized, and he called students the wrong names in December. Nice guy, really really bad at teaching
nice but so confusing and bad. Seems to enjoy inconveniencing students lives. Random grader. Would get a beer with him but not recommend his class

Dr. Vachon is so amazing. He is so passionate about his work and caring towards his students. His lectures can be a little bit long sometimes, but for the most part, class is very interactive and he uses a lot of aids to make lectures more enjoyable. Online quizzes every week, a few reflections, one research paper, and oral final

I took the Economy: Divine and Human course, and it is the best class I have taken at ND. Amazing lectures with profound insights, minimal homework (mostly reading and written 0.5 page reflections), and two very easy exams. The class is easy and edifying at the same time. Every class should be like this, and every professor should be like Doran!

Professor Doran is supposedly the hardest Econ professor but I found the course to be very easy. He is super caring and makes it very clear what he wants from you on the tests. The tests are all multiple choice, and very math heavy but the math is simple applied algebra. His lectures are very entertaining and he can be very funny.

Doran is one of the more challenging micro professors and has a very fast paced teaching style. However, if you put in a lot of effort and studying, you will be able to do well in his class. He is a nice guy but sometimes seems annoyed by student questions. Overall, I would recommend his class but be ready to work hard.

I couldn't have asked for a better Micro teacher, his classes had the perfect balance of math and real life applications, he even brought out some cool economic studies near the end of the semester. Make sure you go along and work out the problems with him in class and you'll be set.

Professor Doran is a great character and just a great person overall. He emphasizes the importance of knowing which practices to master for exams (setting up equations, reasoning behind scenarios, etc.) which was super helpful. I would definitely take Doran again and would highly recommend him to anyone thinking about taking him.
Kirk Doran was the best professor I have had so far. If I could take his class again I would. He effectively highlights what information will be on tests and makes sure you know it.

Doran is known to be one of the harder econ professors, but I thought he was super engaging and really enjoyed his teaching style. The test material was always covered in class or on practice problems, they never try to trick you. It was definitely fast paced but between him and the TAs there were always many opportunities for extra help.
Principles of Microeconomics has a lot of good professors but I loved Doran and he is the reason I switched to the Econ major.

The homework for this class is on Cengage and due before class but it was only mentioned in syllabus week so not sure if it really counts, its not graded on correctness anyway. This class has more exams than the average Micro class around 5 or 6 in total including the final, TA's make the exam and some were slightly harder than others.

Very nice guy but BEWARE TA's make all the tests so they are very unpredictable and hard to study for. One of the hardest Econ professors. Attendance is optional but if you miss one class you will be lost. Review sheets don't really help.

Doran is extremely well-prepared for each class. He is willing to go over problems multiple times at office hours until you understand the concept. Lectures move very fast and it can be hard to keep up with the pace. Class is more math-heavy than other econ sections. Exams are slightly unpredictable. He is one of the harder econ professors.
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Doran is a really good professor. He teaches more of a calculus-based economics class, so if you don't understand math you will be in trouble, but if you do you will find it easy. His office hours are extremely helpful as he is a really nice guy and will appreciate you putting in the effort.

Doran is the best professor I've had at ND. His lectures were super interesting! I recommend this class for students that need Econ for their careers (it is on the more difficult side). Homework and participation are graded on completion. He also curves the exams and has office hours. If you are willing to push yourself, definitely a must-take!

Doran knows the material well and moves quickly. He doesn't take attendance, but if you miss class, you'll be pretty lost. Prob the hardest microecon professor but he cares abt his students a lot

comment_Rating: Had Doran for microeconomics fall semester freshman year (2020). Solid professor who is very personable and knows the material like the back of his hand. He is an amazing lecturer and a very engaing professor. He knows the topic so well that he can answer any question on the spot. He takes participation and effort into consideration when giving you your grade.
Professor Doran is one of the smartest profs you'll meet. He genuinely cares about all his students and his office hours are extremely helpful to drive home the material.

Great lecturer, always helpful, knows microeconomics like the back of his hand, and cares about students understanding the material. Wish more professors were like him.  Sometimes in-class problems become too ubiquitous, but they are helpful.

Professor Gilligan has high standards when it comes to the female body. Whenever we would do poorly and not participate he would punish us severely with tests. He is very passionate about his students learning, he even told us he loved us after only knowing us for a short period of time.

Professor Gilligan was passionate about the topic which made the class spectacular. He really filled me up (with information, of course!) His dress code was somewhat odd, as I had to wear a sundress even when it was freezing cold outside! Overall, extremely satisfying

Professor Gilligan really challenged me this semester. He really wore me out, as the class requires a lot of hands on teaching. I was not expecting Professor Gilligan to be so passionate about this class, but every class session I could tell he loves what he does.
ratingTags_Rating: Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Gilligan really wore me out this semester. He clearly cared deeply about the subject, but I questioned his real-world experience in the field. I enjoyed class, except for the two brutal punishments Professor Gilligan dished out (on test days of course). Ample chance for extra credit.
Professor Gilligan was always accessible after class and the class was very hands-on. Class sessions were long and hard but well worth it. I feel more than satisfied with what I learned.
Prof. Gilligan is a very engaging teacher.

He has a chiller class that fulfills the WKST requirement. This class is the easiest A I have ever gotten. You do not need to go to class all semester. The textbook is great if you want to learn about cosmology.

Can't say enough about Prof. Mathews. Get ready to become a space traveler! Go to the observatory enough and you don't have to take the final.
If you hate science take this class. No labs and extra credit projects at the observatory are enjoyable. If you do well on the first exam and paper there is no need to take the final.

I absolutely love Professor Mathews. Attendance was not mandatory, and gave lots of extra credits. Homeworks are crossword puzzles and quizzes that you can take multiple times. He responded to my emails within an hour even on weekends. Lectures are kind of boring but there no excuse to not get an A. Did not even have to do the final.
ratingTags_Rating: EXTRA CREDIT--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: He is clearly knowledgeable about the content, but staying engaged is hard. LOTS of extra credit- there's no excuse for not making an A. Attendance not required. Homework is crossword puzzles, quizzes you can retake as many times as needed, and 2 papers. I did not learn much from this course but it was an easy way to fulfill a science credit.

This is the easiest science credit to take at Notre Dame. The extra credit gives you an insane grade boost, and the online quizzes are super easy and you are able to retake them an unlimited amount of times. I don't have to sit the final to get an A in the class. The papers are graded very easy. The tests are all MCQ and not difficult.

I'd absolute recommend Professor Mathews. His Cosmology class was very easy. That said, I don't think his teaching style was great; it focused too much on pure lectures to be very engaging after the second or so week. Still, the absolute abundance of extra credit means that you'd have to actually try to get less than an A in his class.

I genuinely enjoyed my elementary cosmology class this semester because Professor Mathews did his best to make the content interesting, but the class still was not difficult even if you didn't pay attention. It was the easiest A I've ever gotten and there is a lot of extra credit. Take this class if you want your science requirement taken care of.
Took Professor Mathews for Elementary Cosmology. Literally the easiest A I have gotten here. Tons of extra credit. Also hilarious, plays music during lectures.
Prof Mathews is too smart to be teaching this class.

Fr. Kevin was a W mans. The mandatory 'textbooks' just refer to the catholic reading bible that is required for everyone in the class to have, and two other short stories but tbh you could just find pdf versions online and have them printed out (not the bible though). He made great hummus for office hours, and the TAs were great as well

Lots of reading and homework due for every class, but if you do the work you'll get the A. The TA's aren't harsh graders and the 2 exams we did in class we get before hand, and he answers all the questions during office hours. He also took the time to learn everyone's names in our lecture. 100% recommend for an easy A to knock out the requirement.

comment_Rating: Amazing professor and learned a lot about the catholic faith in this class. At first it might seem like a lot of work but the grading is fairly easy as long as you showed effort. There are only 2 tests and they are very easy he gives you them ahead of time. I would recommend this class, everyone I know enjoyed it and ended up with a high grade.

As long as you do the work you will probably get an A, especially with the grade boost from the discussions with purpose. The TAs do not grade tough at all. Attendance is mandatory. The readings are long but doable and the papers and exams are not that hard. Lectures are not too boring and can be fun at select times.

There is a lot of homework for this class but if you do even the bare minimum you'll probably get an A. He is not a tough grader and the class isn't super hard. He kind of plays favorites between the dorms
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--So many papers--Caring

comment_Rating: The readings were long but if you do then you will get an A. He is not a tough grader as long as you do the work.  Also if you go to the office hours before the test he will give you the exact answer. He is a fantastic professor and learned the names of almost the whole class despite it being over 200 people.

People hate on Fr. Kev, but don't listen to them. Genuinely such a caring guy. He knew probably every student's name after the first month and lecture had about 200 kids in it (which is mad impressive). Yes, there is a lot of reading, do not get discouraged. His lectures are very clear and his class is truly you get out of it what you put into it.

Great and engaging class and lectures! There is about 1 page of writing for each class (2 per week) but it is graded easily. Exams questions are all given in advance. Massive extra credit opportunity given to boost grade. Worth it!

comment_Rating: Great professor, one of my favorites at ND. Very genuine person who cares about your success and understanding in his class. Perfect fit to teach this class in an engaging way!

comment_Rating: Fr. Kevin is an amazing man, and his class will change your life.

Fr. Kevin is one of the best professors I've ever had. He gives fantastic lectures, and, though his class is reading and writing heavy, the TAs grade fairly. Hard work pays off. His tests aren't bad. Taking his class has been an essential part of my experience at Notre Dame. His class has changed the way I view myself and those around me.

I really enjoyed this class: each class feels genuine and actually reached me, compared to a lot of my other profs. You can't go to Notre Dame and not take a class with Fr. Kevin. By far, one of my favorite professors I have ever had. Fr. Kevin is an amazing guy who genuinely cares so much about his students.  He knows how to connect with the class, and he is a very talented lecturer. He's a great guy and his lectures are pretty engaging but the homework is a little obnoxious. If you are planning to major or minor in theology, I absolutely recommend this class, otherwise it is more work than it is worth.
