comment_Rating: Life changing class, truly. He was so clear about what he wanted us to learn and why. I felt like I learned a lot about myself and the world from him. He was readily available outside of class and the work we needed to do for him, while extensive and not always easy, related directly to our learning in an impactful way. 100% recommend him
A really good guy and will learn something you can take with you forever. But beware, a lot of work.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: I think Prof Rose gets a bad rap based on other reviews. I took him for Cognitive Psychology last year, and I really thought he was engaging, funny, and fair as a professor. He lets you drop your lowest exam score and he also offers 10 points of extra credit and EC questions in exams too. Give him a chance, and don't immediately trust other reviews

This class seem really easy but then you get into the exams and absolutely bomb your grade.  Then when you go to office hours he condescends your study habits and makes it seem like you had horrible habits that barely got you into Notre Dame.  The class is hard, powerpoints are confusing and the only good part is the TA who leaves nice comments.

I don't have a problem with him as a person, but he's not a good professor. He expects you to know things not taught in class and does not explain things well. I was excited about the class (Intro to Cognitive Neuroscience) but it ended up being the worst one I've taken at Notre Dame. DO NOT take a class from Professor Rose.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Get ready to read--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Condescending to students when they ask questions that they "should already know". Seems too busy outside of class for meeting, even when you do manage to schedule one. Tries to relate to students occasionally, but just leaves everyone confused and on guard. Dry lectures, would not recommend.

Socially awkward. Wants good reviews rather than genuinely being a good teacher. hilarious that he has one positive review thats clearly him writing one for himself. Who does that? condescending at office hours too

Keeps the information up-to-date. Makes his lectures interesting & usually has things in there that help keep your attention - adds jokes & funny videos into class. Very knowledgable about psychology - is active in his field. Has a great policy for tests (4, drop lowest) & holds many review sessions (will go over test Q's also).

Professor Rossiter was my favorite professor last semester! I really enjoyed her seminar and learned a lot from it, and on top of that she was a pretty easy grader and really worked with her students when they needed it. Can't recommend enough.
4.5/5 difficulty. Very nice professor who is very engaging. Does a great job explaining the topics but it is a very hard class.

Prof. Nicholson is perhaps the greatest math professor of all time. He has this way of explaining calculus that is simple and very easy to follow. He cares about all of his students and always makes time to explain concepts if you ever need it. 11/10 professor

Though the classwork was not super hard, the assignments themselves were near impossible without help from the TAs or ChatGPT. Easley did not teach during the class. He was also extremely inappropriate with female students, touching my back during class and coming up to only me in class to ask about my weekend, getting close to me. DO NOT RECOMMEND

The flipped classroom made this class feel useless to me. He did not teach much at all, and I had trouble with even the most basic concepts. Over half of the class did poorly on the midterm, seeing as the test was among the most difficult I have ever taken. If you need a gentle push into coding like I did, this is NOT the class for you.

Flipped classroom so he doesn't actually do any of the teaching, so this isn't that important. He isn't great at explaining concepts, but he's an extremely nice guy who loves his subject. Two assignments at home per week which should take about an hour each. Questions on assignments are very unclear, and exam was poorly written.

Foundations of Coding is flipped classroom, so the professor is not too important, but Easley was not great at explaining himself when asked a question. I wouldn't say this recommendation should dissuade you from taking his section if it's at a good time for you, but he's likely not the best teacher for beginner python learners in any given year

Bo is an excellent professor and an even more excellent person. He comes to class bringing the same energy without fail, is very understanding of personal matters, and is accessible outside of class. Bo clearly has an abundance of knowledge about Learning Analytics and Python. I can not recommend a professor more than I recommend Bo.

Bo is a great professor. He really cares about all of his students. He makes an effort and succeeds in forming a connection with all of his students. Bo is super kind and was always willing to help me with any questions I had in or outside of class.

Bo Pei was the best professor I had in 4 years at Notre Dame. His caring personality and unwavering support for students foster an incredible learning environment. He is willing to listen, and takes time to thoroughly answer every question. Finally, his Python teaching abilities are excellent. I would highly recommend any course taught by him.

Eric Jumper is an absolutely brilliant man.  Unfortunately none of that translates into being a good teacher.  The man lacks empathy towards others and is incredibly arrogant.  

He is much more interested in research and publishing.  Students are an unwelcome distraction to his other interests.

Absolutely the worst professor I have had.  Unable to communicate basic principles of aerospace engineering.

He has absolutely no patience for students who cannot learn his material and will launch personal attacks against you in his office.

She was the worst lecturer I have ever had. Bar none. She also stole another professor's course material (assignments, quizzes, and exams) for the majority of the course. Additionally, she admitted to us that she didn't know how to write Python code, despite the fact that she was the professor for a class taught mostly in Python.

During lecture she would constantly struggle to write code, even when copying it, and failed to demonstrate any understanding of the material. She would constantly say "I'll get back to you" when someone would ask a question about why she did something, but she would never actually get back to you. I would not recommend taking her class.

Professor is only interested in advertising her invented 'methods' of psychology, which are nonsense. More interested in telling students why the rest of the world is wrong than teaching any material. Class material has little to no relationship on the textbook but both are tested heavily, 150+ textbook pages per exam. Avoid at all costs.
She is very nice and funny, but she is a truly awful professor. I learned nothing. I taught myself literally everything. Do not take her class.

Do not take this class. Nice person and I am sure I would like her if I weren't in her class, but she should not be a teacher. All she does, every day all class, is advertise her book and teach us absolutely nothing. Then we get tested on 5 chapters worth of information she never taught us, not bc she didn't have time but bc she chose not to.

You're going to have to rely almost entirely on the book for her class. She teaches you almost nothing other than deductive reasoning, which is basically her way of life. She's funny, but not really there to teach psychology.

Staud is my favorite professor on this campus. I highly recommend taking his USEM class. He's easy to talk to and is super understanding when you need extensions. He gets so excited when we discuss the reading material. One day he got so excited he jumped out of his chair. It's wholesome and contagious, as we often will feel more engaged.

For reference, I very much struggled with DiffEQ 1, and was bound to struggle with DiffEQ 2. Professor Wensing is an incredibly intelligent person, but he is still able to communicate complex info to students very effectively. He is incredibly caring and motivated me to do better in this class. I do not think I could have passed without his support

Not much to say. She is a very good Intro to Photography professor. I learned a lot and it was not that much work. A few big projects but not stressful and a nice break from my other work. Would highly recommend

Prof. Marcus has high expectations, but she gives her students the support they need to do well. Regardless of a student's starting point, she pushes them to the next step in their growth as a writer. She's very nice and makes herself accessible to her students for help. Super cool person and great teacher.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Great professor and great class Prof. Visconsi challenges his students in a productive way and makes class enjoyable. I learned a lot of things that I continue to think about and reference. His assignments made you think and were fun to do. He got to know every student and encouraged them to play to their strengths in their final projects.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Very clear lectures and assignments. Her expectations and grading were very reasonable. She really made me care about the material and got students to engage with the educational community.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Group projects--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Great guy, cares about his students learning. The lectures can be a little boring at times given the nature of the class, but he tries to be engaging. The exams are not terrible, and the quizzes are not too hard as well. There is one big group project with a presentation, but he is not a harsh grader.

Professor Toumayan is really patient and offers many opportunities for extra credit. He always gives essay extensions if needed. Participation is worth 25% of the final grade, but you don't need to speak in every lecture.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: I really enjoyed this class. He goes through slides fairly quickly, but honestly I felt that kept me engaged because I knew I had to be paying attention.

He speaks fast and goes through about 60 slides/ class. There's a midterm, a final, a few psets, and a project. He takes forever to grade homework, and goes so fast that we often had to cover the same material in the next class cause he went too fast. He seems like a good guy though, and exams aren't that tough  if you have time to study for them.

She is great, really caring and overall a good person. Funny, engaging, and cares about your learning. Daily readings, but nothing super hard. 5 short, easy quizzes, and if you miss one you have to write an essay. Always available outside class. You will literally learn how to be a better person.

Good guy, pretty funny. Clearly knows what he is talking about, but lectures can be somewhat abstract / highly theoretical, which can be hard to put into practice. Always available outside class to help.

Jonathan Boulos is both an excellent teacher and human. He cares about his students and was extremely understanding of personal extenuating circumstances. His lectures are short and sweet with an emphasis on their application to the real world, in which he has had a detailed career in accounting.

Wojcik is clearly passionate about the course content. She treats it as if she's learning along with us rather than just talking at us. I enjoyed the papers because of the freedom to pick which films to write about. Some films were great and some were boring. I learned a lot from this class and would recommend it for an interesting art credit.

Writing this review to ensure Blado never gets full professorship. He is an incredibly hard-headed individual, and incredibly unhelpful when it comes to giving advice. He has a robotic personality and is unable to connect with students. He turned GGL from a fun introductory philosophy class into a struggle to get a halfway decent grade. Avoid!!
Decent teacher, was offended that he demanded to be called professor despite being a grad student.

He is way too smart for Physics I. If you have never taken physics, a lot of the stuff will go right over your head and you will not understand. The readings sometimes help, but rarely. The examples he goes over in class are a lot more simple than the ones on the homework or on exams which does not help with studying for exams. Very hard
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Christiano is a very sweet guy. He clearly cares about all of his students and their wellbeing. His lectures were often boring and difficult to follow. His grading was quite strange and he often gave not much of an explanation for essay grades. On plus side, he cancelled class some times and was flexible with deadlines. Easier profs for intro soc.
ratingTags_Rating: So many papers--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Terrible lectures

Cell Bio is a hard course. You need to completely memorize the slides in class, which is a lot of slides and is very tough. You are graded on 4 tests, equally weighted and non cumulative. She does a great job explaining the material in lecture, and she is really helpful outside of class. Remember, you'll need to grind before tests, so be ready.

Prof D'Souza-Schorey is one of the best cell bio profs in the department and is very passionate about the field. The course is really dense and fact based. To do well you basically memorize everything on the hundreds of slides from lecture. Grade is from 4 exams equally weighted but are non-cumulative. She does well on explaining the material well.

Prof Coleman is a pretty caring prof whose passion pulls you into interest of the subject as well. I did not care much for environmental history at first but Coleman's lectures got me pretty interested in the subject. His lectures are pretty straightforward however expect to read multiple 300+ pg books in essay writing weeks (only 4 essays tho).

His corporate governance class is a pretty easy A-. Easier than the other finance classes in Mendoza. Iffland and a TA do all the grading. Cremers is actually extremely boring, but he's very nice. The class was interesting. 7 problem sets, a take-home essay midterm, a 6-page paper, and a couple small assignments. They took us out for drinks twice.
His work on active share and shareholder rights is amazing.
Hard course.

Prof. Cremers did an excellent job of first building our knowledge in the three categories of corporate governance.  Once our foundation was built, we explored many cases to apply these concepts to real world examples making the learning more memorable and applicable.

He was a great professor. Very clear explanations, gave lots of helpful examples and did great review sessions before the exams which helped a ton. He is also super funny and cares about his students a lot. The class overall was pretty hard in my opinion, the content itself wasn't too bad but the exams were very tricky and difficult.

Super easy writing and rhetoric. Professor Swanke is a lenient grader and as long as you do all the assignments and revise your papers you should get an A. She is also very flexible with attendance and deadlines.

Professor Swanke is an absolute gem. She makes the class inclusive and relaxing. Classes pretty much ran like a discussion, and she values student input. There were 3 papers (which you could revise for a higher grade), and they had pretty fun topics. She would also have a 1 on 1 meeting after a paper was due for feedback. 100% recommend!!!
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Swanke makes writing and rhetoric all but boring. Most of the time, class was a group discussion/ conversation about a reading or topic rather than a lecture. She LOVES student participation and enjoys to hear comments and criticism regarding course materials. Work load is pretty light outside of a few essays (3). HIGHLY recommend taking!

Professor Swanke is one of the best W&R instructors. Her class has 3 papers (that you can revise) and a final portfolio. You have little assignments, typically before each class but not after the weekend. Her class is always so entertaining and a great place to make friends. Definitely recommend!

Vivirito is a fantastic Italian professor. He is hilarious and genuinely cares about his students' success in his class. Homework is for completion, not accuracy, and he gives you the opportunity to correct your mistakes on writing assignments as well. Great guy and professor overall.
Best teacher at ND - take his class.
I took the 6 credit Italian course and he was the best!
Awesome guy who really loves the language and to teach. Very approachable and will always be willing to help.

Patricio is the man. Seriously. Take his class. He is awesome. He's entertaining and really nice. More than willing to help anybody do well in the class if they are willing to put in the work. He makes class fun. Take him if you can.

This teacher is very helpful when it comes to studying.  He is more than happy to answer any questions you have about his class.  A little slow on getting papers back but overall a really dedicated teacher.  He loves his students and is takes great pride in his work.  TAKE THIS CLASS!!!

Taylor's class was an absolute waste of 3 hrs/wk I could have spent studying the diff eqs on which he mumbled. I already had 85% of the material in the class at another uni, and still only received a C because I came out of his classes more confused than before. If you have no other option, find one, or take it another semester w/ someone else.

Good guy but do not at all recommend his class. He's very confusing, makes far too many mistakes, and generally seems a bit lost. Attending his class is typically a waste of time (so either skip or do other homework during). If you end up with him, go to the math help room, pay attention/ask questions during tutorial, and do all the Mobius homework

DO NOT TAKE UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES. If you have no other choice, find one. Taylor's idea of "teaching" is not explaining anything, finding the most complicated problem possible, and then doing it wrong while mumbling to himself. If you're like me and thought you could deal with a bad professor, just know this is a whole new level of bad.

Professor Taylor is very poorly equipped to handle technology (even a microphone) to make himself decipherable during the pandemic. He does not speak well to engage students, and the material for this course is very challenging, but he does not do a great job engaging students or helping outside of class. One of the worst Profs I have ever had.
Bad, bad lecturer. Confusing, and almost hostile when asked to explain his convoluted statements. I don't think he's a bad guy, I just highly recommend he retire.

Do not take Laurence Taylor under any circumstances. Or if you are forced to take his class, do what everyone else does and go to another professor's lecture. You will not learn anything. There's a reason 38% was *passing* on the midterm.
cannot communicate well. He knows the material, but does not put it into terms that students understand. Also does not answer questions well and regularly makes mistakes in lecture without noticing.

His lectures are confusing and unhelpful. He uses a "flipped classroom" which just means you teach yourself and he does examples in class (except he often gets example problems wrong). I don't recommend going to lectures - just watch videos and teach yourself the material.

He sometimes explains things that only make sense if you are really proficient in math. Office hours aren't always helpful. Really watch and take notes on all the videos and do all the homework before class cause otherwise you'll be lost. Study the homework for tests. Remember your grade is very dependent on the individual work you put in.
Professor Taylor is a horrible professor. Do not attend his lectures as you will be more confused than when you started. Attend a different section and pray you don't have him for calc
Half the class didn't bother showing to his section. Find another professor or teach yourself with the book.

if you didn't take this class in high school, good luck. If you did, it is still hard unless you saved your notes because he is awful at explaining a topic if you have trouble with it. If you took it in high school, you're better off not going to class and just reading the online powerpoints since you're a better a teacher for yourself than he is
Drones on. I took his calc class after taking calc in high school, so I passed easily. But if I hadn't I would have failed. My notes from high school were more useful than he was.
ratingTags_Rating: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: Awful lectures. Just reads off a powerpoint for a calc III lecture. Very difficult to follow along in class.
Lectures are terrible, does not explain anything well, and is not helpful at all when you go to his office hours.
He is very theoretical and very hard to understand in basic terms. He does not so examples, making tests and homework difficult.

Carl is a great guy don't get me wrong but every 5 min we took a break to look at photos with old students and their finance textbook or to play the beverage game. Exams are pretty tough and he pulls a few random questions straight from the textbook which even if you read you may not get right. Wish we spent more time doing more examples.

Carl genuinely cares about his students. His lectures are entertaining, but he takes a "short break" every 5 minutes, and it is quite distracting. Could benefit from a few more examples instead. You HAVE to do the reading, and still may miss questions about small details. Exams are challenging but doable, and he is generous with the curve.

Carl exemplifies Mendoza's dedication to growing the good in business. He might have 400 students, but it feels like you know him personally. He also cares about using money for good. Engaging, funny lecturer. Beware that your entire grade is based on 3 exams with minute details from the textbook and you have to self-teach a fair amount.

Carl is amazing. A very personable and funny guy. His class is meant to weed you out, though. Three exams, with questions from the most random textbook sections. It's very annoying. But if you study the basic formulas and know how to do every question he assigns, it makes the course much easier.

Carl is a fantastic man, but his class should definitely be taken seriously. The course is graded entirely based on three increasingly-weighted exams (90%) and participation plus a "case project" (10%). He spends a large part of class time showing you photos of people in past years with his textbook at parties or in other unconventional locations.

LOVE Carl, but his class is a weed-out course. The first exam is all math, and the second exam is mostly concepts. You won't do well on exams if you don't fully understand material so keep up with the readings. The curve mostly helps. Carl makes class so entertaining and is the only reason I wake up at 9:30. Best prof at ND.
ratingTags_Rating: Hilarious--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Carl Ackermann is overhyped, he wastes half of the class playing the beverage game or throwing candy at you. He makes the class seem like a show and does not get straight to the point. I was able to get an A in honors corporate finance, which is harder than fundamentals which I got a B in due to his absurd teaching style and lack of clarity.
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Carl was the best professor I took in my freshman year. His class is very rigorous but everything he assigns is crucial to success in the course. There is tons of support available so take advantage of it and you will be successful.

Carl is amazing! He goes above and beyond to learn every student's name and he's hilarious. 90% of your grade is based on 3 exams - which are math-heavy -  but he gives you the materials and additional help needed to succeed. He has your best interests at heart and I cannot recommend him enough. Just be prepared to study quite a bit before exams.

Fantastic guy. Really cares about the success of his students. Makes lectures fun. Class is hard but not any harder than any other professor teaching the same class. Really good at accessibility out of class. Will go above and beyond to help you if you're struggling. Best professor and class I've taken at ND so far.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I can not say enough about Carl. He is the best professor at ND.

Carl is quite amazing. The class is definitely difficult and time consuming, but Carl does a spectacular job at making the content interesting and engaging students. He is willing to go the extra mile to help people who need it, and he is very invested in every single student. Exams are pretty difficult, but he does a lot to help students prepare.

amazing professor; goes out of his way to help, gets to know students, adds fun elements. However, your grade depends on 3 exams that require a lot math, attention to detail, and conceptual understanding (he does provide practice exams and practice problems that set you up to do really well on the exams if you are willing to put in the effort).

Carl is great as a person, but his class (fundamentals of finance) is incredibly difficult. I enjoyed his as a professor because he was always enthusiastic, but it felt like his lectures only touched the surface of finance. You definitely have to teach yourself the class, and its not an easy subject to learn. Hes great to have convos with though

Prof. Ackermann is a wonderful man but his class was pretty difficult. He does a lot to help his students, but the fact that your entire grade depends upon only 3 exams is tough. If you aren't good at math or conceptual things, make sure you get a tutor. However, I enjoyed Carl's class a lot, even though it was difficult.
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Professor Ackermann makes what is otherwise relatively boring material fun through his lectures. He has a great reputation and genuinely cares about his students. However, the course grade is entirely dependent upon three tests each worth 30% of the course grade.
Carl Ackermann is the man, plain and simple. He is incredibly nice, and his funny shenanigans make the lectures much more interesting. 10/10 would recommend.

Carl genuinely seems to care about his students, but his positive reviews are a bit misleading. He claims not to believe in grades, yet gives 3 exams worth 90% of the grade- all of which are multiple-choice with no partial credit (even though most require multi-step math). And the exams are absurdly difficult for an intro course.
Ackerman seems to really care about his students and wants them to succeed. While the material he teaches may not be the most exciting in the world, he tries to make it exciting.
Incredible professor and human being. He is the man.

Ackermann is very funny, but his jokes sometimes detract from the learning. Ackermann seems to care about his students and tries to be supportive when people don't do great on tests. Ackermann's class was very difficult for me personally because I didn't understand the concept questions well, but I was able to solve the math problems.

Ackerman is known as the man, and the reputation is spot on.  Boring material, but he does his best to make it interesting, so class is generally pretty fun.  Attendance not at all required.  Tests are exactly like the practice tests- no excuse to not know what is coming on his tests.  Could not give a higher recommendation
Best professor I've ever had. Genuinely cares about his students and goes out of his was to help them in any way he can. Keeps class entertaining, very knowledgeable, and overall great teacher.
excellent
Best prof I've ever had! Challenging but very helpful.
BEST TEACHER I'VE EVER HAD. CARL'S THE MAN!
the epitome of what every teacher should aspire to be.
strong to quite strong
Best prof. I ever had.

No Comments
Pizza, gorilla suits, house calls and a Prof. that knows his stuff.  What more could you want?!
Best prof I have ever had
Best teacher I had in my 4 years
No Comments

5 quizzes count for 85% of your grade, and the rest is participation. He is a very good lecturer who explains certain subjects clearly and simply. Class is usually professional but relaxed. Course is not too demanding, but one should pay attention to the readings and the lectures if he or she wants to do well.

He knows everyone's name on the first day of class. He is trying to squeeze his previous semester into a half-semester class, so everyone is on their grind from day one. He assigns a ton of homework. The grade is purely based on how you do on pop quizzes and tests, which are only memorization. You memorize Ted Talks, the textbook, and slides.
ratingTags_Rating: Inspirational--Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: The entirety of this class is about how well you retain information from Ted talks. Professor Stevens is an accomplished business professor who is not afraid to tell you all about it but only spends about a quarter or less of the class speaking. Ted talks are legitimately everything. Memorize all of the slides for a good grade on the final.

Professor Stevens is a really inspirational guy. Take notes on the Ted Talks for homework as there was only one pop quiz in my class, so doing poorly on that would hurt your grade. The exam is all memorization on minute details from Ted Talks, the book, and guest speakers, so study hard (acronyms, quizlet, etc.). He is generous with partial credit.

This is not a good class. Graded by so few things everyone goes into final with a high grade. Final is on ridiculous Ted talks and asks for specific quotes from these assigned videos and from the text book. Final is heinous. Simon Sinek is the main man in this class and he is a tool.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: He is way overhyped and the grading stinks. If you're not in the tip top of the class, you won't do well. I missed one pop quiz question and dropped my grade from an A to a B+. I wrote a very good and creative final exam, and yet still couldn't bring my grade up. It seemed fun at first. Looking back, I would've taken someone else 100%.

The class is ridiculously difficult for no reason. He forces students to watch hours of speeches on youtube then creates exam questions about tiny details from them. He has unreasonable expectations and the content from his class serves no purpose outside of his exams. He should be teachings actual management concepts, rather than cliche lessons.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Stevens is an outstanding professor. Class is TedTalk heavy, and although attendance isn't mandatory you'll see pop quizzes fairly often. Presents management in an engaging way that doesn't necessarily rely on the textbook, but tests are mainly memorization and are pretty brutal. However, he makes a genuine effort to get to know the whole class.
ratingTags_Rating: Inspirational--Graded by few things--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Prof Stevens is one of my favorite professors. He posses confidence and gives insightful, inspirational lectures. In class, students listen to TED talks teaching life lessons. For homework, students provide book and chapter summaries. Additionally, on the last day of class, students participate in a talent show for extra participation points.

Calling Mr. Stevens a professor would be an inaccurate start to this review because calling someone a professor implies that you learned something from them in the first place. While he tries to be friendly, he is beyond condescending and self-congratulatory. His exams are useless memorization tests and he doesn't teach anything, just shows videos.

Stevens was not my favorite professor. While he tries to show that he cares for his students, he also is very narcissistic. His personality rubbed me the wrong way, but I appreciated his effort. The tests are based off of TED Talks and arbitrary aphorisms, and they are all short answer questions (even though he claims they're multiple choice).
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--GROUP PROJECTS

comment_Rating: Chris Stevens' class is honestly a once in a lifetime opportunity. You don't just learn about management, wow that's only the beginning. You learn so much more. He sets an example that I think we all can aspire to achieve.

Without a doubt the best professor I have ever had at Notre Dame. Every day I was looking forward to coming to his class. On the first day of class he memorized our entire class' names. Our class was over a hundred people.

Lectures are a lot of fun and interactive. Homework is difficult. I recommend taking this class, it made me really excited about majoring in physics. Really teaches you problem-solving and thinking creatively. Go to office hours, put in the effort, and you'll do well.

Prof Surman is an excellent Physics professor. I took her for E&M, with no exposure to it in high school. Teaches in a well-structured, logical way that made sense to me. She is relaxed and very approachable. Learned a ton and thoroughly enjoyed her class. Exams are hard, but all material is covered well and you'll score well if you pay attention.
She is an easy grader. For exams, she gives a study guide and gives the answers for the study guide the class before the exam. As an extra credit in the final exam she asked us to do Theology Memes.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: She is amazing. Although there is a bit of homework for every class, Dr. Mahon makes the lectures easy to understand and follow. She also gives study guides for all of her tests, and everything comes from those.

He cares a lot about his students and it shows in his flexibility, availability outside of class, and encouragement of all perspectives. His lectures can be hard to follow (mostly tangents that lack an overarching theme). He is particular with grading essays (but not journal assignments). He says that participation does not matter but it does.

Prof Gasse's class was amazing! There are no tests which is great, just keep up with the daily reading journals (super easy to do well on). He's super accessible outside of class and is always willing to help/talk about any concerns. He addresses any questions that anyone has and is super accepting to people of all backgrounds. HIGHLY RECOMMEND!

Prof Noemi was great! She is a super fun and personable professor who genuinely cares about her students. She gives feedback on essays before you submit them and you will edit your lowest scoring essay at the end of the course (your grade will change). Lectures are not the best and she often runs out of time to go through examples, however, I recommend attending her office hours and the math help hours with a Grad student. Content is similar to AP AB Calc. Homework is manageable and there are practice tests for each exam. Definitely use online videos for extra help.
She is honestly amazing. Her lectures are extremely helpful and she does an amazing job at breaking down points as well as making it interesting. It is clear that she loves her job! :)

Never met the professor once. The class was taught by a TA that didn't really know what he was doing. The lessons were all over the place and poorly explained. Learned most of the class on Khan Academy rather than from the class itself. They make assumptions that everyone took Calc 1 in High School so they skip/brush over a lot of topics.

I absolutely love her! One of the best math teachers I've ever had. She explains the concepts very well and provides so many resources for extra help outside of class. On top of that she is hilarious and somehow makes calc class not the most boring thing ever. I would definitely recommend!

Does not explain lessons well, homework due at 2 am, does not answer questions efficiently, 0/10 would not recommend, told a student when they dropped the class "I wouldn't even take this class if I were a student. Don't even bother retaking the class. You're better off taking stats". Overall, I very much dislike this class.

Professor Pilkington is an Amazing person, but a bad professor. Descriptions of topics are not clear at all and will leave you confused. Review for exams in this class is old and irrelevant and won't help you on exam. Moves very fast and gets distracted. Most TA's for this class are even confused when trying to receive help. Would never recommend.

Decent professor. Mandatory attendance and participation is required. Don't necessarily need to do readings but helps for participation. A lot of the class and grading seem kinda subjective and based on his personal opinions. If you answer the questions in the specific ways he wants, you'll do fine. Sometimes the assignments are not super clear.

He assigns a lot of reading for the class, but not from a textbook. He has certain criteria that he wants for each assignment that feels subjective. If you know what he wants, you will do a great job.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: Not much inspirational thing, just about sharing his past experiences and making unnecessary implicit judgments about some countries that he doesn't like. He is a tough grader overall. Rubrics are unclear, grades relying simply on his personal judgment.

Prof. Pannekoek's int. management class was interesting and relatively easy. The tests are weighed pretty heavily, so you need to read the textbook and use the lecture material to do well. Attendance isn't mandatory, but it benefits you to show up and participate. Overall, it was a pretty easy class as long as you pay attention.
VERY HARD CLASS. DO NOT TAKE IT!!!! YOU HAVE TO MEMORIZE 10 SLIDES ABOUT AN EXAM AND SHE ASKS THE MOST SPECIFIC QUESTIONS EVER.
Way too heavy with her tests. Brush through content and makes us take exam.

she is just an awful teacher. i somewhat feel bad writing this review because she is not a bad person, but my goodness she is a horrible teacher. she thinks she is connecting with the class when 8 people have passed out during lectures about why it is important to use soap. she is also not as easy as she likes to think, this is just a rough class
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Like literally all you have to do is review the notes and be semi conscious in class and you'll do well. The only people who don't do well are people who don't know how college courses work.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Used to be if you didnt have something nice to say dont say anything… I have nothing nice to say and I will say it…. she STINKS

just awful. i dont know why notre dame thinks she is capable of teaching science because she goes up in the front of the room and rambles on about hand washing techniques. this was the class I was looking forward to most and I couldn't even make it through class without falling asleep. she is just a brutal teacher to be honest
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Horrible. the worst teacher and worst attitude. she seems to really dislike teaching, her students and doing anything remotely helpful for her class
literally the worst class and professor ever. ruins a cool topic and is just a really mean person
AWFUL!!!!! THE WORST AND MEANEST PROFESSOR IVE HAD IN 4 YEARS. JUST A REALLY MEAN PERSON WHO ENJOYED SEEING STUDENTS STRUGGLE

I honestly can't believe anyone didn't enjoy Professor Vaughan! It was alot of fun learning all the diseases caused by different microbes and we watched like 4 docu style movies. As long as you study like actual ND student, you should be fine. Ngl, her lab was my favorite one I have ever taken, never stayed more than an hour.

I am not quite sure why there are so many negative reviews because she is amazing. I found the material to be very interesting, but also not complex at all. I also really enjoyed the videos. Sometimes the class is a little boring, but I found it to be a good way to learn about biology. She also gives some slack with grading.

Well, if Professor Vaughan teaches it!!! She is truly awful. One of the most self-centered, my road or the high road people Ive ever met. Do yourself a favor and avoid her at all costs.

comment_Rating: scale is not low enough for me because she deserves negative ratings.
avoid. here is your warning. tests are nothing like she says in class and really doesn't care about helping you learn.

Very easy A if you put in some effort. You just need to memorize the slides bc that's the entire test. you can find video answers on quizlet which is cool. you don't have to go to class, but it will make the class easier. your grade is 4 exams and your lowest score is 1/2 the weight
just a truly awful professor. if i could go back and take a different class with a more caring and interesting professor I would.
Pretty easy class but terrible professor.
awful teacher. really poor at lecturing and tests are nothing like class. Just makes a really interesting topic very unenjoyable
terrible. arrogant and bad at teaching. avoid and thank me later.

terrible professor. she acts like the class is super easy and if you show up you will do well. Nope. Doesn't explain anything and the exams are nothing like the textbook or class. Do not take if you want an A, really overrated professor.

This woman is goated. The class has no HW, only four tests that are all multiple choice with no trickery--she tells you what you need to know. Half the class is basic note-taking and the other is videos. This woman is legendary. I took her in 2018 and even then we were watching Contagion and she was calling out a pandemic. Goated

Microbes and Man is a great class.. The topics are interesting and she helps you understand while knowing that many who take this class don't want to be science majors. The tests aren't hard and she always does review and gives hints before them so listen to those. She also lectures for 50 mins and shows videos for the remaining 25 which is nice.

Prof Bennet made the subject of stats much more interesting by being a relatable and cool professor. She was good at explaining the concepts, but the class could have benefitted from more examples. She is open to questions during lecture and cares about her students. Class is not impossible if you pay attention and work hard on the homework.

Do not take her for Stats. Confusing lectures that rarely helped with homework sets or tests, I felt like I learned most of the class material outside of class. The exams are very difficult, study hard or you will do poorly.

Professor Bennett is super sweet and approachable, and genuinely cares about her students. Homework load isn't bad and exams are fair. Classes are sometimes a little rushed and can be confusing, but you can get the help you need from her or the TAs. Tutorial is like a third class (not revision of material). Data project at the end is super easy!

Professor Bennett is great. Her lectures are entertaining, and as a non-econ major, I found her class to be highly informative. The problem sets were generally not too hard, and the writing assignments were easy. While the exams were difficult, her grading system allows you to still do well even if you mess up on a midterm. Definitely recommend.

Professor Bennett is great for principles of microeconomics! Her lectures were pretty entertaining, always filled with lots of examples, and the homework load was pretty light. The tests are hard, but there are plenty of practice questions and opportunities to succeed in the class. Highly recommend!

She tries to be a good professor but falls behind in so many aspects. Tough grader; does not let you ask her questions during exams but rather you must write what you were confused on and debate with her; not accessible at all, she only hosts office hrs once a week; HER ANSWER KEYS, EXAMS, AND HOMEWORKS ALL HAVE TYPOS, EVERY SINGLE TIME

Easily the best principles of micro professor from what I've heard about the others. Her class is far easier than other professors and although she doesn't really care about meeting the needs of students her lectures are great.

She does expect a lot out of incoming freshmen, but if you spend the time to actually study you'll do perfectly fine. I went into the final with a B- and came out with an A due to her lenient final grade scaling as well. She also is quite entertaining. My only issue is that she does not post her slideshow/lectures online so class is required.

Professor Bennett was a great principles of micro professor. She communicated things in a very understandable way, helping make sense of complicated topics. Midterms were more conceptual than the problem sets and practice midterms, so make sure you have a thorough understanding. Overall, if you are engaged and take good notes, you will get an A.

This is for ECON 30340 which is Stats for Economics. I heard her principles class is really good, but I only had her for stats and it was awful. This was her first time teaching stats, so maybe that's a contributing factor. She just would constantly mess up the material and examples, confusing everyone in class. Her office hours are also unhelpful.

Prof Bennett's intro classes are probably the easiest in the department. She grades pretty easily and really only one of the mid terms matters towards your final grade. Just study for all exams and you'll be fine

She is so bad. Never take her if you love your life. She will never be satisfied. If you expect an A, you are going to get a B. Worst grader and lecturer. Messes up her own problems. Gets them off of chegg. Even if you chegg the HW, you will never get full marks. THIS IS FOR THE STATISTICS FOR ECONOMICS CLASS.

I loved having Professor Bennett as she made the class very enjoyable. I also really enjoyed our writing assignments because she chose relevant subject matter and made the assignment relate to current events.

Prof Bennett is a good professor. Class is heavily reliant on PollEverywhere questions and can be somewhat painfully slow paced at times. Exams are of moderate difficulty. You'll be fine if you study and attend each lecture. She includes assignments designed to provoke interest in the subject matter, which I liked.

Professor Blaschko made lectures engaging and interesting. Although TA's can be harsh graders, they are always open to help outside of class. The coursework for this class was relatively light and all assessments were open notes so be sure to take notes on the homework readings.

Professor Blaschko is both hilarious and gives really good lectures. The content for the class is very well structured and easily broken down on the website. Because quizzes and assignments are open-note, if you take good notes on the readings, you will do well. I highly recommend GGL with Professor Blaschko for a 1st Philosophy at ND.

Extremely engaging, I learned a ton about philosophy and it changed my outlook on life. Easier than other philosophy classes but still has challenging assignments. A few papers and quizzes, all graded by TAs. The TAs grade fairly and give good feedback. They are accessible for office hours too.

Good lectures- he includes personal examples and is entertaining. But the lectures were exactly the same as the daily readings, which made them repetitive. Daily readings, quizzes, and application article annotations become busywork. The final apology paper is long but interesting. TAs can be hard graders. Dialogue meetings are fun though!
Good professor with fun lectures- grades are very dependent on your TA though.  Attendance was not mandatory and the homework was pretty light most of the time.
Professor Blaschko is very smart and teaches the class very well. However, he is very hard to reach out of class and your only contact will be your TA who also does all of your grading.

Professor Blaschko is very interesting and engaging during lecture. There are quizzes before every class that require a lot of reading and he doesn't go over the answers during class. However, he truly cares about his students and is accessible outside of class if you need him, but the TA's do all of the grading.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Good class and professor to take for intro philosophy. Blashko makes the lectures interesting and easy to understand. Lots of busy work which can get annoying. The class is harder than it needs to be but overall not terribly difficult. TAs grade the apology pretty strictly.

Professor Blaschko is passionate about what he teaches and I could tell that he wants his students to have a good understanding of the material he presents in class. You will receive an A in this class if you show up, do your work, and have a positive mindset. If you are thinking about taking GGL as your first philosophy requirement, do it!!

The class is a pretty straightforward intro to philosophy that doesn't dive too deeply into any individual topic. Daily reading quizzes are tough but not weighted heavily. Most important grades are done by TAs, who are pretty tough/aggravating graders. You need a 95 for an A but an A- is pretty easily achievable.

Great lecturer but the class is tougher than you think. Your grade is pretty much dictated by your TA. The reading quizzes are actually quite difficult but don't make up too much of your grade. Reading/homework isn't too bad, just busy work. Your apology makes up a lot of your grade so work hard on it and go to your TA, they are generally helpful.
The apology draft is graded with as much scrutiny as if it were the final paper. My TA was nice but was a tough grader.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: God and the Good Life is the perfect introductory philosophy class, and Professor Blaschko makes his lectures very engaging. There is work before every class but it doesn't take more than 30 minutes if you pay attention.

Prof. Blaschko really wants you to learn about philosophy in a relatable way. It's just that the class itself is a decent amount of work. I find his lectures to be fascinating. Also heads up: the TAs do all of the gradings, but I'd still recommend office hours with him.

While I think that Professor Blaschko is a great professor, I think that GGL has become a class of busy work. Whether it be through Perusall or the reading quizzes before every class, I think the work is excessive and somewhat pointless. I often took nothing away from the lectures because the readings and quizzes before class covered everything.

Deceptive teacher. Seems to care about you a lot but lets the TAs decide your grade. If you end up with an unreasonable TA, oh well, he DOES NOT CARE because he needs some students to have poorer grades in order for the course to seem like it's difficult. Do not be fooled by his seemingly optimistic character. If you want an A, it's a toss up.

The weekly quiz answers could be found in the practice quizzes. Many of my peers complained about getting terrible grades on the written work because some of the TAs are tough graders. I had an 95 in the class before my 82% on the final tanked my grade to a B+. The TAs were sometimes such hard graders.
Amazing lecturer and great personality. For his class it is easy to receive a good grade if you do your work on a regular basis, and this takes a total of 30 minutes a week.
One of the best professors I had this semester. 10/10

Professor Branco is very invested in the classes she teaches. Very knowledge and utilizes unique teaching strategies to get information across to students. However, questions on tests can be difficult as she will only teach the basics of a topic, but ask very applied questions on the test. If you dedicate enough time to the class you'll be fine.

Dr. Branco is an engaging lecturer, and she is really intentional about reviewing previous material at the start of each class. Test grades are a combination of your individual score and your group score (re-taking the same exam with a group), which was odd at first but actually pretty helpful. Weekly homework is graded on effort, not accuracy.

Dr. Branco is one of the most amazing professors I have ever had. She makes sure all of the lectures have purpose, does many practice problems in class, and makes lectures interesting. She is super reasonable with amount of work and grading. She also does fun review activities and is amazing at explaining hard topics.
Avoid at all costs.

Bad. Avoid at all costs. Does not give you an explanation or feedback but just assigns any grade he pleases. No rubric for assignments and not helpful when you ask questions. He doesn't teach, he just talks at you and makes the subject painful.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Rush is a notoriously tough grader. Luckily I took this course (Socialist philosophy) during the pandemic, so I took the passing grade. Rush is also very condescending and not very interested in student input. He loves to hear himself talk. Sometimes hundreds of pages of reading each night. Made socialism boring, somehow.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Very interesting class. Wonderful lecturer. I never quite knew how I was doing in the class. Reading responses were required for homework before every class. No exams, just essays. One 15 minute presentation for each student to teach a chapter of the book we read in class.

Really hard class. Every class is discussion-based. Readings are the most intellectually challenging texts I've ever read for a liberal arts class. It is very niche and she knows what she is talking about. Only take her class if you know you like the subject, not to satisfy a general credit.

Mnev presented all the content in Honors Calculus 3 thoroughly and clearly, closely following our textbook. We were allowed to work on the homework in small groups, which makes it significantly easier. He usually just gives lectures (which seems effective for math), and makes sure to occasionally ask if there are any questions.

The material for linear algebra is incredibly difficult, so unfortunately it looks bad on Mnev. But really, I think he's a fine teacher. I'd recommend sitting closer to the front to get the most from class. Unexceptional teacher but he goes through all the material and does a decent job of explaining and posting his notes online.

If you take TBS as a MSA student you will question every ounce of education till this point. This professor talks in circles about stuff you did not learn. I hope you aren't one of his victims because he will call on you all day everyday. He will come close to you start a sentence, fall asleep, then revive and expect an answer.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Ilona has a lot of passion for accounting. She is not the best at explaining accounting topics. She is good at being open to office hours and puts in the effort to make her class the best. This year was her first year teaching, so she has a lot of room to improve in the coming years.

Very nice professor. Truly cares about the well-being of her students and tries her best to be accessible outside of the classroom. She talks pretty fast during lectures but can be humorous most times. You'll deal with case study group projects, three exams (increases in difficulty), and homework that isn't graded but extremely helpful for exams!
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Initially hard, gets better, good person, ok teacher

She is amazing. 
100% recommend taking foundations with her. She is super nice and energetic, which makes all lectures fun. Her smile is always present and she will go through anything you don't understand multiple times. She truly wants the best for her students and she is very accessible. HW is optional but DO THEM, the exams come from those.

The class was really challenging for me but also interesting. Dan is awesome and somehow always available outside of class. So while it's super hard he gives lots of opportunities to get extra help. The problem sets took me forever every week though. Go to his office hours, they were so helpful for the homework

Definition of a no-nonsense professor. Gets straight to the point every class and you can tell she's really good at what she does. Some might even find her intimidating. That being said, she teaches very clearly and is great at answering questions so you should be able to get a good grade

Loved Professor D! Her personality outside of class was A1. She is very caring of her students but can be a bit passive-aggressive sometimes. She gives out a lot of homework that is very time-consuming, the exams progress in difficulty but she has old exams to help you study! Her lectures can be engaging & interesting, but at the same time dull. :)

Fun teacher, but posted a lot of meaningless assignments during the week. Classes were lecture heavy and even though it was a big class, she knows if you skipped. Each of her exams has practice ones online that mirror the real one, so easy to prep for. The final was quite terrible though and tanked my high A to a B, so prepare extra for final.

She wants to know your name (which I didn't really like) but it shows she cares. Class is easy if you just take the practice exams on her website. They're the exact same as the ones you take in class. Three exams, homework due every Sunday. Econ is easy if you make it easy.

I was a fan overall and walked away with a high A, but I could definitely see how a few small mistakes could tank your grade in one of her classes. So make sure to be super detail-oriented and follow any rubrics for projects closely or she will take considerable points off. The same goes for tests. She sometimes asks very hyperspecific questions.

Prof. Dziadula is a wonderful professor. I took her for Macro, but I have heard she is great for micro as well. Very strict, but explains topics well and gives ample resources to prepare for exams. I really enjoyed her class and teaching style, especially compared to other Econ professors I have had.

LOVE Prof. D! Had her for principles of macro. Great lecturer and has a clear set of standards for students. Counts attendance randomly a handful of times throughout the semester. She's always there to answer questions and is one of the econ dept. advisors so definitely enjoys getting to know more about the students.

Absolutely awful. By far my least favorite teacher ever. Doesn't care about her students. Isn't just not polite but is downright rude to her students. Gives good lectures, but that is the only good thing about her. Highly recommend not having anything to do with her. Will never take her again.

AMAZING PROF who cares so much about her students (makes an effort to learn everyones name). Decent amount of HW and quizzes but overall manageable (use textbook for help). Practice tests are helpful for the exams which are generally easy. Attend class or you'll fall behind!

*always remember to put the dollar sign on tests and problem sets :)
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Dziadula is a wonderful professor. You be successful in this course if you go to class, take notes, and ask questions. Her lectures are simply excellent, and her expectations are clear. I would definitely take her again, and I highly recommend for anyone looking to take Principles of Macroeconomics.

Dr. Dziadula is the best professor I have had at the University of Notre Dame. She clearly cares about all of her students by learning their names and offers tons of resources to succeed. Her lectures are interactive and she makes sure to tie in lots of relevant information. 10/10 recommend Eva Dziadula for Micro.

Great professor with excellent lectures. Relatively easy tests. Available outside of class for extra help. Very friendly but strict with rules/syllabus. Just show up, take notes, ask questions, and participate, and you will get a good grade.

Biggest thing, do not mess up submission times, page order or literally anything because she is very very strict about no exceptions to anyone no matter the circumstance. Very funny in class though and lectures are hugely important and helpful to understanding the material so go to class.

Professor D is my favorite. She is an absolute girlboss and is to the point. Pay attention in class, ask questions, go to office hours, do the practice tests and it will be fine. Doing the practice tests over until you get the problems all right is a good strategy. She is a really cool professor and I absolutely love her.
Had her for principles of micro. if you attend class and take notes, you will pass. it's as simple as that.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Professor D's made lectures interesting, even at 8am. The tests are rather easy as she takes problems right from the practice tests. Do the practice tests and you'll be golden for exams. Minimal homework compared to other profs. Beware of final, it is cumulative and she will pull from even the smallest of topics. Respectable professor overall.

Every other micro professor except Dziadula will let you take a cheat sheet into the midterms and final exam. She'll give the least amount of homework, shortest problem sets, no papers or projects, and least midterms. You will not have a ton of work. But it's a tough class and not being able to have a cheat sheet like other students will break you.

Prof D is organized, fair, efficient, and caring. She won't waste your time inside or outside class, and puts a lot of effort into getting to know her students. The class does require a bit of effort, but if you attend class and follow Prof D's HW instructions and exam prep recommendations, you'll learn a lot and will earn a good grade.

Microecon. Very little homework... only had problem sets due the class before each exam. Quite a bit of extra credit. She goes around the class quizzing you but it's easy stuff. I never read the textbook (only learned from her lectures), and I got an A. By far one of the easiest classes I ever took.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: When I think back about great profs I've had at ND, she'll be at the top of the list. Take her class. It's not a breeze, but having her as a prof is worth it. Funny, intelligent, and cares about you as a student. Great teacher. Will be in ND teaching Hall of Fame when it's all said and done.
she gives out clear guidelines and shes a good teacher. class can be hard to keep up so you have to pay attention. but overall good experience and engaged me with econ.
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Clear grading criteria--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Good lecturer; class not very difficult. Put in the work.

If you go to class you will do fine. She is very helpful and tries to help everyone's grades the best she can. She drops multiple online quiz scores. She also has two possible grade calculations and gives you the better grade at the end of the semester. She has no empathy for those who don't come to class, though, and she does notice.

As much fun as "Easy A" classes are, sometimes you have to take the punch and work your butt off. You have to read the textbook and you have to take good notes. Attendance is not graded, but you definitely want to show up. If you work hard, ask questions, and do the homework/readings, you'll do great and have a great recommendation by the end.

Make sure you go to class. Exams are on a difficult side and could be a bit overwhelming for a bunch of first-years who have no idea what college is about. No PPT slides or anything, so the only things you can rely on are your notes, and her lectures tend to be a bit boring. So if you don't go to class or start daydreaming, welp good luck
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: She is very clear, talks quickly, and discusses the details of the topic very thoroughly. She is funny and caring but isn't afraid to put her foot down if she knows you don't come to class. Tests are relatively easy and if you fail one of the two midterms, that midterm will only count as 5% of your grade and more weight will be on the final.
Love Dziadula- her lectures are very entertaining and she is always willing to answer questions

One of my best profs this semester. Clear, concise, easy to understand. Cares about you  if your alarm doesn't go off for an 8am exam and you talk to her afterward, she will give you extra time. As long as you pay attention in class and take notes, you will be fine. Have not used my textbook (except for assignments) and still have an A.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: Really good teacher. Class is tough but she is really understanding and even more helpful. If you bomb a test the grading criteria is set up to discount the bad grades and upgrade the good grades.

I don't know why the other reviews on here are so negative. I'm a science major so Econ has never been my strong suit, but as long as you pay attention in class and take accurate notes, you'll do just fine. She's the tough love type, but if you participate in class or see her at office hours, she's really nice and will make sure to help you.
She ad libs her lectures and strays from the course outline sometimes.  The textbook is much clearer.
moves to fast, not very clear, hard tests

In the realm of BPS, I would recommend Balko for sure. The course isn't fun if you end up in a bad group but given the stressful nature of the course, I would say Balko is your best bet. He's about as understanding as you can get when it comes to group issues / the many difficulties that arise when working with the same 4 people all semester.

As far as Business Problem-Solving professors go, Balko is a great choice. While most of your grade depends on group projects, you can do just fine in the class by making sure your individual project is well-created. Show up to class, participate, and be a good team member.

I really liked Balko as a professor. He's a little quirky, but it is clear he cares about his students. His Business Problem Solving class had 4 group projects, where the groups were assigned based on Myers Briggs types, a few short reflection essays, and a semester long project. The class gave me good experience, but I really hated the projects.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Group projects--So many papers

comment_Rating: While I got an A in the course, I received zero feedback as to why, and the entire grade was based on a single paper. So do that paper well I guess. There was a lot of assigned reading but it didn't really have much incentive without any tie to a grade, and to me it was quite repetitive and pushed a lot of the same recurring themes over and over.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Respected--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Prof. Omar truly cares about each of his students and is so passionate about peace studies. He made the 15 page paper very manageable by having a 5 page draft due in March then a 12 page draft in April. This was super helpful because we got his feedback to incorporate into the final paper. He gives great lectures and assigns interesting readings
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Caring--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I took Pricing Analytics with him, and really felt that I learned a lot. You have to submit a report every week based on a case study which are time consuming, but the professor is super helpful and can be easily reached by email or office hours. Heavy workload, but as long as you get everything done, you will likely get an A in the course.

Review the provided videos before class and you'll be fine. The main value of going to class is working through in-class exercises with him. This was his first semester so he'll probably be better for future classes. Also you'll be lost the whole course if you don't get the first two chapters so lock in early.

Homework is optional and not graded. Lectures are very boring as well. Not a lot of energy or participation in class. Two exams and one final. They are somewhat easy and the Mendoza curve usually helps in this class. There are better accounting professors at ND in my opinion, but not a terrible one to have either.
Very nice guy who cares about his students. Lectures are straight to the point which can be dry, but he is effective at teaching. Grade is mostly based on the exams but there are group projects, too.

Professor Agrelius is inredible at listening to student feedback and making sure he is constantly adjusting his class to make it the best experience. He added on a lot of extra credit opportunities on the exams towards the end of the year. As a younger professor, I also feel like he is relatable in a way that some other teachers migt not be.

Quantitative reasoning course. I really struggled in the class because any type of coding is really not my things. exams apply what you've learned in the class to a real world solution - felt like I could not adequately prepare for them (prac exams not like exams). The project is super important! She's available outside of class which saved me.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Test heavy--Accessible outside class

Professor Wietstock does not care about his students and created a very stressful environment in lab. Students who were even a minute late were given a zero even if they were taking another exam. He was not helpful or supportive and the TA's did all the grading, which was often graded very hard.

Prof Wietstock essentially didn't do anything in lab so hope you have a good TA. Very strict on attendance. Labs (that he wrote and makes us pay for) make no sense and writeups are tedious. Prelab quizzes are hard but not worth many points. He is fairly pleasant outside lab but did deny my friend disability accommodations which I think is illegal.

Professor is not very involved in the lab. Definitely get to know your TA and ask him any questions you have. Lab and content are not difficult, although the class is out of sync with the lecture. Quiz questions are very specific, so make sure to review the material.

Wietstock is the worst. I'm actually surprised the University keeps him around. Shows no kindness or sympathy - don't even bother emailing him with any questions; he won't respond. Overall chem lab sucks but to be fair it's a pretty easy A if you do the work.

Steve Wietstock does not care about his students or their grades. He sat in the back of my class every day and ate fast food while we were in the lab. The pre-lab quizzes were difficult and it was rare to get a 5/5. The work itself was not too bad, there were just times when the lab itself would take longer than the allotted class time (3 hours).
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: he has you do long division by hand because that is for some reason indicative of your knowledge of chemistry.
Odious, odious man. Goes out of his way to make the class a pain for students.

This man is terrible at his job. He does absolutely nothing. If you have a bad TA, good luck. His pre-lab lectures will put you to sleep. You have to be to class on time because there's quizzes at the beginning of each class. I have seen him  give zeros to students who are late with valid excuses. He shows no mercy.
This man is not good at his job.

Arrive early to lab because he gives quizzes at the beginning of every class that require a code to get in...he will not give you the code if you come in late. Instead, he will give you a zero. He is not very compassionate and he only ever sits in his chair. The TA's most (all) of the work, so hopefully you get a good TA.

This professor does not care about his class. The curriculum he teaches is poor and unrelated to the chemistry lessons.  his own TAs rant about him to the students because of how unreasonable he is.  This man does not understand empathy, one of my friends got the flu and had to go to the emergency room, and asked for an extension but was denied.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating:
Arrive early to lab! Prof. Wietstock has clear rules, and he's strict about some things, but it's all of necessity. He's a nice guy that has a lot of responsibility placed on him by the university so he's strict about some stuff: don't forget your lab notebook, or your lab equipment!

TAs are your friends!! Get to know them, and how they grade!
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: What an absolutely terrible professor to have lab with. To start off, he writes the book that you will use in this lab, so he is getting a percentage of the ~$15 it costs for every student. He is NOT a nice person when it comes to answering emails and the system he has to turn in papers is incredibly confusing+unforgiving. Avoid at all costs.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating: The most universally dreaded class in the College of Science. Professor disdainful at students, entirely unresponsive, unnecessary and long lecture/prelab. Equipment never works, or enough of it. Hope that you don't get sick over a lab, or injure yourself trying to go regardless. Lab is out of sync with lecture, so it's on content you don't know.

I did not have a bad experience with him but I had a friend who was in the emergency room and missed a lab - Wietstock was not very forgiving in giving her a chance to make it up. Your grade for each post-lab is dependent on the TA grading it. Wietstock doesn't really do anything in the class. The post-labs are often pretty confusing.

Some people dislike Prof. W's teaching style because he takes time explaining what to pay attention to. However, he would give hints during his explanations, so PAY ATTENTION. He talks slowly enough for everyone to understand (v helpful), and if you try, he notices and is more likely to respond to you outside of class. Just keep asking questions!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Overall, this course was not too bad. The one thing that makes the course difficult is the amount of work associated with the post labs. Make sure that you record all of the numbers and statistics you need before leaving the lab and make sure to not procrastinate the post lab (they are worth a large portion of your grade and take considerable time)
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment_Rating: He has the worst attitude but in all honesty the labs aren't difficult if you just follow instructions. If you need help just ask one of the TA's; asking Wietstock will get you nowhere
This lab makes me so miserable every week and Professor Wietstock isn't helpful.

Wietstock is as understanding as a gas station, and is as available outside of class as a Target after 11pm. Be prepared to read cranky, snarky emails on a weekly basis. Don't even think about sending him emails with questions. That's the equivalent of throwing your socks into a black holes. His TAs will be the only help you would ever receive.

He is very dismissive and rude. He either won't respond to emails or will yell at you for bothering him without answering your question. During our first day of lab, he literally told us he didn't want us to ask him any questions or send him any emails regarding anything in the class.

'Nuff said about his teaching style. It's all already been said. So long as you follow the instructions (do your labs online so people can read them, trust me) and make sure to double check your lab work with someone else, the course is honestly pretty easy. I got a 98 by just doing the work assigned to me.

comment_Rating: Wietstock has the personality of a damp paper towel. Don't expect to get any help from him. If you read the e-book and utilize the help of your TAs, lab shouldn't be too bad. Just avoid Wietstock and let the TAs teach you.
Does not do anything. Just sits there and reads off a slide. Also, he never wants to answer questions

During the lab itself, I am not sure what Wietstock does. He lectures a little in the beginning of class and then is essentially done and the TAs take over. Lab is chaos. He is snarky and impolite for no reason. I honestly think he just enjoys deducting points.

Gives unclear instructions, changes the structure of assignments midway through the semester, does very little for the class, sends snarky and sometimes cryptic emails, takes himself too seriously, etc. The TA's tend to be more competent than him.
